UNIQUE-ID - Type-I-FAS
TYPES - Proteins
COMMON-NAME - a type I fatty acid synthase
COMMENT - Type I fatty acid synthases are large multifunctional proteins found in eukaryotic organisms whose main function is to catalyze the synthesis of |FRAME: PALMITATE| and other long-chain saturated fatty acids from |FRAME: ACETYL-COA| and |FRAME: MALONYL-COA|, in the presence of NADPH.
/
/In addition to an acyl-carrier-protein domain, the enzyme contains domains that catalyze 7 different
/catalytic activities, which are:
/
/(1) |FRAME: ACP-S-ACETYLTRANSFER-RXN "EC 2.3.1.38, [acyl-carrier-protein] <i>S</i>-acetyltransferase"|
/
/(2) |FRAME: MALONYL-COA-ACP-TRANSACYL-RXN "EC 2.3.1.39, [acyl-carrier-protein] <i>S</i>-malonyltransferase"|
/
/(3) |FRAME: 2.3.1.41-RXN "EC 2.3.1.41, 3-oxoacyl-[acyl-carrier-protein] synthase"|
/
/(4) |FRAME: 3-OXOACYL-ACP-REDUCT-RXN "EC 1.1.1.100, 3-oxoacyl-[acyl-carrier-protein] reductase"|
/
/(5) |FRAME: 4.2.1.61-RXN "EC 4.2.1.59, 3-hydroxyacyl-[acyl-carrier-protein] dehydratase"|
/
/(6) |FRAME: ENOYL-ACP-REDUCT-NADPH-RXN "EC 1.3.1.10, enoyl-[acyl-carrier-protein] reductase"|
/
/(7) |FRAME: 3.1.2.14-RXN "EC 3.1.2.14 , acyl-[acyl-carrier-protein] hydrolase"|
/
/Since the substrates do not leave the enzyme during the process, but instead are handed from one functional domain to the next, the full process received its own EC numbers. The mammalian enzyme is classified as |FRAME: EC-2.3.1.85|, while the enzyme from yeast has been classified as |FRAME: EC-2.3.1.86|.
/
/The overall reaction is described as:
/
/|FRAME: FATTY-ACID-SYNTHASE-RXN|
//
