UNIQUE-ID - Cofactors
TYPES - Compounds
COMMON-NAME - a cofactor
COMMENT - A cofactor is a non-protein chemical compound that is required by an enzyme for catalysis of a chemical reaction. Cofactors associate with inactive <i>apo</i>-enzymes, resulting in formation of active <i>holo</i>-enzymes.
/Unlike cosubstrates, the cofactors are restored to their original state at the end of the catalytic cycle and are thus not included in the reaction equation.
/
/Cofactors can be inorganic ions (e.g. Ca<sup>2+</sup>), inorganic molecules (e.g. |FRAME: FeS-Centers|) or organic molecules (e.g. |FRAME: PYRIDOXAL_PHOSPHATE|). Some compounds may act as cofactors for a particular enzyme and a cosubstrate for a different enzyme, depending on whether they are restored to their active state at the end of the reaction. 
/Cofactors that are tightly bound to an enzyme have often been referred to as prosthetic groups. It should be noted that the degree of tightness required for this definition has not been defined, and that the same cofactor may bind differently to different enzymes, making this term imprecise. Thus, it is recommended not to use it. Organic cofactors that are loosely bound to the enzyme have been often referred to as coenzymes. However, that term is also imprecise, and it is recommended not to use it either.
//
