UNIQUE-ID - Peroxiredoxins
TYPES - Proteins
COMMON-NAME - a peroxiredoxin
COMMENT - |FRAME: Peroxiredoxins Peroxiredoxins| are a ubiquitous family of antioxidant enzymes that have been identified in eubacteria, archaea, yeast, algae, higher plants, and animals |CITS: [12714747]|. All peroxiredoxins share the same basic catalytic mechanism, in which an activated cysteine (the peroxidative cysteine or Cp) is oxidized to a sulfenic acid by the peroxide substrate. They have a rather low activity, but possess a broad substrate specificity. Substrates for peroxiredoxins include |FRAME: HYDROGEN-PEROXIDE "hydrogen peroxides"|, |FRAME: Alkyl-Hydro-Peroxides "alkyl hydroperoxides"|, and |FRAME: CPD0-1395 peroxynitrites|.
/
/Depending on the specific peroxiredoxin enzyme, reductive regeneration of the oxidized catalytic thiol depends on |FRAME: GLUTATHIONE|, |FRAME: Thioredoxin thioredoxin|, |FRAME: Glutaredoxins glutaredoxin|, cyclophilin, and/or tryparedoxin |CITS: [16284092]|.
/
/The first peroxiredoxin was identified in |FRAME: TAX-4932| in 1987 and named thiol-specific antioxidant (TSA), because it was thought to remove reactive sulfur species rather than reactive oxygen species |CITS: [2895105]|. The correct functional assignment was made after the discovery of AhpC (alkyl hydroperoxide reductase) in |FRAME: TAX-90371| |CITS: [2191951]|.
/
/All peroxiredoxins contain an L-cysteine residue that attacks the substrate (Cp) and becomes hydroxylated during the catalytic cycle. There are two classification systems for the peroxiredoxins, one based on the mechanism for the reduction of the hydroxylated Cp residue, and the other based on sequence analysis.
/
/According to the first classification system, the enzymes can categorized into three classes based on the location or absence of a second L-cysteine residue (C<sub>R</sub>) that is involved in restoring Cp to its reduced state. The three classes are:
/
/1. The |FRAME: 2-Cys-Peroxiredoxins "2-Cys-peroxiredoxins"| (also called typical 2-Cys-peroxiredoxins) are homodimeric and contain two conserved (Cp and C<sub>R</sub>) cysteine residues per subunit. The Cp&ndash;SOH that is formed during the catalytic cycle reacts with the C<sub>R</sub> of the other subunit to form an intersubunit disulfide.
/
/2. |FRAME: Type-II-Peroxiredoxins "Atypical 2-Cys peroxiredoxins"| are monomeric, and the Cp&ndash;SOH that is formed during the catalytic cycle reacts with the C<sub>R</sub> of the same subunit, forming an intrasubunit disulfide. Members of this class can use thioredoxin and/or glutaredoxin as the reductant |CITS: [12913160]|. A subtype is the |FRAME: Q-Type-Peroxiredoxins "Q-type peroxiredoxins"|, which are homologs of the |FRAME: EG10108| (bacterioferritin co-migrating protein) of |FRAME: TAX-562| |CITS: [10998352]|.
/
/3. |FRAME: 1-Cys-Peroxiredoxins "1-Cys-peroxiredoxins"| contain a single conserved catalytic cysteine |CITS: [8914536]|. Given the absence of a C<sub>R</sub>, Cp&ndash;SOH of 1-Cys enzymes cannot be resolved within the peroxiredoxin molecules and instead forms a disulfide with a cysteine residue provided by other proteins or small thiol molecules |CITS: [20919932]|.
/
/According to the second classification system, which was introduced in 2011 based on sequence analysis of more than 3500 enzymes, the enzymes are divided into six classes -  AhpC-Prx1 (identical to the typical 2-Cys class), BCP-PrxQ (named after the |FRAME: TAX-562| |FRAME: EG10108| and plant |FRAME: AT3G26060|), Tpx (named for the |FRAME: TAX-562| |FRAME: G6660|), Prx5 (named for the mammalian |FRAME: HS05016-MONOMER|), Prx6 (named for the mammalian |FRAME: CPLX-9416|, sometimes referred to as the “1-Cys” group), and AhpE (named for |FRAME: TAX-1773| AhpE) |CITS: [21287625]|.
/
/Mammalian cells express six peroxiredoxins - PrxI to PrxIV are 2-Cys, PrxV is an atypical 2-Cys, and PrxVI is 1-Cys |CITS: [11795591]|. The yeast |FRAME: TAX-4932| expresses five peroxiredoxins -  Tsa1 and Tsa2 are two 2-Cys, Ahp1 and nTpx are atypical 2-Cys, and mTpx is 1-Cys |CITS: [26813659]|. The plant |FRAME: TAX-3702| expresses nine peroxiredoxins.
//
