UNIQUE-ID - Corrinoid-Adenosyltransferases
TYPES - Proteins
COMMON-NAME - a [corrinoid adenosyltransferase]
COMMENT - Corrinoid adenosyltransferases catalyze an adenosylation reaction in which the Co(I) ion of the corrinoid substrate conducts a nucleophilic attack on the adenosyl moiety of ATP, which leaves it in a Co(III) state.
/some of these enzymes can accept a number of substrates including |FRAME:CPD-694|, |FRAME:COBINAMIDE | and |FRAME:COB-I-ALAMIN|, and can also accept other nucleotides, including |FRAME: CTP|, |FRAME: UTP| and |FRAME: GTP| (in decreasing order of activity).
/
/One of these reactions, involving |FRAME:CPD-694|, is an integral part of the <i>de novo</i> adenosylcobalamin biosynthesis pathway (see |FRAME:PWY-5507|). The other reactions are important in vitamin B12 salvage pathways (such as |FRAME:COBALSYN-PWY|) |CITS: [2403541]|.
/
/The actual substrate for the enzymatic reaction is |FRAME: COB-I-ALAMIN|, in which the cobalt ion has a valency of +1. However, |FRAME: COB-I-ALAMIN| is very reactive, and, if left unprotected, is rapidly oxidized to |FRAME: CPD-1829|. The midpoint redox potential of the Co<sup>2+</sup>/Co<sup>1+</sup> couple is -610 mV, which is is too low for any known cellular reductant |CITS: [4489]|.
/Remarkably, the enzyme is able to overcome this thermodynamic barrier. After binding the corrinoid substrate an aromatic amino acid residue displaces the lower ligand |CITS: [19236001]|, generating a four-coordinate |FRAME: CPD-1829| intermediate, the reduction potential of which is higher by >250 mV than the free compound, bringing it within physiological range |CITS: [15954777][15913339][18672897]|. The cobalt is subsequently reduced to the +1 valence. The source of the electron used for the reduction of the enzyme-bound |FRAME: CPD-1829| to |FRAME: COB-I-ALAMIN| <i>in vivo</i> has not been established. However, CobA was shown to interact <i>in vitro</i> with flavodoxin A (FldA), and reduced FldA was shown to efficiently drive the adenosylation of cob(II)alamin |CITS: [11408479][16207720]|. Furthermore, free reduced flavins and non-specific flavoproteins can also reduce cob(II)alamin bound in the active site of the enzyme, leading to the suggestion that bona fide cobalamin reductases may not be necessary |CITS: [19933577]|.
/
/Three types of corrinoid adenosyltransferases that share no sequence similairty have been reported so far, all of which are found in the bacterium |FRAME: TAX-90371|. |FRAME: G-10061 CobA| is produced continuously to maintain basal concentrations of |FRAME: ADENOSYLCOBALAMIN|, while the other two enzymes, encoded by the |FRAME: STM2050| and |FRAME: STM2467| genes, provide the |FRAME: ADENOSYLCOBALAMIN| cofactor for |FRAME: EC-4.2.1.28|, and |FRAME: EC-4.3.1.7|, respectively, and are induced by the substrates of these enzymes (|FRAME: PROPANE-1-2-DIOL| and |FRAME: ETHANOL-AMINE|, respectively). The mammalian enzyme, encoded by the |FRAME: HS13779| gene, belongs to the PduO type.
//
