UNIQUE-ID - CAPSULAR-POLYSACCHARIDES
TYPES - Compounds
COMMON-NAME - a capsular polysaccharide
COMMENT - Polysaccharide capsules are ubiquitous structures found on the cell surface of a broad range of bacterial species. They are thick, mucous-like, layers of polysaccharides that form a cap around the bacterial surface.They are an important factor in the virulence of many animal and plant pathogens, where they protect the bacteria from opsonophagocytosis and complement-mediated killing by the host.
/
/Capsular polysaccharides are linear and consist of regularly repeating subunits of one to six monosaccharides. They have molecular weights on the order of 100-2000 kDa, and are linked to the cell surface of the bacterium via covalent attachments to phospholipids, lipid-A molecules, or peptidoglycan. The composition allows for a remarkable variability - over 80 different capsular polysaccharides (also known as K antigens) have been described for |FRAME: TAX-562| alone.
/
/Capsular polysaccharides are highly hydrated, and consist of over 95% water. 
/
/Biosynthesis and assembly of capsular polysaccharides is a complex process. In Gram-negative bacteria the activated precursors (nucleotide monophospho and diphospho sugars) are assembled in the cytoplasm into the nascent polysaccharide by enzymes associated with the inner membrane, and while attached to the membrane by an undecaprenyl membrane anchor. A dedicated translocation pathway moves the nascent polymer through the periplasm and across the outer membrane to the cell surface, where it is removed from the membrane anchor and attached to the core oligosacchride of lipid A.
//
