UNIQUE-ID - Oxyhemoglobins
TYPES - Proteins
COMMON-NAME - an oxyhemoglobin
COMMENT - An oxyhemoglobin is |FRAME: Hemoglobins| with bound oxygen. The oxygen is in a |FRAME: SUPER-OXIDE| state, with a charge of -1, while the hemoglobin iron is in an oxidized +3 state.
/
/The iron is located at the center of a |FRAME: Heme-b| group, and is bound covalently to the globular protein via the imidazole ring of a histidine residue (known as the proximal histidine) below the porphyrin ring. A sixth position of the iron can reversibly bind oxygen by a coordinate covalent bond, but only when the iron is in the ferrous (II) state.
/
/When oxygen is bound, it is in an "end-on bent" geometry where one oxygen atom binds the Fe atom and the other protrudes at an angle. When oxygen is not bound, a very weakly bonded water molecule fills the site, forming a distorted octahedron.
//
UNIQUE-ID - O-AMP-tyrosine-Modifications
