UNIQUE-ID - Iron-Sulfur-Cluster-Scaffold-Proteins
TYPES - Proteins
COMMON-NAME - an [Fe-S] cluster scaffold protein
COMMENT - |FRAME: Iron-Sulfur-Cluster-Scaffold-Proteins "[Fe-S] cluster scaffold proteins"| act as a scaffold on which the [Fe-S] clusters are assembled and from which the clusters are delivered to various apoproteins.
/This type of proteins is found in both prokaryotes and eukaryotes (in the mitochondria) and serves similar functions in all organisms.
/
/Initial studies performed with the IscU [Fe-S] cluster scaffold protein from |FRAME: TAX-2336| suggested that the protein exists in a dynamic equilibrium between two distinct conformations |CITS: [12909018][14688265]|. Further studies conducted with the |FRAME: G7324 "<i>apo</i>-IscU"| of |FRAME: TAX-562| showed that the protein exists in equilibrium between a structured (S) and |FRAME: D-form-FeS-Cluster-Scaffold-Proteins "disordered"| (D) state |CITS: [19492851]|. The D-state of <i>apo</i>-IscU is the substrate for the |FRAME: CPLX0-248 "IscS cysteine desulfurase"|, which transfer sulfur atoms from L-cysteine molecules to cysteine residues of IscU |CITS: [22203963]|. Upon the addition of iron atoms, a [2Fe-2S] cluster forms on the scaffold protein. The cluster is transferred to other proteins via the action of chaperons, such as HscB and HscA |CITS: [23333622]|.
/
/The structure shown here depicts the four |FRAME: CYS| residues that coordinate the Fe atoms of a [4Fe-4S] cluster.
//
