UNIQUE-ID - All-Amines
TYPES - Compounds
COMMON-NAME - an amine
COMMENT - Amines are derivatives of |FRAME: AMMONIA|, with one or more of the hydrogen atoms replaced by organic substituents such as alkyl and aryl groups.
/
/When only one of the three hydrogen atoms in ammonia is replaced by an alkyl group, the compound is called |FRAME: Primary-Amines|. When two, three, or four of the hydtogen atoms are replaced, the compound is called |FRAME: Secondary-Amines|, |FRAME: Tertiary-Amines|, or |FRAME: Quaternary-Amines|, respectively.
