//
UNIQUE-ID - Opines
TYPES - Compounds
COMMON-NAME - an opine
COMMENT - Opines are a large family of low molecular weight compounds most commonly found in plant crown gall tumors or hairy root tumours produced by parasitic bacteria of the genus Agrobacterium. However, they are also found in marine invertebrates, fungi, higher plants and mammals.
/
/Opine biosynthesis in crown gall tumors is catalyzed by enzymes encoded by genes contained in T-DNA (transfer DNA), which is part of the Ti plasmid (in Agrobacterium) or Ri plasmid (in Rhizobium). The plasmids are inserted by the bacteria into the plant genome, where they are integrated and expressed.
/
/The opines are used by the bacterium as energy, carbon and nitrogen sources. Each strain of Agrobacterium and Rhizobium induces and catabolizes a specific set of opines, determined by the specific Ti or Ri plasmid they possess. Over 30 different opines have been described.
//
