TYPES - Proteins
COMMON-NAME - a farnesylated protein that ends with a CaaX sequence
COMMENT - CaaX proteins are eukaryotic proteins that terminate with a CaaX motif (C = cysteine, A = generally an aliphatic residue, X = one of a few amino acids) that undergo three ordered post-translational maturation events referred to as CaaX  processing. These events are: covalent attachment of an isoprenoid lipid (farnesyl or geranylgeranyl) to the cysteine (|FRAME: EC-2.5.1.58|), proteolytic removal of the AAX tripeptide (|FRAME: EC-3.4.24.84|), and carboxyl methylesterification of the newly exposed COOH-terminal prenylcysteine (|FRAME: EC-2.1.1.100|).
