UNIQUE-ID - CPD-12378
TYPES - Compounds
COMMON-NAME - melanochrome
COMMENT - Spectroscopic studies of the biosynthesis of |FRAME: CPD-12379| showed that it takes place in three chromophoric phases.
/The first phase corresponds to the formation of a red pigment (&lambda;max 475 nm), |FRAME: L-DOPACHROME|. The second phase corresponds to a purple intermediate, which was designated |FRAME: CPD-12378|, with a broad absorption maximum at 540 nm, and the third phase is characterized by a general absorption due to |FRAME: CPD-12379| |CITS: [Napolitano85]|.
/
/Chemical analysis of |FRAME: CPD-12378| suggests that it is composed of different oligomers (mostly dimers and trimers)
/of |FRAME: DIHYDROXYINDOLE| (DHI) and |FRAME: 56-DIHYDROXYINDOLE-2-CARBOXYLATE| linked by 2-4' and 2-7' linkages |CITS: [Prota91]|.
//
UNIQUE-ID - Cobamide-Upper-Ligands
TYPES - Compounds
COMMON-NAME - a cobamide upper ligand
COMMENT - |FRAME: Cobamides "A cobamide"| is a corrinoid molecule based on the structure of |FRAME: CPD-20843|, a cobalt-corrinoid hexaamide that is formed from |FRAME: COBINAMIDE| by the attachment of an &alpha;-D-ribofuranose 3-phosphate residue at the 2 position of the aminopropanol chain. Cobamides serve as cofactors for a number of important enzymes.
/
/A key structural feature of cobinamides is a corrin ring with a cobalt ion in its center. Four of the six coordination sites of the cobalt ion are provided by the corrin ring, while the other two are provided by |FRAME: Cobamide-Upper-Ligands upper| (&beta;) and |FRAME: Cobamide-Lower-Ligands lower| (&alpha;) ligands, which are located above and below the ring plane, respectively. The best known cobamide, |FRAME: Cobalamins cobalamin|, contains |FRAME: DIMETHYLBENZIMIDAZOLE| as the lower ligand and either a methyl group or 5'-deoxyadenosyl group as the upper ligand.
//
UNIQUE-ID - Cobamide-Lower-Ligand-Ribotides
TYPES - Compounds
COMMON-NAME - a cobamide lower ligand ribotide
COMMENT - |FRAME: Cobamides "A cobamide"| is a corrinoid molecule based on the structure of |FRAME: CPD-20843|, a cobalt-corrinoid hexaamide that is formed from |FRAME: COBINAMIDE| by the attachment of an &alpha;-D-ribofuranose 3-phosphate residue at the 2 position of the aminopropanol chain. Cobamides serve as cofactors for a number of important enzymes.
/
/A key structural feature of cobinamides is a corrin ring with a cobalt ion in its center. Four of the six coordination sites of the cobalt ion are provided by the corrin ring, while the other two are provided by |FRAME: Cobamide-Upper-Ligands upper| (&beta;) and |FRAME: Cobamide-Lower-Ligands lower| (&alpha;) ligands, which are located above and below the ring plane, respectively. The best known cobamide, |FRAME: Cobalamins cobalamin|, contains |FRAME: DIMETHYLBENZIMIDAZOLE| as the lower ligand and either a methyl group or 5'-deoxyadenosyl group as the upper ligand.
/
/At least 16 different cobamides with structural variability in the lower ligand have been described. The 16 bases reported so far are |FRAME: BENZIMIDAZOLE|, |FRAME: CPD-18320|, |FRAME: CPD-18321|, |FRAME: CPD-18497|, |FRAME: CPD-18495|, |FRAME: DIMETHYLBENZIMIDAZOLE|, |FRAME: ADENINE|, |FRAME: CPD-18323|, |FRAME: GUANINE|, |FRAME: HYPOXANTHINE|, |FRAME: PHENOL|, |FRAME: CPD-108|, |FRAME: CPD-5723|, |FRAME: CPD-20865|, |FRAME: CPD-20864|, and |FRAME: CPD-20885|  |CITS: [24055007]|. Different cobamides may not be functionally equivalent as cofactors for cobamide-dependent enzymes |CITS: [14351147][13796808][13796809][21696461][22923412][23417488]|.
//
