UNIQUE-ID - IS-Elements
TYPES - Transposons
COMMENT - An IS element is a short DNA sequence that acts as a transposable element, meaning
/it can change its position within the genome.  IS elements are small relative to other
/transposable elements, and they code only for proteins (e.g., transposases) involved in transposition
/activity.  When IS elements occur in the middle of genes, they interrupt the coding
/sequence and inactivate the gene.  IS elements can also block the expression of
/other genes within the same operon.
/
//
