UNIQUE-ID - NifDK-M-cluster
TYPES - Protein-Complexes
TYPES - Modified-Proteins
COMMON-NAME - a NifDK protein containing an M-cluster
COMMENT - The NifDK heterotetrameric complex constitutes the dinitrogenase component of molybdenum-type (MoFe) nitrogenases.
/
/The [MoFe]-nitrogenase enzyme complex consists of two oxygen-sensitive metalloprotein components |CITS: [8297344]|.
/The first component, dinitrogenase reductase (NifH), is a homodimer protein with a binding site for ATP hydrolysis in each subunit and a single [4Fe4S] cluster bridging the two subunits. The [4Fe4S] cluster transfers electrons from an external electron donor (a ferredoxin or a flavodoxin, depending on the species) to the second component, dinitrogenase |CITS: [1529351]|.
/
/The second component is a heterotetramer of two NifD and two NifK proteins. It contains two unique cofactors: |FRAME: 8FE-7S|, known as the P-cluster, sitting at each &alpha;&beta;-subunit interface, and two copies of the |FRAME: CPD-41|, known as the M-cluster, which are located within each &alpha;-subunit (NifD).
/
/For the protein from |FRAME: TAX-354|, the M-cluster is held in its place by interactions with Cys275 and His442, and the homocitrate is anchored by interactions with Lys428 |CITS: [21212358]|. 
/
/The structure shown below depicts Cys275 and His442, which interact with the M-cluster.
//
