UNIQUE-ID - Phosphorylated-Phosphoglucosamine-Mutase
TYPES - Polypeptides
TYPES - Modified-Proteins
COMMON-NAME - a phosphorylated phosphoglucosamine mutase
COMMENT - Phosphoglucosamine mutase catalyzes the interconversion of the |FRAME: D-GLUCOSAMINE-6-P| and
/|FRAME: GLUCOSAMINE-1P| isomers.  
/
/The enzyme is active only in phosphorylated form; the site of phosphorylation in the enzyme from |FRAME: TAX-562| is Ser102 |CITS: [10231382]|. it can autophosphorylate <I>in vitro</I> in the presence of ATP to a low level |CITS: [10671448]|. 
/
/The phosphoglucosamine mutase reaction follows a ping-pong bi-bi mechanism, where |FRAME: CPD0-1096| acts as an intermediate |CITS: [10231382]|.
//
UNIQUE-ID - Hybrid-Cluster-Proteins
TYPES - Polypeptides
COMMON-NAME - a hybrid-cluster protein
COMMENT - Hybrid-cluster proteins (also known as prismane proteins or HCPs) are present in a wide variety of organisms from the Bacteria, Archaea and Eukarya kingdoms |CITS: [Hagen89][1318832][1311311][8003528][10651802][18560155]|.
/These proteins contain two types of Fe–S clusters: one, which is variable, is either [2Fe-2S] or [4Fe-4S], and the other, the actual hybrid cluster, is an ususual [4Fe–2S–3O] cluster. The latter as initially thought to be a [6Fe–6S] moiety in a `prismane' configuration, until the real structure was resolved in 1998 |CITS: [Arendsen98][11941509][12764602]|. HCPs share sequence and structure homology with |FRAME: EC-1.2.7.4| |CITS: [18560155]|.
/
/The physiological function of the hybrid-cluster proteins has not yet been elucidated. Two main hypotheses for its function include a role in protection against reactive nitrogen species and a role in oxygen-related oxidative-protection mechanisms.
/
/In |FRAME: TAX-562| the hybrid cluster is reduced by a dedicated protein (Hcr) that transfers the electrons from NADH to the cluster |CITS: [10651802]|.
/
//
