UNIQUE-ID - SPHINGOLIPIDS
TYPES - Lipids
COMMON-NAME - a sphingolipid
COMMENT - Sphingolipids are a class of lipids derived from the unsaturated aliphatic amino alcohol |FRAME: SPHINGOSINE|. They are named for the mythological Sphinx because at the time (1884) their function was enigmatic |CITS: [Thudichum84]|.
/The sphingosine backbone (often referred to as the |FRAME: Sphingoids "sphingoid base"|) is amide-linked to an acyl group, such as a fatty acid, and is often also <i>O</i>-linked to a charged head group such as ethanolamine, serine, or choline. 
/
/There are three main types of sphingolipids: |FRAME: Ceramides ceramides|, |FRAME: Sphingomyelins sphingomyelins|, and |FRAME: Glycosphingolipids glycosphingolipids|. Ceramides are the most simple sphingolipids, composed of only the sphingoid base and a fatty acid. Sphingomyelins are composed of a ceramide bound to a charged head group, usually |FRAME: PHOSPHORYL-CHOLINE|. Glycosphingolipids are composed of a ceramide with attached mono- or oligosaccharide moieties.
/
/Mammals usually produce |FRAME: PHOSPHORYL-CHOLINE|-containing |FRAME: Sphingomyelins sphingomyelins|, while plants and fungi usually produce glycosphingolipids with inositol as the head group.
//
UNIQUE-ID - Apo-3-methylcrotonoyl-CoA-carboxylase
TYPES - Polypeptides
COMMON-NAME - a methylcrotonoyl-CoA carboxylase
COMMENT - |FRAME: EC-6.4.1.4|.
/
/In 1960 Rilling and Coon demonstrated the carboxylation of |FRAME: 3-METHYL-CROTONYL-COA| by extracts of  |FRAME: TAX-301| |CITS: [13741692]|.
/
/One year later, Lynen et al. reported that a carbon dioxide-fixing enzyme, |FRAME: CPLX66-17|, was necessary for the oxidation of leucine and isovalerate in species of  Mycobacterium and Achromobacter isolated from soil |CITS: [14467590]|.
/
/The genes encoding the human 3-methylcrotonyl-CoA carboxylase have been cloned and sequenced based on sequence similarity to other organisms. Sequencing of genes from patients with 3-methylcrotonyl-CoA (MCC) deficiency verified that the disease is caused by mutations in this enzyme |CITS: [11406611]|.
/
/The enzyme was reported to be induced in higher plants during carbohydrate starvation, indicating the breakdown of protein and the massive degradation of leucine |CITS: [8925891]|.
//
UNIQUE-ID - CoI-Corrinoid-Fe-S-proteins
TYPES - Cobalt-I-Corrinoid-Proteins
TYPES - Corrinoid-Fe-S-Proteins
TYPES - Protein-Complexes
COMMON-NAME - a [Co(I) corrinoid Fe-S protein]
SYNONYMS - Co(I)FeSP
SYNONYMS - a corrinoid Fe-S protein
COMMENT - The corrinoid iron-sulfur protein (CoFeSP) is functional in the |FRAME:CODH-PWY| of autotrophic carbon fixation in various bacteria and archaea, where it is essential for the biosynthesis of acetyl-CoA.
/
/The protein from |FRAME: TAX-129958| contains two cofactors - |FRAME: Co-a-5-methoxy-benzimidazole-cobamides "5-methoxybenzimidazolylcobamide"| and |FRAME: CPD-7|. The cobamide is bound in a base-off state, with neither the 5-methoxybenzimidazolyl group nor a nitrogen atom from a protein side chain coordinating the cobalt |CITS: [16983091]|.
/
/CoFeSP acts in two methylation reactions: the transfer of a methyl group from methyltransferase-bound methyltetrahydrofolate to the cob(I)amide of CoFeSP, during which the cobalt is oxidized to the (III) state (|FRAME: EC-2.1.1.258|), and the transfer of the methyl group of methyl-cob(III)amide to the reduced Ni-Ni-[4Fe-4S] active site cluster of |FRAME: EC-2.3.1.169|, during which the cobalt is restored to its active (I) state |CITS: [16983091]|.
/
/More recent findings suggest that the protein may also be involved as a methyl donor in methionine biosynthesis by MesB-type core methionine synthases |CITS: [Price20]|.
/
/The protein is heterodimeric, consisting of two tightly interacting subunits. The large subunit, encoded by the |FRAME: G-80944| gene, comprises three domains, of which the N-terminal domain binds the [4Fe-4S] cluster, the middle domain is a (&beta;&alpha;)<sub>8</sub>-barrel, and the C-terminal domain shows an open fold and binds Cobeta-aqua-(5,6-dimethylbenzimidazolylcobamide) in a "base-off" state without a protein ligand at the cobalt ion. The small subunit, encoded by the |FRAME: G-80945| gene, also displays a (&beta;&alpha;)<sub>8</sub>-barrel fold and interacts with the upper side of the corrin macrocycle |CITS: [16983091]|.
/
//
