UNIQUE-ID - Siderophore
TYPES - Secondary-Metabolites
COMMON-NAME - a siderophore
COMMENT - Siderophores are small, high-affinity iron chelating compounds usually produced and secreted by microorganisms. Once outside the cell, siderophores bind |FRAME: FE+3| with high affinity, and the iron-siderophore complexes are imported back into the cell by active-transport mechanisms.
/
/Siderophores are very common in pathogenic bacteria, since iron in the host organism is usually tightly bound to proteins, resulting in an extremely low concentration of free iron in the blood.
/
/Most siderophores belong to one of three major groups: the |FRAME: Catecholate-siderophores "catechols"|, |FRAME: Hydroxamate-siderophores "hydroxamates"| and |FRAME: Thiazoline-siderophores "thiazolines"|.
/
/Some grasses are known to make siderophores as well. These |FRAME: Phytosiderophores "phytosiderophores"| are also known as mugineic acids.
//
UNIQUE-ID - Egg-glycoprotein-Gp43
TYPES - Polypeptides
COMMON-NAME - egg glycoprotein Gp43
COMMENT - Animal eggs contain several glycoproteins involved in species-specific sperm binding, induction of the acrosome reaction and prevention of post-fertilization polyspermy. In mammals these proteins form the zona pellucida - a glycoprotein membrane surrounding the plasma membrane of the oocyte. The mammalian zona pellucida consists of four glycoproteins - ZP1, ZP2, ZP3 and ZP4. ZP3 is responsible for species-specific sperm binding.
/
/The homolog of ZP3 in frogs is called Gp43 |CITS: [9352194]|. Gp43 is synthesized in an <i>apo</i> inactive form, and is cleaved to form the active form, known as Gp41, by |FRAME: EC-3.4.21.120| |CITS: [10084976]|.
//
