UNIQUE-ID - Methyl-Acceptors
TYPES - Acceptors
COMMON-NAME - a methyl group donor
SYNONYMS - a methyl group acceptor
SYNONYMS - a methyl donor
COMMENT - |FRAME: Methyl-Acceptors "A methyl group donor"| is a compound that can donate a methyl group to another compound in a reaction catalyzed by enzymes that belong to the |FRAME: EC-2.1.1 methyltransferase group"|.
/Prior to donating the methyl group the compound is |FRAME: Methylated-methyl-acceptors| and after donating it the compound is |FRAME: Demethylated-methyl-acceptors|.
/
/Since methylation reactions are sometimes reversible, the distinction between a methyl group donor and a methyl group acceptor is not always determined by the actual chemical entity, but by the role it plays in a particular reaction. However, some compounds are often used as methyl group donors by the methyltransferases in reactions that are physiologically unidirectional.
/
/By far, the most common methyl group donor in biology is |FRAME: S-ADENOSYLMETHIONINE|. However, other methyl donors exist, including |FRAME: METOH|, |FRAME: 5-METHYL-THF-GLU-N "<i>N</i><sup>5</sup>-methyl tetrahydrofolate"|, |FRAME: METHYL-THMPT|, |FRAME: METHYLAMINE|, |FRAME: DIMETHYLAMINE|, |FRAME: TRIMETHYLAMINE|, and |FRAME: CPD-7671|.
/
/This particular entry is used when the identity of the methyl group donor (or acceptor) is not known or cannot be defined.
//
UNIQUE-ID - Gramicidin-S-synthetases
TYPES - Non-ribosomal-peptide-synthetases
COMMON-NAME - a gramicidin-S synthetase
COMMENT - Gramicidin-S synthetase is composed of two large, multidomain polypeptides (reviewed in |CITS: [15487945]| and in |CITS: [16895337]|). Gramicidin-S synthetase I comprises module 1, which contains three domains: an adenylation domain, a thiolation domain and an epimerization domain |CITS: [7534306]|. The thiolation domain is referred to in the literature as the T, holo-[acyl-carrier protein], ACP, peptidyl-carrier protein, or PCP domain (the latter two names are used in the case of non-ribosomal peptide synthetases). The thiolation domain is generated from an apo form that is posttranslationally modified by phosphopantetheinyltransferase-catalyzed covalent attachment of |FRAME: PANTETHEINE-P| (derived from |FRAME: CO-A|) to a conserved serine residue.
/
/Gramicidin-S synthetase II comprises modules 2-5. These modules each contain adenylation, condensation and thiolation 
/domains, with module 5 also containing a thioesterase domain (In |CITS:[16895337]| |CITS:[8939709]|).
/
/Note in the structure below shows the |FRAME: PANTETHEINE-P| that is added post-translationally to a Serine residue in the thiolation domain |CITS: [16774586]|.
/
//
