TYPES - Cytochromes-CL
TYPES - Modified-Proteins
COMMON-NAME - an oxidized cytochrome <i>c</i><sub>L</sub>
COMMENT - Cytochrome <i>c</i><sub>L</sub> is a relatively large (about 19 kDa) acidic cytochrome that is specifically involved in electron transfer from the quinoprotein methanol dehydrogenase |CITS: [6263253][6295363]|.
/Despite its relatively large size it contains only one heme. Its amino acid suggests that it is completely different, except for its haem-binding site, from all other cytochromes |CITS: [2851998]|.
/
/The cytochrome <i>c</i><sub>L</sub> has been cloned and studied from several methylotrophic bacteria, including |FRAME: TAX-272630| |CITS: [3129405][2842733]| and |FRAME: TAX-266| |CITS: [1657871]|.
//
UNIQUE-ID - B-vitamins
TYPES - Vitamins
COMMON-NAME - a B vitamin
COMMENT - B vitamins are a class of eight water-soluble vitamins that play important roles in cell metabolism. The B vitamins were classified together because all of them serve as either enzyme cofactors, cosubstrates in important metabolic reactions, or as precursors for cofactors or cosubstrates. 
/
/The different B vitamins are chemically distinct compounds that do not resemble one another. The dietary supplements known as "B complexes" contain all eight of these compounds.
/
/The eight members of the vitamin B class are:
/
/Vitamin B<sub>1</sub>: |FRAME: THIAMINE|
/
/Vitamin B<sub>2</sub>: |FRAME: RIBOFLAVIN|
/
/Vitamin B<sub>3</sub>:|FRAME: NIACINE|, |FRAME: NIACINAMIDE|, and |FRAME: NICOTINAMIDE_RIBOSE "nicotinamide riboside"|
/
/Vitamin B<sub>5</sub>: |FRAME: PANTOTHENATE|
/
/Vitamin B<sub>6</sub>: |FRAME: PYRIDOXINE|, |FRAME: PYRIDOXAL|, and |FRAME: PYRIDOXAMINE|
/
/Vitamin B<sub>7</sub>: |FRAME: BIOTIN|
/
/Vitamin B<sub>9</sub>: |FRAME: THF folate|
/
/Vitamin B<sub>12</sub>: |FRAME: ADENOSYLCOBALAMIN| (although supplements usually contain |FRAME: CPD-9037| or |FRAME: CPD-315|, which are converted to the active form <i>in vivo</i>)
/
//
