UNIQUE-ID - Rhodopsins
TYPES - Opsins
TYPES - Modified-Proteins
COMMON-NAME - a rhodopsin
COMMENT - |FRAME: Rhodopsins Rhodopsin| is a biological pigment found in the retina that is responsible for both the formation of the photoreceptor cells and the first events in the perception of light. 
/
/Vertebrate rhodopsin consists of the protein moiety |FRAME: Opsins opsin| (|FRAME: Aporhodopsins <i>apo</i>-rhodopsin|), which is a G protein-coupled receptor, and a reversibly covalently bound cofactor, |FRAME: CPD-881| |CITS: [6342691]|. Insect rhodopsin often contains |FRAME: 3-Hydroxy-11-cis-retinal| |CITS: [Seki98]|. Most insects examined use the |FRAME: CPD-14329 "R enantiomer"| of 3-hydroxyretinal, but the dipteran suborder |FRAME: TAX-480117|, including |FRAME: TAX-7215|, use |FRAME: CPD-14328|. Firefly squid (|FRAME: TAX-6625|) have been found to use |FRAME: CPD-14331| |CITS: [3416013]|. 
/
/When a photon is absorbed by the retinal chromophore, it isomerizes from |FRAME: CPD-881| into |FRAME: RETINAL| (while bound to the protein) and induces a conformational change in the opsin. In mammalian cells this process is known as bleaching. The protein goes through several conformations: 
/
/photorhodopsin &rarr; bathorhodopsin &rarr; lumirhodopsin &rarr; metarhodopsin I &rarr; metarhodopsin II
/
/|FRAME: Metarhodopsins-II "Metarhodopsin II"| activates the associated G protein transducin and triggers a second messenger cascade. It is subsequently deactivated in a process that involves phosphorylation and binding of the protein arrestin. Vertebrate rhodopsin eventually dissociates into |FRAME: RETINAL| and |FRAME: Aporhodopsins opsin| |CITS: [3006038][2719933][2550422]|, and needs to be regenerated in a reverse process that involves arrestin release, dephosphorylation, and the binding of a newly synthesized molecule of |FRAME: CPD-881| |CITS: [13011282][1386362]|. Invertebrate metarhodopsin, on the other hand, is thermally stable, and rhodopsin regeneration is triggered by the absorption of a second photon |CITS: [3780740][8446607][8639666]|.
/
/The retinal chromophore is connected to the protein via a Schiff base (a double bond between a carbon in the chromophore to a nitrogen in a lysine residue of opsin) |CITS: [Harosi95]|. The structure shown here is a generic representation, as not all rhodopsins utilize this particular form of retinal.
//
UNIQUE-ID - Beta-Phycoerythrocyanins-PCB84
TYPES - Polypeptides
TYPES - Modified-Proteins
COMMON-NAME - a [phycoerythrocyanin &beta;-subunit]-Cys<sup>84</sup>-phycocyanobilin
SYNONYMS - a [phycoerythrocyanin &beta;-subunit Cys-84]-PCB
COMMENT - |FRAME: Phycoerythrocyanins Phycoerythrocyanins| are members of the |FRAME: Phycobiliproteins phycobiliproteins|, which are components of the photosynthetic light-harvesting antenna complexes of |FRAME: TAX-1117| and some algae (|FRAME: TAX-2763 rhodophytes|, |FRAME: TAX-3027 cryptomonads|, and |FRAME: TAX-38254 glaucocystophytes|) that capture light energy and pass it on to |FRAME: Chlorophylls chlorophylls| during photosynthesis. They increase the efficiency of photosynthesis by collecting light energy at wavelengths over which chlorophyll absorbs poorly.
/
/|FRAME: Phycoerythrocyanins Phycoerythrocyanins|, which are found in in some cyanobacteria, have a characteristic magenta color, and an absorption maximum around 575 nm. Like other |FRAME: Phycobiliproteins phycobiliproteins|, they are composed from two types of subunits. The &alpha; chain (encoded by the <i>pecA</i> gene) contains one molecule of the violet chromophore |FRAME: Phycoviolobilins phycoviolobilin|, which is covalently attached at Cys-84, and the &beta; subunit (encoded by the <i>pecB</i> gene) contains two molecules of the blue chromophore |FRAME: Phycocyanobilins phycocyanobilin|, which are covalently attached at Cys-84 and -155, respectively.
/
/The |FRAME: Phycoviolobilins phycoviolobilin| chromophore is synthesized by the attachment of free |FRAME: CPD-17222| to the &alpha; subunit (PecA) followed by its isomerization to |FRAME: Phycoviolobilins phycoviolobilin|, catalyzed by the |FRAME: CPLX-8936| enzyme (PecEF) |CITS: [10708746][19182270]|.
/
/Attachment of the |FRAME: Phycocyanobilins phycocyanobilin| chromophore to the Cys-84 position of the &beta; subunit is catalyzed by |FRAME: MONOMER-18987| |CITS: [17895251]|.
//
