UNIQUE-ID - Tetramethylammonium-corrinoid-proteins
TYPES - Corrinoid-Proteins
COMMON-NAME - a tetramethylammonium-specific corrinoid protein
SYNONYMS - an MtqC corrinoid protein
SYNONYMS - a [tetramethylammonium-specific corrinoid protein]
COMMENT - The pathways for methanogenesis from methylated C1 compounds follow a similar route. Methyl transfer from the electron acceptor to |FRAME: CoM| is carried out by enzyme systems composed of three polypeptides: a protein that binds a corrinoid prosthetic group |CITS: [9654068]|, and two methyltransferases, named MT1 and MT2. MT1 and the corrinoid protein form a tight heterodimeric complex. When the substrate binds to this complex, MT1 catalyzes the transfer of the methyl group from the substrate to the corrinoid group. MT2 then transfers the methyl group from the corrinoid to 
/|FRAME: CoM| |CITS:[6438059]|. Individual MT1 and corrinoid-binding proteins are highly specific for their respective substrate, and exhibit little or no activity with similar substrates |CITS: [6615129][9195968][9006042][9654067][10852929]|.
/
/The enzymes responsible for methanogenesis from |FRAME: CPD-7679| were isolated from |FRAME: TAX-117561| and found to consist of two methyltransferases (MtqA and MtqB) and a 22-kDa corrinoid protein (MtqC) (the naomenclature MTQ stands for Methyl Transferase Quarternary amine) |CITS: [9732435]|.
//
UNIQUE-ID - alpha-C-phycoerythrins-PEB84
TYPES - Polypeptides
TYPES - Modified-Proteins
COMMON-NAME - a [C-phycoerythrin &alpha;-subunit]-Cys<sup>82</sup>-phycoerythrobilin
COMMENT - |FRAME: Phycocyanins Phycocyanins| are members of the |FRAME: Phycobiliproteins phycobiliproteins|, which are components of the photosynthetic light-harvesting antenna complexes of |FRAME: TAX-1117| and some algae (|FRAME: TAX-2763 rhodophytes|, |FRAME: TAX-3027 cryptomonads|, and |FRAME: TAX-38254 glaucocystophytes|) that capture light energy and pass it on to |FRAME: Chlorophylls chlorophylls| during photosynthesis. They increase the efficiency of photosynthesis by collecting light energy at wavelengths over which chlorophyll absorbs poorly.
/
/|FRAME: Phycoerythrins Phycoerythrins|, which are found in in red algae and cryptophytes, have a characteristic red color, and have absorption peaks near 495 and 545/566 nm, depending on the chromophores bound and the organism.
/Like other |FRAME: Phycobiliproteins phycobiliproteins|, |FRAME: Phycoerythrins phycoerythrins| are composed of two different subunits that form either trimers [(&alpha;&beta;)<sub>3</sub>] or hexamers [(&alpha;&beta;)<sub>6</sub>] and |FRAME: Phytobilins phytobilin| chromophores that are covalently attached to cysteine residues of the proteins.
/
/Common types of phycoerythrins include |FRAME: R-Phycoerythrins R-phycoerythrin|,  |FRAME: B-Phycoerythrins B-phycoerythrin|, and |FRAME: C-Phycoerythrins C-phycoerythrin|. 
/The "C" in the name |FRAME: C-Phycoerythrins C-phycoerythrin| comes from |FRAME: TAX-1117|, from which the compound was originally isolated. 
/
/The only bound chromophore is |FRAME: Phycoerythrobilins phycoerythrobilin|, with five phycoerythrobilin molecules on each (&alpha;&beta;) monomer |CITS: [24242963]|.
/
/The lyase encoded by |FRAME: G-43725 cpcS| genes (also sometimes found in a heterodimer with CpcU) are known to catalyze the attachment of PEB at Cys-84 of both subunits of C-phycoerythrin |CITS: [17726096]|.
//
