UNIQUE-ID - Orsellinyl-ArmB
TYPES - Modified-Proteins
TYPES - Polyketide-ACP-Proteins
COMMON-NAME - an orsellinyl-[armB polyketide synthase]
COMMENT - It has been shown by feeding studies that the |FRAME: CPD-47| moiety of the |FRAME: Melleolides melleolides| is biosynthesized via a polyketide pathway |CITS: [19795841]|.
/
/The |FRAME: G-55167| gene of the basidiomycete fungus |FRAME: TAX-47429| (also known as honey mushroom) encodes an iterative type I polyketide synthase (PKS). Using degenerate PCR primers the complete sequence of the gene was amplified and cloned. Sequence analysis showed that the gene contains nine introns and that ArmB is composed of seven domains (SAT-KS-AT-PT-ACP-ACP-TE). A cDNA was also obtained by reverse transcription and subsequent PCR |CITS: [23078836]|.
/
/
/The cDNA was cloned with an N-terminal His<sub>6</sub> tag and expressed in |FRAME: TAX-562|, and the recombinant protein was purified to homogeneity. An <i>in vitro</i> assay of the purified protein in the presence of |FRAME: ACETYL-COA| and |FRAME: MALONYL-COA| confirmed the production of |FRAME: CPD-47|. Addition of the putative starter unit acetyl-CoA was not required, presumably because loading of malonyl-CoA and subsequent decarboxylation can also prime the reaction |CITS: [23993460]|.
/
/Adding an alcohol receptor molecule to the reaction resulted in the formation of an alcohol-orsellinate ester, which is assumed to be catalyzed by the C-terminal thioesterase (TE) domain. The enzyme strongly preferred primary alcohols over secondary alcohols, and yields increased with chain size from methanol to pentanol. The enzyme could aslo catalyze the esterification with a natural substrate, |FRAME: CPD-20190| (produced by hydrolysis of |FRAME: CPD-20170|), forming |FRAME: CPD-20171| |CITS: [23993460]|.
/
//
UNIQUE-ID - HIF-Alpha
TYPES - Polypeptides
COMMON-NAME - a hypoxia inducible factor (HIF) &alpha; subunit
SYNONYMS - HIF-&alpha;
COMMENT - Hypoxia-inducible factors (HIFs) are transcription factors that respond to decreases in available oxygen in the cellular environment, or hypoxia. Most HIFs are heterodimers.
/
/Under normal conditions the &alpha; subunits of HIF complexes are hydroxylated at conserved proline residues by |FRAME: EC-1.14.11.29|, allowing their recognition and ubiquitination by the VHL E3 ubiquitin ligase, which labels them for rapid degradation. In hypoxic conditions HIF prolyl-hydroxylase is inhibited, since it requires oxygen for its activity, and thus the &alpha; subunits of HIF are not degraded, permitting HIF to upregulate several genes to promote survival in low-oxygen conditions.
ABBREV-NAME - HIF &alpha; subunit
//
