UNIQUE-ID - Methylated-thiol-corrinoid-proteins
TYPES - Corrinoid-Proteins
COMMON-NAME - a methanethiol-specific corrinoid protein
SYNONYMS - an MtsB corrinoid protein
SYNONYMS - a [methanethiol-specific corrinoid protein]
COMMENT - The pathways for methanogenesis from methylated C1 compounds follow a similar route. Methyl transfer from the electron acceptor to |FRAME: CoM| is carried out by enzyme systems composed of three polypeptides: a protein that binds a corrinoid prosthetic group |CITS: [9654068]|, and two methyltransferases, named MT1 and MT2. MT1 and the corrinoid protein form a tight heterodimeric complex. When the substrate binds to this complex, MT1 catalyzes the transfer of the methyl group from the substrate to the corrinoid group. MT2 then transfers the methyl group from the corrinoid to 
/|FRAME: CoM| |CITS:[6438059]|. Individual MT1 and corrinoid-binding proteins are highly specific for their respective substrate, and exhibit little or no activity with similar substrates |CITS: [6615129][9195968][9006042][9654067][10852929]|.
/
/Unlike similar systems for |FRAME:CoM| methylation by |FRAME:METOH| and different methylamines, the enzymatic complex that methylates |FRAME:CoM| with methylated thiols consists of only two types of peptides. The MtsA peptide catalyzes both methyltransferase activities, which are catalyzed in the other systems by two different methyltransferase, MT1 and MT2 |CITS: [11073950]|. 
/The second peptide, MtsB, is a corrinoid protein, similar to the one found in the other systems. Earler studies suggested that one corrinoid cofactor is bound per MtsA:MtsB pair, and six to seven such pairs coprise a 480 kDa complex |CITS: [8335638][8282704]|. However, later work suggested that MtsA forms dimers in solution |CITS: [11073950]|.
