UNIQUE-ID - G-protein-coupled-receptors
TYPES - Polypeptides
COMMON-NAME - a G protein-coupled receptor
COMMENT - G protein-coupled receptors (GPCRs) constitute a large protein family of receptors that sense molecules outside the cell and activate signal transduction pathways and, ultimately, cellular responses, inside the cell.
/
/G protein-coupled receptors are found only in eukaryotes, including yeast, choanoflagellates,and animals. When a ligand binds to the GPCR it causes a conformational change that allows it to act as a guanine nucleotide exchange factor (GEF). The GPCR can then activate an associated heterotrimeric G-protein (|FRAME: EC-3.6.5.1 "EC 3.6.5.1"|) by exchanging its bound GDP for a GTP. The G protein's &alpha; subunit, together with the bound GTP, dissociates from the &beta; and &gamma; subunits and interact with either intracellular signaling proteins or directly with functional proteins, depending on the &alpha; subunit type.
//
UNIQUE-ID - Vitamin-E
TYPES - Chromanes
TYPES - Quinones
TYPES - Vitamins
COMMON-NAME - vitamin E
SYNONYMS - a tocochromenol
SYNONYMS - tocopherol
COMMENT - The term |FRAME: Vitamin-E| (tocochromenols) is a collective term for the eight forms of |FRAME: Tocotrienols tocotrienols| and |FRAME: Tocopherols tocopherols|, each existing as &alpha;, &beta;, &gamma;, and &delta; species.
/
/Structurally tocotrienols and tocopherols differ only in the degree of unsaturation of their side-chain. The tocotrienol chain comprises three <i>trans</i>-double bonds, whereas the tocopherol chain is fully saturated. In addition, the &alpha;, &beta;, &gamma;, and &delta; species of both compound groups vary in the methylation pattern of the chromanol ring |CITS:[12897790]|.
/
/Vitamin E compounds are synthesized only by photosynthetic organisms, although they are essential dietary components for animals (including humans), where they act primarily as antioxidants. Their presumed role in plants involve protection of chloroplast lipids and chlorophylls against oxidative damages. The tocotrienols are mostly found in monocots |CITS:[Padley94]| and a few dicots |CITS:[17110122]|, whereas tocopherols are wider spread in the plant kingdom and dominate in the dicots |CITS:[8827691]|.
//
