UNIQUE-ID - DNA-Ligases
TYPES - Polypeptides
COMMON-NAME - a DNA ligase
COMMENT - DNA ligases facilitate the joining of DNA fragments together by catalyzing the formation of a phosphodiester bond. Most DNA ligases participate in repairing single-strand breaks in duplex DNA, but some forms specifically repair double-strand breaks. In addition to DNA repair, DNA ligase are crucial for DNA replication.
/
/Most DNA ligases catalyze the formation of a phosphodiester bond between a 3'-hydroxyl and 5'-phosphate ends of DNA strands, and require ATP, although some forms require GTP, NAD, or ADP instead of ATP) (see |FRAME: EC-6.5.1.1|, |FRAME: EC-6.5.1.2|, |FRAME: EC-6.5.1.6| and |FRAME: EC-6.5.1.7|).
/
/The reaction proceeds in three steps:
/
/1. Adenylation/guanylylation of a lysine residue in the active center of the enzyme, with the concomitant release of pyrophosphate
/
/2. Transfer of the adenylate/guanylate group to the 5' phosphate of the donor strand, forming a temporary A (or G)-5'-pp-5'-(deoxynucleotide)-[DNA] cap.
/
/3. An attack by the 3'-hydroxyl end of the acceptor strand on the A (or G)-5'-pp-5'-(deoxynucleotide)-[DNA] cap, leading to release of the adenylate/guanylate and formation of a phosphodiester bond between the two substrate fragments.
//
