UNIQUE-ID - E3-independent-Ubiquitin-carrier-E2
TYPES - Polypeptides
COMMON-NAME - an (E3-independent) E2 ubiquitin-conjugating enzyme
SYNONYMS - an (E3-independent) ubiquitin-conjugating enzyme E2
SYNONYMS - a ubiquitin-carrier enzyme E2
SYNONYMS - a ubiquitin-carrier protein E2
SYNONYMS - ubiquitin-carrier protein E2
SYNONYMS - ubiquitin-carrier enzyme E2
SYNONYMS - (E3-independent) ubiquitin-conjugating enzyme E2
COMMENT - The E3-independent ubiquitin-conjugating enzyme E2 performs the second and third steps in the ubiquitination reaction, combining the activities of the regular E2 proteins (see |FRAME: EC-2.3.2.23|) and the E3 proteins (see |FRAME: EC-2.3.2.26|, |FRAME: EC-2.3.2.27| and |FRAME: EC-2.3.2.n|).
/
/The activity of the enzyme starts with the transfer of |FRAME: Ubiquitins ubiquitin| from an |FRAME: Ubiquitin-activating-proteins-E1 E1|-ubiquitin complex to a catalytic L-cysteine residue at its active site by transesterification. Once loaded with ubiquitin, the enzyme binds a target protein and transfers the ubiquitin to a lysine residue of that protein.
/
/Regular E2 proteins transfer the ubiquitin to one of several |FRAME: E3-ubiquitin-carrier-proteins "E3 ubiquitin-carrier proteins"| (or E3 enzymes). The E3 enzyme also binds the target protein substrate, and catalyzes the transfer of the ubiquitin from the E2 cysteine to the lysine residue on the target protein.
//
UNIQUE-ID - Mitogen-Activated-Protein-Kinase
TYPES - Polypeptides
COMMON-NAME - a mitogen-activated protein kinase
COMMENT - Mitogen-activated protein kinases (MAP kinase or MAPK) are eukaryotic protein kinases that are specific to the amino acids serine, threonine, and tyrosine. They are found in all eukaryotes including unicellular eukaryotes, fungi, plants, and animals.
/
/MAP kinases are involved in directing cellular responses to a diverse array of stimuli, such as mitogens, osmotic stress, heat shock and proinflammatory cytokines. They regulate cell functions including proliferation, gene expression, differentiation, mitosis, cell survival, and apoptosis |CITS: [11294822]|.
/
/MAP kinases are catalytically inactive in their base form. In order to be active, they need to be phosphorylated. Most of the MAP kinases belong to the "classical MAP kinases" family and need to be phosphorylated on two amino acids, a threonine and a tyrosine, which are found in a TxY motif at the activation loop. Phosphorylation of the tyrosine precedes phosphorylation of the threonine.
/
/Some MAP kinases are atypical and require only a single residue in their activation loops to be phosphorylated.
