UNIQUE-ID - Glutamine-synthases
TYPES - Protein-Complexes
COMMON-NAME - a glutamine synthetase
COMMENT - Glutamine synthetase (|FRAME: EC-6.3.1.2|) catalyzes the lone reaction in the glutamine biosynthesis pathway, combining |FRAME: GLT| and |FRAME: AMMONIUM| to generate  |FRAME: GLN|.
/
/Glutamine Synthetases are usually complexes of 8, 10, or 12 identical subunits, separated into two face-to-face rings |CITS: [2572586]|. Each monomer contains an active site that  is ahped as a ‘bifunnel’, where three distinct substrates bind: ATP, an ammonium ion, and L-glutamate |CITS: [8563633]|. In addition, there are two divalent cations binding sites |CITS: [235885]|.
/
/ATP phosphorylates glutamate to form ADP and an acyl-phosphate intermediate, &gamma;-glutamyl phosphate, which reacts with ammonia, forming glutamine and inorganic phosphate. The ADP and phosphate groups are released only after the ammonium ion binds and glutamine is released |CITS: [7904828][10708854]|.
//
