COMMENT - Most |FRAME: Ubiquitin-carrier-proteins-E2 "ubiquitin-carrier-proteins"|, also known as E2 enzymes or ubiquitin-conjugating enzymes, catalyze the transfer of |FRAME: Ubiquitins ubiquitin| from an |FRAME: Ubiquitin-activating-proteins-E1 "E1"|-ubiquitin complex to one of their L-cysteine residues. The ubiquitin is then transferred either to a ubiquitin transferase (E3) or directly to the target protein, as in the case of |FRAME: EC-2.3.2.24|, which transfer ubiquitin to a lysine group of a target protein.
/
/This type of E2 proteins also transfer the ubiquitin from |FRAME: Ubiquitin-activating-proteins-E1 "E1"|-ubiquitin complex to a target protein, but it only ubiquinates the &alpha;-amino groups of the N-termini of target proteins.
