UNIQUE-ID - Tirandamycins
TYPES - Antibiotics
COMMON-NAME - a tirandamycin
COMMENT - The tirandamycins belong to a small group of natural products based on tetramic acid, containing a 2,4-pyrrolidinedione ring system. Compounds on this gamily demonstrate extensive biological activities such as antibacterial, antiviral, antiulcerative, cytotoxic, mycotoxic, and antitumor |CITS: [18334299]|. In addition to dienoyltetramic acid moiety, tirandamycins possess a bicyclic ketal skeleton that is also found in some other antimicrobial tetramic acid antibiotics, such as |FRAME: CPD-18222|, |FRAME: CPD-18221|, |FRAME: CPD-18224|, and |FRAME: CPD-18223| |CITS: [Royles95]|.
/
/Tirandamycins inhibit the bacterial RNA polymerase (RNAP), and inhibit both chain initiation and chain elongation |CITS: [791108]|.
/
/|FRAME: CPD-18214 "Tirandamycin A"| was first isolated from the terrestrial bacterium |FRAME: ORG-6282| |CITS: [5092790]|, and its absolute stereochemistry was determined by X-ray diffraction shortly after |CITS: [4710070]|.
/
/Tirandamycin A and its other congeners |FRAME: CPD-18216|, |FRAME: CPD-18217|, and |FRAME: CPD-18218| were later reisolated or discovered from |FRAME: TAX-67297| |CITS: [962473]|, the marine-derived |FRAME: TAX-529089| |CITS: [19883065]|, and |FRAME: TAX-861528|, which was isolated from South China Sea marine sediment.
//
UNIQUE-ID - CPD-9093
TYPES - Organometallics
TYPES - Chlorins
COMMON-NAME - a bacteriochlorophyll <i>d</i>
COMMENT - Green sulfur bacteria (|FRAME: TAX-191412|) and green flimentous bacteria (|FRAME: TAX-1106|) contain chlorosomes - large organelles that are believed to be the most efficient light-harvesting antennae in nature |CITS: [20130996][Saga10]|. Green sulfur bacteria can grow at light intensities that are too low to support growth of any other phototroph, up to a million times lower light than normal sunlight |CITS: [Overmann92]|.
/
/Chlorosomes contain about 1,500 bacteriochlorophyll molecules per reaction center. They are filled with 10–30 rod-shaped elements which are oriented parallel to the long axis of the chlorosomes and have a diameter of 10 nm. Each rod consists of a tubular bilayer formed by self-organization of the antenna bacteriochlorophyll molecules. Unlike all other known photosynthetic antenna, in which the chlorophyll molecules are bound to proteins, chlorosomes do not contain accessory proteins. The chlorosomal bacteriochlorophyll pigments are able to self-aggregate due to their unique chemical characteristics.
/
/The bacteriochlorophylls found in chlorosomes are either |FRAME: CPD-9092 "bacteriochlorophyll <i>c</i>"|, |FRAME: CPD-9093 "bacteriochlorophyll <i>d</i>"| or |FRAME: CPD-9094 "bacteriochlorophyll <i>e</i>"|, depending on the species. They all possess a hydroxyl group at the C3<sup>1</sup> position that allows them to chelate the Mg atom of a neighboring molecule and to interact with the C13-oxo carbonyl group of another neighboring pigment molecule, affording the self-aggregation |CITS: [16121276][19435848][22210764]|. In addition, all of these bacteriochlorophylls lack C-13<sup>2</sup>-methylcarboxyl side chains, which are found in all other (bacterio)chlorophylls but would interfere with the ability to form aggregates |CITS: [16245042]|.
/
/Despite of their names, |FRAME: CPD-9092 "bacteriochlorophyll <i>c</i>"|, |FRAME: CPD-9093 "bacteriochlorophyll <i>d</i>"| and |FRAME: CPD-9094 "bacteriochlorophyll <i>e</i>"| are actually chlorins rather than bacteriochlorins. All three are usually found with an unsaturated farnesyl tail rather than phytyl tails |CITS: [2350541][Borrego99]|, although exceptions have been reported.
/
/In chlorosomes of |FRAME:  TAX-191412| (but not |FRAME: TAX-1106| |CITS: [Risch79][3442679]|) all three types of bacteriochlorophyll appear in several forms with different degrees of methylation at the C-8<sup>2</sup> and C-12<sup>1</sup> carbons |CITS: [12656478][14610639]|. The variety in methylation is depicted in the structure shown here by the R groups. In general, pimgents produced by cultures grown at lower light intensities are more highly methylated at the C-8<sup>2</sup> position than pigments produced by cells of the same organism grown at higher light intensities. Different methylation states result in different aggregation properties and light absorbance of the chlorosome, and thus methylation is used as an adaptation to altering envireonmental conditions. 
/
/Most of the green sulfur bacteria growing in stratified lakes contain |FRAME:CPD-9093 "bacteriochlorophyll <i>d</i>"|, and species containing |FRAME: CPD-9092 "bacteriochlorophyll <i>c</i>"| are rarely found |CITS: [vanGemerden95]|.
//
