UNIQUE-ID - E3-independent-UCP-E2
TYPES - Polypeptides
COMMON-NAME - an E3-independent ubiquitin-carrier-protein E2
COMMENT - Most |FRAME: Ubiquitin-carrier-proteins-E2 "ubiquitin-carrier-proteins"|, also known as E2 enzymes or ubiquitin-conjugating enzymes, catalyze the transfer of |FRAME: Ubiquitins ubiquitin| from an |FRAME: Ubiquitin-activating-proteins-E1 "E1"|-ubiquitin complex to one of several ubiquitin ligases (or E3 enzymes), which in turn catalyze the transfer of the ubiquitin to a lysine residue on the target protein.
/
/However, some E2 proteins act independent of the E3 ligases, and catalyze the transfer of ubiquitin from an E1-ubiquitin complex directly to a lysine residue on the target protein. While confusingly they are also referred to as E2 proteins, we refer to them here as E3-independent ubiquitin-carrier-proteins E2.
//
