UNIQUE-ID - GFP
TYPES - Polypeptides
COMMON-NAME - a ground state green fluorescent protein
SYNONYMS - GFP
COMMENT - Green fluorescent proteins (GFPs) are proteins that exhibit bright green fluorescence when exposed to light in the blue to ultraviolet range. GFPs form a part of the bioluminesence systems of many marine organisms. 
/
/The protein from the jellyfish |FRAME: TAX-6100| was the first GFP to be described |CITS: [13911999]|. In this organism GFP is coupled to the |FRAME: Aequorins aequorin| enzyme, which catalyzes a reaction that forms |FRAME: CPD-20235|. This compound can emit blue light, which can then trigger fluorescence by GFP. However, due to coupling between aequorin and GFP, the short distance enables <A href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F%C3%B6rster_resonance_energy_transfer">F&ouml;rster resonance energy transfer</A> (FRET), a much more efficient, non-radiative energy-transfer process |CITS: [4397528][4151620]|. A similar situation occurs in the soft coral |FRAME: TAX-6136|, where GFP interacts with the luciferase enzyme |CITS: [33175]|.
/
/The protein was first isolated and purified in 1974 |CITS: [4151620]|. A more thorough characterization, including molecular weight, sedimentation coefficient, extinction coefficient, diffusion coefficient, and amino acid composition, was published a few years later |CITS: [28749]|. A cDNA encoding the enzyme was isolated in 1992, suggesting multiple chromosomal genes encoding the protein |CITS: [1347277]|. Cloning and expressing GFP in bacteria and in |FRAME: TAX-6239| has suggeted that GFP could serve as a marker for studying gene expression <i>in vivo</i> |CITS: [8303295][8137953]|.
/
/Several studies have identified the structure of the GFP chromophore, which is produced by autocatalytic cyclization of the tripeptide Ser65-Tyr66-Gly67, which involves dehydration and oxidation by air |CITS: [Shimomura79][Ward80][McCapra88][8448132][9811837]|. It was also shown that the protein undergoes a reversible oxidation-reduction reaction in the presence of molecular oxygen, with only the oxidized form being fluorescent |CITS: [8082767]|.
/
/Over the years GFP has become an extremely useful tool in cell and molecular biology, where it is used as an <i>in situ</i> reporter of expression. The scientists Roger Y. Tsien, Osamu Shimomura, and Martin Chalfie were awarded the 2008 Nobel Prize in Chemistry for their discovery and development of the green fluorescent protein.
//
UNIQUE-ID - Holo-Base-off-His-on-Enzymes
TYPES - Modified-Proteins
COMMON-NAME - a <i>holo</i>-["base-off/His-on" B12-enzyme]
COMMENT - Adenosylcobalamin-dependent enzymes fall into one of three groups: carbon-skeleton mutases (e.g. |FRAME: EC-5.4.99.1|, |FRAME: EC-5.4.99.4|, |FRAME: EC-5.4.99.13|, |FRAME: EC-5.4.99.64|, |FRAME: EC-5.4.99.2|, and |FRAME: EC-5.4.99.63|); eliminases (e.g. |FRAME: EC-4.3.1.7|, |FRAME: EC-4.2.1.28|, |FRAME: EC-4.2.1.30|, and |FRAME: EC-1.17.4.2|), and aminomutases, which also require pyridoxal phosphate as a cofactor (e.g. |FRAME: EC-5.4.3.5| and |FRAME: EC-5.4.3.3|).
/
/In the carbon skeleton mutases and aminomutases an |FRAME: HIS| residue, part of a conserved DxHxxG motif from the protein |CITS: [1397267]|, replaces the dimethylbenzimidazole tail as the lower ligand to cobalt, which is instead extended down into the core of the protein. This mode of binding has been termed "base-off/His-on"" |CITS: [Padmakumar95a][8805541]|.
/
/In contrast, in the eliminases the adenosylcobalamin is bound with the dimethylbenzimidazole base coordinated to cobalt, as it is in free solution. This mode is known as "dmb-on" |CITS: [9537996][10496987]|. Why different proteins use different binding mode of their adenosylcobalamin cofactor remains unclear |CITS: [22516318]|.
//
UNIQUE-ID - Unwound-RNA
TYPES - RNAs
COMMON-NAME - an unwound RNA
//
