UNIQUE-ID - RNA-Ligases
TYPES - Polypeptides
COMMON-NAME - an RNA ligase
COMMENT - RNA ligases facilitate the joining of RNA fragments together by catalyzing the formation of a phosphodiester bond. They participate in repair, splicing and editing pathways that either reseal broken RNAs or alter their primary structure. 
/
/Most RNA ligases catalyze the formation of a phosphodiester bond between a 3'-hydroxyl and 5'-phosphate ends of RNA strands, and require ATP.  They have been divided into two classes on the basis of RNA substrate specificity: Rnl1 enzymes catalyze the joining of broken ends of single-stranded RNA generated by a site-specific RNA endonuclease. Examples include Bacteriophage T4Rnl1, which functions to repair breaks in the anticodon loop of tRNALys |CITS: [4342972]|, and yeast and plants tRNA ligase (Trl1), which participates in intron splicing |CITS: [9582290][15653639]|. Yeast Trl1 is also responsible for nonspliceosomal splicing of mRNA in the unfolded protein response pathway |CITS: [8898194]|.
/
/Rnl2 enzymes repair breaks in double-stranded RNA. While these enzyme are found in all three phylogenetic domains, their biological function is not well understood |CITS: [12228725]|, with the exception of kinetoplastid, where they are involved in altering the translational reading frame of mitochondrial mRNAs by the insertion or removal of uridines |CITS: [11158286]|.
/
/The reaction proceeds in three steps:
/
/1. Adenylation of a lysine residue in the active center of the enzyme, with the concomitant release of pyrophosphate
/
/2. Transfer of the adenylate group to the 5' phosphate of one of the substrate (the donor), forming a temporary A-5'-pp-5'-(deoxynucleotide)-[RNA] end.
/
/3. An attack by the 3'-hydroxyl end of the acceptor strand on the App-(deoxynucleotide)-[RNA] end, leading to release of the adenylate and formation of a phosphodiester bond between the two substrate fragments.
//
