UNIQUE-ID - Sulfolipids
TYPES - Lipids
COMMON-NAME - a sulfolipid
COMMENT - Sulfolipids are a class of lipids that possess a sulfur-containing functional group.
/
/An abundant class of sulfolipids, found in many photosynthetic organisms, including all photosynthetic plants, algae, cyanobacteria, and purple sulfur and non-sulfur bacteria, is |FRAME: SULFOQUINOVOSYLDIACYLGLYCEROL "sulfoquinovosyl diacylglycerol"| (SQDG), which is composed of a glycoside of |FRAME: CPD-10247| and |FRAME: 1-2-Diglycerides diacylglycerol|.
/
/Other important sulfolipids include |FRAME: GALACTOSYLCERAMIDE-SULFATE sulfatide|, which is abundant in myelin,  and |FRAME: Seminolipids seminolipid|, which is the most common glycolipid in mammalian testes.
//
