UNIQUE-ID - Phosphoglucomutase
TYPES - Polypeptides
COMMON-NAME - a phosphoglucomutase
COMMENT - |FRAME: EC-5.4.2.2|  catalyzes the interconversion of the |FRAME: GLC-1-P| and |FRAME: D-glucopyranose-6-phosphate| isomers.  
/
/The enzyme is active only when a specific serine residue at the active site is phosphorylated |CITS: [23074][6223925]|. It can autophosphorylate using its substrate |FRAME: GLC-1-P|, although inefficiently. Maximum activity is obtained only in the presence of the reaction intermediate |FRAME: ALPHA-GLUCOSE-16-BISPHOSPHATE|, which is formed by transferring the phosphate group from the serine residue to |FRAME: GLC-1-P| |CITS: [13156640]|. The dephosphorylated enzyme then facilitates the transfer of a phosphoryl group from the |FRAME: ALPHA-GLUCOSE-16-BISPHOSPHATE| intermediate to the enzyme, leaving |FRAME: D-glucopyranose-6-phosphate| |CITS: [14165931][5726186]|.
