COMMON-NAME - a small archaeal modifier protein
SYNONYMS - SAMP
COMMENT - Small archaeal modifier proteins (SAMPs) are |FRAME: Ubiquitins ubiquitin|-like proteins that are covalently attached to proteins in archaea. Like ubiquitin, these proteins possess a &beta;-grasp fold and carboxy-terminal diglycine motif, and as in ubiquitination, the C-terminal carboxylate forms an isopeptide bond with the &epsilon;-amino group of lysine residues on target proteins |CITS: [20054389]|. In addition, it has been shown that the C-terminal glycine of SAMP2 can form a bond with Lys 58 of SAMP2 itself, forming poly-SAMP chains, as in the case of polyubiquitination. The process of modification by SAMP has been termed SAMPylation.
/
/It has also been shown that SAMP proteins are involved in sulfur transfer. SAMP1 is involved in |FRAME: CPD-4| biosynthesis, while SAMP2 is involved in the thiolation of tRNA |CITS: [21368171]|.
//
