UNIQUE-ID - Xanthine-oxidases
TYPES - Protein-Complexes
COMMON-NAME - a xanthine oxidase
COMMENT - Xanthine oxidoreductase is a molybdoenzyme that is involved in hydroxylation of purines, pterins and aldehydes. In the purine degradation pathway it is the rate-limiting enzyme in the production of |FRAME: URATE|.
/
/The mammalian enzyme, but not the enzymes from prokaryotes or plants, exists in two interconvertible forms designated |FRAME: EC-1.17.1.4|, and |FRAME: EC-1.17.3.2|. Interconversion can occur reversibly through formation of disulfide bonds (catalyzed by |FRAME: EC-1.8.4.7|), or irreversibly by proteolysis |CITS: [2610112][18513323]|. The dehydrogenase form is thought to be the predominant form <i>in vivo</i>.  The enzyme has a complex reaction mechanism involving the |FRAME: CPD-8123|, two iron-sulfur centers (|FRAME: CPD-6|) and |FRAME: FAD|. The dehydrogenase reaction initiates at the |FRAME: CPD-8123| center and the two |FRAME: CPD-6| centers mediate electron transfer to |FRAME: FAD| and then to |FRAME: NAD|.  In the oxidase reaction the final electron acceptor is |FRAME: OXYGEN-MOLECULE|, with the production of |FRAME: SUPER-OXIDE| and |FRAME: HYDROGEN-PEROXIDE|. Reviewed in |CITS: [15218545][14694147][19436671]|.
/
/Both forms of the enzyme can generate reactive oxygen species and the enzyme may have a role in vascular oxidative stress that contributes to endothelial dysfunction in cardiovascular disease. The enzyme also has antimicrobial properties. Mutations in the human gene encoding this enzyme have been identified that cause xanthinuria type I. |FRAME: CPD-9024 Allopurinol|, an inhibitor of this enzyme, has been used for decades in the treatment of gout. Reviewed in |CITS: [19436671]| and in |CITS: [14694147]|.
//
UNIQUE-ID - Co-E-Clth
TYPES - Protein-Complexes
COMMON-NAME - a corrinoid Fe-S protein
SYNONYMS - CoFeSP
COMMENT - The cobalt- and iron-containing corrinoid iron-sulfur protein (CoFeSP) is functional in the
/|FRAME:CODH-PWY| of autotrophic carbon fixation in various bacteria and archaea,
/where it is essential for the biosynthesis of acetyl-CoA.
/CoFeSP acts in two methylation reactions: the transfer of a methyl group from methyltransferase-bound
/methyltetrahydrofolate to the cob(I)amide of CoFeSP, and the transfer of the methyl group of
/methyl-cob(III)amide to the reduced Ni-Ni-[4Fe-4S] active site cluster of acetyl-CoA synthase
/|CITS: [16983091]|.
/
