UNIQUE-ID - E3-ubiquitin-carrier-proteins
TYPES - Polypeptides
COMMON-NAME - an E3 ubiquitin transferase
SYNONYMS - an E3 ubiquitin-carrier protein
COMMENT - E3 ubiquitin-transferases (also called ubiquitin-carrier proteins and incorrectly ubiquitin ligases or E3 ubiquitin ligases) are enzymes that transfer |FRAME: Ubiquitins ubiquitin| from a ubiquitin-|FRAME: Ubiquitin-carrier-proteins-E2 E2| complex to the target protein that is to be ubiquitinated. The enzyme attaches the ubiquitin to a lysine residue on the target protein via an isopeptide bond.
/Since no ATP is required for this transfer operation, these enzymes are transferases and not ligases.
/
/E3 ubiquitin-carrier proteins are also involved in poly-ubiquitination, building poly-ubiquitin chains by adding a second ubiquitin to the first, a third to the second, and so forth.
/
/Chains can be added to different lysines on the ubiquitin molecule. Chains at different locations result in different fate for the ubiquitinated protein. For example, human proteins with chains of ubiquitin molecules connected via Lys48 are targeted to the proteasome for degradation, while proteins with chains of ubiquitin molecules connected via Lys63 seem to be important for DNA repair.
/
/E3 ubiquitin-transferases contain a domain for binding the E2-ubiquitin complex and a substrate-specific domain for binding the target protein. Many E2- and substrate-binding domains exist, and depending on these domains the E3 ubiquitin-transferases have been classified into several families. Common families include |FRAME: HECT-E3-ubiquitin-carrier-proteins HECT| (Homologous to the E6-AP Carboxyl Terminus) and |FRAME: RING-E3-ubiquitin-carrier-proteins RING| (Really Interesting New Gene).
//
