UNIQUE-ID - Q-Type-Peroxiredoxins
TYPES - Peroxiredoxins
COMMON-NAME - a BCP-PrxQ-type peroxiredoxin
COMMENT - BCP stands for “bacterioferritin comigratory protein,” and members of the BCP-PrxQ subfamily include the bacterial BCP proteins |CITS: [10644761]| and the plant PrxQ |CITS: [10998352]| proteins. These proteins are predominantly bacterial, although they are present in some eukaryotes including yeast and plants but excluding mammals |CITS: [21287625]|. 
/
/To date, the BCP-PrxQ subfamily contains the only Prx proteins shown to function as monomers (although there are two examples of dimeric members of this subfamily).
/
/BCP-PrxQ subfamily members can function as either atypical 2-Cys or 1-Cys |CITS: [17644813]|.
