UNIQUE-ID - Histones
TYPES - Polypeptides
COMMON-NAME - a histone
COMMENT - Histones are proteins found in the nuclei of eukaryotic cells that package and order the nuclear DNA into structural units called nucleosomes. The histones act as spools around which DNA can wind, and play an important role in gene regulation. For example, a human cell has about 1.8 meters of DNA, but when wound around histones, it is compacted into a structure of about 90  &mu;m.
/
/There are five major families of histones: H1, H2A, H2B, H3 and H4, all of which are involved in the formation of a single nucleosome. Two molecules each of H2A, H2B, H3 and H4 (also known as the core histones) assemble to form one octameric nucleosome core particle, around which the DNA wraps in a left-handed super-helical turn. A single molecule of histone H1 (known as the linker histone) then binds to the nucleosome, locking the DNA in place.
/
/Two higher-order structures involving multiple nucleosomes are formed -  a 30 nm fiber (forming an irregular zigzag) and a 100 nm fiber. The H1 histone also binds to the "linker DNA" (approximately 20-80 nucleotides in length) region between nucleosomes, helping stabilize the zig-zagged 30 nm fiber.
/
/The complex structure of multiple nucleosomes, including the histones and the DNA wrapped around them, is known as chromatin.
//
