UNIQUE-ID - pyruvate-phosphate-dikinase
TYPES - Polypeptides
COMMON-NAME - a pyruvate,phosphate dikinase
COMMENT - Pyruvate phosphate dikinase (PPDK) catalyzes the reversible conversion of phosphoenolpyruvate (PEP), AMP, and Pi to pyruvate and ATP.
/
/The enzyme contains two remotely located reaction centers: a nucleotide binding site at the N-terminal domain, and a PEP/pyruvate binding site at the C-terminal domain. A central domain contains a histidine residue that acts as a phosphoryl-binding intermediate. The crystal structure of the maize enzyme was determined at a resolution of 2.3 &Aring; and shows that the His domain is not sufficiently close to the binding sites for productive phosphoryl group transfer between PEP/pyruvate and the reactive histidine residue |CITS: [15667207]|. The transfer becomes available by a swiveling domain mechanism. The His domain can swivel around its linkers to adopt two two extreme conformational states |CITS: [18052212]|.
//
UNIQUE-ID - CBP-Calcium
TYPES - Modified-Proteins
TYPES - Polypeptides
COMMON-NAME - a Ca<sup>2+</sup>-loaded <i>apo</i>-[coelenterazine-binding protein]
COMMENT - The coelenterazine-binding protein was discovered in 1974 in the soft coral |FRAME: TAX-6136|. This crucial member of the bioluminescence system binds |FRAME: Coelenterazines coelenterazine| and protects it from auto oxidation. The protein has three Ca<sup>2+</sup>-binding sites. Upon an increase in the calcium ions concentration the protein binds three Ca<sup>2+</sup> ions, resulting in a structural shift and release of the coelenterazine, making it available for the |FRAME: EC-1.13.12.5| uciferase|. This discovery explained an earlier observation that light emission could be triggered by calcium |CITS: [4149963][33174][18385886][18655070]|.
//
