UNIQUE-ID - Oxidized-Putidaredoxins
TYPES - Putidaredoxins
TYPES - Modified-Proteins
TYPES - Polypeptides
COMMON-NAME - an oxidized putidaredoxin [iron-sulfur] cluster
COMMENT - Putidaredoxin (Pdx) is a 106-residue (11.6  kDa) ferredoxin that is produced in |FRAME: TAX-303| strains. It contains a |FRAME: CPD-6| and carries electrons from the flavoprotein putidaredoxin reductase (PdR) to the acceptor cytochrome CYP101, also known as P450cam because it catalyzes camphor hydroxylation. This NADH-supplied electron-transfer chain is one of the best studied of the P450 systems |CITS: [4383050]|. The structure of Pdx was determined by NMR methods |CITS: [8204575]|. The electronic properties and redox interactions of Pdx have been extensively studied |CITS: [1445875][8845752][8663375][9268300][10433692]|.
/Pdx carries one electron at a time, such that the two irons switch between [Fe3+, Fe3+] (oxidized) and [Fe2+, Fe3+] (reduced) states |CITS: [15103126]|.
//
UNIQUE-ID - Cre-C
TYPES - Polypeptides
//
UNIQUE-ID - NifB-with-K-cluster
TYPES - Polypeptides
TYPES - Modified-Proteins
COMMON-NAME - a NifB protein with a K-cluster
COMMENT - NifB is a protein involved in the biosynthesis of the |FRAME: CPD-41| of [MoFe]-nitrogenases, and contains the CX<sub>3</sub>CX<sub>2</sub>C motif characteristic of the radical SAM superfamily. Sequence analysis suggested that in addition to a radical SAM [4Fe-4S] cluster, NifB contains two other |FRAME: CPD-7 "[4Fe-4S] iron-sulfur clusters"|. It is now known to catalyze the condensation of these two clusters into a single |FRAME: CPD-18407|, inserting a carbide atom at the center of the molecule |CITS: [23019652][25477518]|.
/
/Early attempts at characterizing a His-tagged form of NifB from |FRAME: TAX-354| were unsuccessful due to the extreme instability of NifB in aqueous solutions. The problem was circumvented by creating a fusion between NifB and NifN, resulting in successful isolation of a NifE(N-B) complex |CITS: [21551100]|. It should be noted that such a fusion occurs naturally in the bactrerium |FRAME: TAX-1501|.
/
/The NifE(N-B) complex was fully active as a |FRAME: CPD-41| donor for a cofactor-deficient MoFe protein (the dinitrogenase component of [MoFe]-nitrogenase enzymes). Metal, activity, ultraviolet/visible (UV/vis), and electron paramagnetic resonance (EPR) analyses established the presence of two transient clusters, designated K-cluster and |FRAME: CPD-18407|, respectively, on the NifEN-B fusion protein. The K-cluster was found to consist of a pair of [4Fe-4S] clusters, while the L-cluster is a [8Fe-9S-C] cluster |CITS: [16423898][21726031][21212358]|.
/
/The fusion protein was overexpressed in |FRAME: TAX-354| in the presence of all accessory proteins except the nitrogenase components (NifH and NifDK). In the absence of |FRAME: S-ADENOSYLMETHIONINE| cluster maturation was halted at the NifB state. Upon addition of |FRAME: S-ADENOSYLMETHIONINE|, the EPR signal of [4Fe-4S] clusters was replaced by the signal of the [8Fe-9S-C] cluster. In addition, both both |FRAME: CH33ADO| and |FRAME: ADENOSYL-HOMO-CYS| were formed during the reaction. Thus, it has been established that NifB utilizes two molecules of |FRAME: S-ADENOSYLMETHIONINE|. One is used to generate a |FRAME: CPD-15400| that activates the substrate by abstraction of a hydrogen atom, while the second is used as the source of the carbide atom that is inserted into the cluster |CITS: [16423898][21726031][21212358]|.
/
/The carbon atom insertion is concomitant with incorporation of a sulfide of unknown origin that bridges the two clusters, as well as rearrangement of the two clusters. Both processes are not yet understood |CITS: [25477518]|.
//
UNIQUE-ID - Glycerolipids
