UNIQUE-ID - Nucleotides
TYPES - All-Nucleosides
COMMON-NAME - a nucleotide
SYNONYMS - nucleotide
SYNONYMS - a nucleoside phosphate
COMMENT - A nucleotide is composed of |FRAME: Bases| (nitrogenous base), a five-carbon sugar (either |FRAME: CPD0-1110 ribose| or |FRAME: 2-DEOXYRIBOSE|), and one to three phosphate groups attached to one of the carbons of the ribose or deoxyribose moiety. When joined together, nucleotides make up the structural units of RNA and DNA.
/The nucleotides are called |FRAME: Ribonucleotides| when the sugar is |FRAME: CPD0-1110 ribose|, and |FRAME: Deoxynucleotides| when it is |FRAME: 2-DEOXYRIBOSE|.
/
/In the absence of phosphate, the combination of |FRAME: Bases| (nitrogenous base) and a five-carbon sugar is called |FRAME: Nucleosides|.
