TYPES - Polypeptides
TYPES - Modified-Proteins
COMMON-NAME - a [HypE hydrogenase maturation protein]-<i>S</i>-cyanyl-L-cysteine
COMMENT - HypE is one of the hydrogenase maturation proteins required for the assembly of the CN ligand of the NiFe metal center of [NiFe]-hydrogenases.  
/
/At least seven gene products are involved in the maturation of hydrogenases in |FRAME: TAX-562|, which includes the generation and incorporation of the CN ligand from |FRAME: CARBAMOYL-P|. The generation of these ligands starts with activation of |FRAME: CARBAMOYL-P| to |FRAME: CPD-15424| by HypF, at the expense of ATP |CITS: [12377778]|. HypF then forms a tight stoichiometric complex with HypE |CITS: [15291820]| and transfers the carbamoyl group to the HypE carboxy terminal cysteine |CITS: [12586941]|. HypE then catalyzes the ATP hydrolysis-dependent dehydration of the carbamate group to a cyanate group |CITS: [15291820][12586941],| which is transferred to the iron of the nascent cofactor carried by the |FRAME: HypCD-Dimer-Fe-CO "HypC-HypD complex"| |CITS: [15504408][18065529]|. Two cyanate ligands are transferred from HypE to the nascent cofactor, though the exact details of the transfer are still not known.
/
/HypE forms a homodimer via a disulfide bridge formed by the C-terminal cysteine residue |CITS: [15291820]|. The dimeric structure is stabilized by a pseudo-&beta;-barrel formed by interactions between the domain A from each protomer. The HypE dimer forms a ternary structure with two molecules of the |FRAME: HypCD-Dimer "HypC/HypD heterodimer"|, with the two HypCD complexes attaching to the two side faces of the HypE dimer |CITS: [32227866]|. The HypCDE ternary complex formation causes the HypE C-terminal tail to adopt an outward conformation, which is favorable for the cyano group transfer |CITS: [32227866]|.
ABBREV-NAME - [HypE]-<i>S</i>-cyanate
//
