UNIQUE-ID - RPL3
TYPES - Polypeptides
COMMON-NAME - a ribosomal protein L3
SYNONYMS - RPL3
COMMENT - Ribosomal protein L3 is one of the proteins that make up the large 60S subunit of eukaryotes and 50S subunit of prokaryotes. The protein belongs to the L3P family of ribosomal proteins and is located in the cytoplasm.
/
/
/The human protein can bind to the HIV-1 TAR mRNA, and it has been suggested that it contributes to the transactivation mediated by the HIV Tat protein.
//
UNIQUE-ID - CRPB-all-trans-Retinol
TYPES - Modified-Proteins
COMMON-NAME - an <i>all-trans</i> retinol-[cellular-retinol-binding-protein]
COMMENT - Retinoid-binding proteins are carriers of various forms of vitamin A in body fluids and within the cell.
/The sequestration of retinoids inside a high-affinity binding-protein draws them into the cell and protects them from unfettered metabolism |CITS: [9932510][7683727]|.
/
/X-ray structures of retinoid-binding proteins have shown that bound retinol is sandwiched inside a 10-stranded, anti-parallel &beta;-barrel with the alcohol moiety situated innermost and in close contact with a glutamine side chain, forming a hydrogen bond. The bound retinol has a 6-<i>S</i>-trans conformation |CITS: [7683727][8487303][8839926]|.
//
UNIQUE-ID - Excited-GFP
TYPES - Modified-Proteins
TYPES - Polypeptides
COMMON-NAME - an excited state green fluorescent protein
SYNONYMS - GFP*
COMMENT - Green fluorescent proteins (GFPs) are proteins that exhibit bright green fluorescence when exposed to light in the blue to ultraviolet range. GFPs form a part of the bioluminesence systems of many marine organisms. 
/
/The protein was first described from the jellyfish |FRAME: TAX-6100| |CITS: [13911999]|, from which it was eventually purified |CITS: [4151620]|. In this organism GFP is coupled to the aequorin enzyme, which catalyzes a reaction that forms |FRAME: CPD-20235|. This compound can emit blue light, which can then trigger fluorescence by GFP. However, due to coupling between aequorin and GFP, the short distance enbales <A href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F%C3%B6rster_resonance_energy_transfer">F&ouml;rster resonance energy transfer</A> (FRET), a much more efficient energy-transfer process |CITS: [4397528][4151620]|. A similar situation occurs in the soft coral |FRAME: TAX-6136|, where GFP interacts with the luciferase enzyme |CITS: [33175]|.
/
/GFP has become an extremely useful tool in cell and molecular biology, where it is used as an <i>in situ</i> reporter of expression. The scientists Roger Y. Tsien, Osamu Shimomura, and Martin Chalfie were awarded the 2008 Nobel Prize in Chemistry for their discovery and development of the green fluorescent protein.
//
