UNIQUE-ID - Alpha-Allophycocyanins-PCB84
TYPES - Polypeptides
TYPES - Modified-Proteins
COMMON-NAME - an [allophycocyanin &alpha;-subunit]-Cys<sup>84</sup>-phycocyanobilin
SYNONYMS - a [allophycocyanin &alpha;-subunit-Cys84]-PCB
COMMENT - |FRAME: Phycoerythrocyanins Phycoerythrocyanins| are members of the |FRAME: Phycobiliproteins phycobiliproteins|, which are components of the photosynthetic light-harvesting antenna complexes of |FRAME: TAX-1117| and some algae (|FRAME: TAX-2763 rhodophytes|, |FRAME: TAX-3027 cryptomonads|, and |FRAME: TAX-38254 glaucocystophytes|) that capture light energy and pass it on to |FRAME: Chlorophylls chlorophylls| during photosynthesis. They increase the efficiency of photosynthesis by collecting light energy at wavelengths over which chlorophyll absorbs poorly.
/
/Allophycocyanins, which are found in in cyanobacteria and red algae, have a characteristic blue color, and absorb red light around 650 nm. Like other |FRAME: Phycobiliproteins phycobiliproteins| allophycocyanins are composed of two different types of subunits, forming an (&alpha;&beta;)<sub>6</sub> structure. Both subunits covalently bind a single |FRAME: Phycocyanobilins phycocyanobilin| chromophore to a cysteine residue at position 84 |CITS: [7783202]|.
/
/
/Attachment of the |FRAME: Phycocyanobilins phycocyanobilin| chromophore to the Cys-84 position of both the &alpha; and &beta; subunits of |FRAME: Allophycocyanins allophycocyanin| is catalyzed by the |FRAME: MONOMER-18986 "CpcS lyase"| |CITS: [17895251]|.
//
UNIQUE-ID - Release-factors
TYPES - Polypeptides
COMMON-NAME - a release factor
SYNONYMS - peptide chain release factor
COMMENT - A release factor is a protein that allows for the termination of translation by recognizing the termination codon or stop codon in an mRNA sequence.
/
/In the standard genetic code, there are three mRNA stop codons: UAG (amber), UAA (ochre), and UGA (opal).
/
/Prokaryotes have two release factors that recognize different stop codons: RF1 recognizes the termination codons UAA and UAG, while RF2 recognizes UAA and UGA.
/
/Eukaryotes have only a single release factor, eRF1, that recognizes all three termination codons.
/
/A different, GTP-binding protein (RF3 in prokaryotes and eRF3 in eukaryotes) promotes the dissociation of the release factors from the polypeptide following the release of the polypeptide-release factor complex from the ribosome.
//
UNIQUE-ID - auxiliary-transport-proteins
TYPES - PC-1
COMMON-NAME - an auxiliary transport protein
COMMENT - Encompasses Family 8.A in the IUBMB classification of membrane transport proteins and in the Transporter Classification Database (TCDB) |CITS: [24225317]|.<BR>Also included are proteins from the TCDB superfamily 1.A.30: H+- or Na+-translocating Bacterial Flagellar Motor/ExbBD Outer Membrane Transport Energizers (Mot-Exb) and TCDB family 2.C.1:  TonB-ExbB-ExbD/TolA-TolQ-TolR (TonB) Family of Auxiliary Proteins for Energization of Outer Membrane Receptor (OMR)-mediated Active Transport
//
