UNIQUE-ID - TUM1
TYPES - Polypeptides
COMMON-NAME - a 3-mercaptopyruvate sulfurtransferase
SYNONYMS - an MPST sulfurtransferase
SYNONYMS - a TUM1 sulfurtransferase
COMMENT - 3-Mercaptopyruvate sulfurtransferase (TUM1, MPST, tRNA thiouridin modification protein 1) belongs to an enzyme superfamily of proteins that contain a rhodanese-like domain.
/
/The enzyme was initially found to catalyze the reaction of |FRAME: EC-2.8.1.2|. During this reaction the enzyme catalyzes a transsulfuration of |FRAME: 3-MERCAPTO-PYRUVATE| |CITS: [16107337]|, forming |FRAME: PYRUVATE| and an enzyme-bound persulfide, which can be released as H<sub>2</sub>S in the presence of reducing systems like GSH or thioredoxin |CITS: [21732914]|.
/
/In addition to that function, the enzyme was reported to mediate the transfer of sulfur from the NFS1 L-cysteine desulfurase to other sulfurtransferase (Uba4p in yeast and MOCS3 in humans), as part of a sulfur relay chain that is responsible for the 2-thiolation of certain tRNAs in the cytosol |CITS: [19151091]|.
/
/Deficiencies of |FRAME: HS05177-MONOMER| cause mercaptolactate-cysteine disulfiduria characterized by the presence of &beta;-mercaptolactate-cysteine disulfide in the urine |CITS: [4690911]|. The disease has been associated with mental retardation |CITS: [4973015]|.
