UNIQUE-ID - Sulfatases
TYPES - Polypeptides
COMMON-NAME - a sulfatase
COMMENT - Sulfatases are enzymes of the esterase class that catalyze the hydrolysis of sulfate esters.
/Different types of sulfatases act on different ranges of substrates, including aromatic compounds, steroids, carbohydrates and proteins. Many types of sulfatases received their EC number, including |FRAME: EC-3.1.6.1|, |FRAME: EC-3.1.6.1|, |FRAME: EC-3.1.6.2|, |FRAME: EC-3.1.6.4|, |FRAME: EC-3.1.6.8|, |FRAME: EC-3.1.6.12|, |FRAME: EC-3.1.6.13|, and |FRAME: EC-3.10.1.1| (the latter acts on a sulfur-nitrogen bond).
/
/Sulfatases play important roles in the cycling of sulfur in the environment, in the degradation of sulfated glycosaminoglycans and glycolipids in the lysosome, and in remodelling sulfated glycosaminoglycans in the extracellular space.
/
/All eukaryotic sulfatases contain a highly conserved hexapeptide L/V-FGly-X-P-S-R, which is found in the N-terminal region. The X residue contains a hydroxyl or thiol group, while formylglycine (FGly, also known as |FRAME: 2-AMINOMALONATE-SEMIALDEHYDE|) is a unique modification of an L-cysteine residue |CITS: [9342345]|.
//
UNIQUE-ID - Oxidized-Rubredoxins
TYPES - Modified-Proteins
TYPES - Rubredoxins
COMMON-NAME - an oxidized rubredoxin
COMMENT - Rubredoxins are found in some bacteria and archaea. Unlike |FRAME: FeS-Proteins "iron-sulfur (Fe-S) proteins"|, rubredoxins do not contain inorganic sulfide. Instead they contain a mononuclear thiolate complex [Fe(Cys)<sub>4</sub>]<sup>2-</sup>. Rubredoxins participate in electron transfer in biological systems, and transfer a single electron. During the process, the central iron atom changes between the +2 and +3 oxidation states.
/
/The reduction potential of a rubredoxin is typically in the range +50 mV to -50 mV.
//
