UNIQUE-ID - Melleolides
TYPES - Antibiotics
COMMON-NAME - a melleolide
COMMENT - The |FRAME: Melleolides melleolides| are a large family of aryl ester secondary metabolites produced by species of the basidiomycete genus |FRAME: TAX-47424|, which are composed of an |FRAME: CPD-47| moiety esterified to a tricyclic sesquiterpene (|FRAME: CPD-14796|) alcohol |CITS: [Midland82][Donnelly82]|. Both |FRAME: CPD-47| and protoilludane derivatives have been described from numerous other organisms |CITS: [11281843][12714063][19666480]|, but these two elements are combined into a single entity only in the melleolides, which are not found outside the |FRAME: TAX-47424|. 
/
/Biosynthesis of the sesquiterpene protoilludene moiety is achieved by cyclization of |FRAME: FARNESYL-PP|, catalyzed
/by |FRAME: EC-4.2.3.135|, and results in the tricyclic |FRAME: CPD-14796| backbone |CITS: [21148562]|. In |FRAME: TAX-47429|, |FRAME: CPD-47| is biosynthesized by a seven-domain polyketide synthase whose terminal thioesterase domain also catalyzes the coupling of |FRAME: CPD-47| to protoilludene-based alcohols |CITS: [23993460]|. Modifications of the basic structure include hydroxylation at various positions of the sesquiterpene, oxidation of the primary alcohol at C-1 to an aldehyde or carboxy group, shift or reduction of the cyclohexene double bond, methyl ether formation at O-5', and chlorination at C-6' |CITS: [26655762]|, resulting in excess of 60 melleolide analogs and making the melleolides one of the most diverse groups of fungal natural products |CITS: [Misiek12]|.
/
/Various melleolides have been shown to inhibit microbial growth |CITS: [Arnone86][10805573]| and display phytotoxicity |CITS: [1418682]|.  The antifungal activity has been linked to the position of the double bond within the sesquiterpene moiety |CITS: [24906293]|. Melleolides have also been reported to have cytotoxic effects on human cancer cell lines by decreasing DNA synthesis |CITS: [21376582]|.
//
UNIQUE-ID - Corphins
TYPES - Macrocycles
COMMON-NAME - a corphin
//
UNIQUE-ID - HypE-Proteins
TYPES - Polypeptides
COMMON-NAME - a HypE [NiFe]-hydrogenase maturation protein
COMMENT - HypE is one of the hydrogenase maturation proteins required for the assembly of the CN ligand of the |FRAME: CPD-24862| of |FRAME: NiFe-hydrogenases "[NiFe]-hydrogenases"|.  
/
/At least seven gene products are involved in the maturation of hydrogenases in |FRAME: TAX-562|, which includes the generation and incorporation of the CN ligand from |FRAME: CARBAMOYL-P| (CP). First, HypF converts CP and ATP to |FRAME: CPD-15424|, inorganic phosphate, pyrophosphate, and AMP |CITS: [12377778]|. It then transfers the carbamoyl group to the carboxy terminal cysteine of HypE |CITS: [12586941]|. During the carbamoyl transfer reaction, HypE and HypF form a tight stoichiometric complex |CITS: [15291820]|. HypE then catalyzes the ATP hydrolysis-dependent dehydration of the carbamate group to a cyanate group |CITS: [15291820][12586941]| which is transferred to the HypC-HypD complex |CITS: [15504408]| and from there to the hydrogenase.
/
/Purified HypE displays low intrinsic ATPase activity |CITS: [15291820]|.  crystal structure of apo-HypE from <i>E. coli</i> O157:H7 has been solved at 2 &Aring; resolution, and a reaction mechanism has been proposed |CITS: [18065529]|. HypE forms a homodimer via a disulfide bridge formed by the C-terminal cysteine residue |CITS: [15291820]|. The dimeric structure is stabilized by a pseudo-&beta;-barrel formed by interactions between the domain A from each protomer. The HypE dimer forms a ternary structure with two molecules of the |FRAME: HypCD-Dimer "HypC/HypD heterodimer"|, with the two HypCD complexes attaching to both side faces of the HypE dimer |CITS: [32227866]|. The HypCDE ternary complex formation causes the HypE C-terminal tail to adopt an outward conformation, which is favorable for the cyanide transfer |CITS: [32227866]|. It is still not known how exactly is a second cyano group transferred from HypE to the cofactor precursor.
ABBREV-NAME - HypE protein
//
UNIQUE-ID - Evg-A
TYPES - Polypeptides
//
UNIQUE-ID - apo-malonate-decarboxylases
TYPES - Protein-Complexes
COMMON-NAME - [an <i>apo</i> malonate decarboxylase acyl-carrier protein]
COMMENT - Several strains of bacteria are able to utilize malonate as sole source of carbon and energy. The key reaction in the pathway is the decarboxylation of malonate to acetate, which is catalyzed by malonate decarboxylase. Malonate is a rather inert compound, and its decarboxylation under physiological conditions requires an activation step, in which malonate forms a thioester derivative.
/
/Malonate decarboxylase is an enzyme complex composed of three subunits, one of which is a dedicated acyl-carrier protein (acp). The acp protein is synthesized in an <i>apo</i> form, and is converted to its <i>holo</i> form by the covalent binding of the prosthetic group |FRAME: 2-5-PHOSPHORIBOSYL-3-DEPHOSPHO-COA| to a serine residue. This prosthetic group is very unusual and the only other enzyme known to use it is |FRAME: ACECITLY-CPLX| (see |FRAME: P2-PWY|).
ABBREV-NAME - [a malonate decarboxylase acyl-carrier protein]
//
