UNIQUE-ID - DNA-containing-abasic-Sites
TYPES - DNA-N
COMMON-NAME - a DNA containing an apurinic/apyrimidinic site
SYNONYMS - DNA containing an apurinic/apyrimidinic site
SYNONYMS - a DNA containing an apurinic/apyrimidinic site
SYNONYMS - an AP (apurinic or apyrimidinic) site
SYNONYMS - a DNA containing an abasic site
SYNONYMS - a DNA containing an AP site
COMMENT - An AP site (apurinic/apyrimidinic site), also known as an abasic site, is a location in DNA where a base (either a purine or a pyrimidine)  is missing, but the phosphodiester backbone of the DNA is still intact.
/
/AP sites can occur either spontaneously or due to DNA damage. It has been estimated that up to 10,000 apurinic sites may be generated in a cell each day |CITS: [2676144]|.
/
/AP sites are generated as intermediates during the DNA repair process known as base excision repair. The first step in that process is the cleavage of the damaged base by a DNA glycosylase, leaving an AP site.
//
UNIQUE-ID - 30S-ribosomal-subunit-protein-S5
TYPES - Polypeptides
COMMON-NAME - a 30S ribosomal subunit protein S5
COMMENT - The S5 protein is a component of the 30S subunit of the ribosome.  It was suggested that S5 is positioned to have access to the interface between the 30S and 50S subunits of the ribosome |CITS: [9973556]|.
/
/The N-terminal half of S5 contains the sites of mutations that confer resistance to spectinomycin |CITS: [129673][4904980][4273819]| and binds non-specifically to helix 34 of the 16S rRNA |CITS: [8658142][2459389]|.  S5 may be involved in modulating the conformation of the 16S rRNA |CITS: [9271564]|.  S5 can be cross-linked to mRNA |CITS: [1712292]| and tRNA |CITS: [2660905]|.
/
/The S5 protein is acetylated at the N-terminus |CITS: [363452][10094780]|; mutants in the alanine acetyltransferase enzyme, |FRAME: EG10851-MONOMER RimJ|, are temperature sensitive |CITS: [385889][2828880]|.  N-terminal acetylation of S5 and S18 correlates with correct folding of the platform and central pseudoknot domains of 16S rRNA |CITS: [24207057]|.  An S5 G28D mutant shows altered cell growth, folding of 16S rRNA, and translational fidelity |CITS: [17053085]|.  The G28D mutant has a defect in 16S rRNA maturation |CITS: [20176963]|; overexpression of RimJ, even when lacking its acetyltransferase activity, suppresses this defect |CITS: [18466225][20176963]|.
/
/S5 influences translational fidelity.  Certain mutations in <i>rpsE</i> confer a "ribosomal ambiguity" (ram) phenotype, which is characterized by decreased growth rate, increased streptomycin sensitivity, and increased errors in translation |CITS: [4589342][4589343][1105158]|.  Many ram mutations map to the interface between S4 and S5; additional <i>rpsE</i> mutants were isolated in a random mutagenesis screen |CITS: [25548247]|.
/
/<i>spcA</i>: "spectinomycin"
/
//
