UNIQUE-ID - Lovastatin-nonaketide-synthase
TYPES - Polypeptides
COMMON-NAME - lovastatin nonaketide synthase
SYNONYMS - LovB
SYNONYMS - LNKS
COMMENT - |FRAME: CPD-5561 Lovastatin| is a polyketide produced by the fungus |FRAME: TAX-33178|. It is widely prescribed (along with the semisynthetic derivative |FRAME: CPD66-17|) as a hypercholesterolemia drug because of its inhibitory activity towards |FRAME: EC-1.1.1.34| (HMGR).
/
/Two highly reducing iterative type I polyketide synthases play central roles in the biosynthesis of lovastatin acid. The lovastatin nonaketide synthase (LNKS or LovB), together with the dissociated enoylreductase LovC, are responsible for the 
/assembly of |FRAME: CPD-16907|, a key intermediate in the process. This intermediate is then modified by the cytochrome P450 monooxygenase LovA through hydroxylation and dehydration to produce |FRAME: CPD-16905|, which is then hydroxylated at C-8 by the same enzyme to produce |FRAME: CPD-16908|.
/
/The process is finalyzed by the synthesis of the &alpha;-methylbutyryl side chain (catalyzed by the lovastatin diketide synthase (LDKS or LovF)) and its transfer to the C-8 hydroxy group of monacolin J acid by the acyl transferase LovD.
//
