UNIQUE-ID - RNA-3-phosphate-cyclase
TYPES - Polypeptides
COMMON-NAME - an RNA 3&prime;-terminal-phosphate cyclase
COMMENT - RNA 3&prime;-terminal-phosphate cyclases are enzymes that recognize a 3' terminal phosphate group in RNAs and convert it to a cyclic 2',3' cyclophosphate.
/
/Two types of the enzyme are known, an ATP-dependent enzyme (|FRAME: EC-6.5.1.4|) and a GTP-dependent enzyme (|FRAME: EC-6.5.1.5|).
/
/The reaction proceeds in three steps:
/
/1. Adenylation of a lysine residue in the active center of the enzyme, with the concomitant release of pyrophosphate
/
/2. Transfer of the adenylate/guanylate group to the 3' phosphate group of the substrate, forming a [RNA]-(ribonucleotide)-3'-A-5'-pp cap.
/
/3. An attack by the 2'-hydroxyl group on the (ribonucleotide)-3'-A-5'-pp cap, leading to release of the adenylate/guanylate and formation of the cyclic phosphate.
ABBREV-NAME - RNA 3&prime;-phosphate cyclase
//
