TYPES - Active-2-Hydroxyacyl-CoA-Dehydratases
COMMON-NAME - a lactoyl-CoA dehydratase
COMMENT - |FRAME: EC-4.2.1.54|, is a |FRAME: PWY-5494 "propionate fermentation pathway"| enzyme that belongs to the (<i>R</i>)-2-hydroxyacyl-CoA dehydratase family.
/
/Members of this family are two-component systems composed of an extremely oxygen-sensitive activator (component A) and a dehydratase (component D). Component A is a homodimer with one [4Fe&ndash;4S] cluster bound in the dimer interface, while component D is a heterodimer with 1-2 [4Fe&ndash;4S] clusters and FMN. In order to catalyze the reaction, the dehydratase requires one high-energy electron that transiently reduces the electrophilic thiol ester carbonyl to a nucleophilic ketyl radical anion, facilitating the elimination of the hydroxyl group. The electron needs to be supplied only once, before the first reaction takes place, since it is regenerated at the end of each reaction cycle. This initial activation is provided by the activator. 
/
/The activator, which has been named |FRAME: CPLX-9330 archerase| because its open position resembles an archer shooting arrows, binds two ADP molecules. Upon the reduction of its [4Fe&ndash;4S] cluster by a single electron, delivered by a dedicated flavodoxin, the two ADP molecules exchange for two ATP molecules, resulting in a large conformational change. The change results in the activator binding to the dehydratase component, upon which the two ATP molecules are hydrolyzed and the electron is transferred to the dehydratase, activating it |CITS: [15374661][18337824]|.
/
/The structure shown here depicts the reduced [4Fe&ndash;4S] cluster.
//
