UNIQUE-ID - URM1
TYPES - Sulfur-Carriers-Gly-Gly
COMMON-NAME - a ubiquitin-related modifier 1
COMMENT - The ubiquitin-related modifier 1 protein (|FRAME: HS15524|) is a small protein that acts as a sulfur carrier during the thiolation event leading to |FRAME: CPD-19978| (mcm<sup>5</sup>s<sup>2</sup>U) at tRNA wobble positions of cytosolic tRNA(Lys), tRNA(Glu) and tRNA(Gln). Like ubiquitin, the C-terminus of the protein ends with two glycine residues, and can be adenylated and sulfurated by the |FRAME: HS04742| sulfurtransferase. Sulfuration forms a C-terminal thiocarboxylate group, which serves as the sulfur donor for the tRNAs |CITS: [19017811][19145231]|.
/
/URM1 also acts as a ubiquitin-like protein (UBL) and is covalently conjugated via an isopeptide bond to lysine residues of certain target proteins in a process that is called urmylation. Documented target proteins include |FRAME: HS04742|, |FRAME: HS06936|, |FRAME: G-55129|, USP15, CAS, and peroxiredoxin Ahp1 |CITS: [21209336]|. However, URM1 differs from canonical ubiquitin family members in that the formation of the thiocarboxylate group appears to be crucial not only for sulfur transfer reactions, but also for protein urmylation |CITS: [28357324]|. The mechanism by which the thiocarboxylated URM1 protein is transferred to its target protein is not known yet.
/
/The URM1 protein and its activities are conserved from yeast to man |CITS: [25747390]|
//
