UNIQUE-ID - TtuB-Sulfur-carrier-proteins
TYPES - Sulfur-Carriers-Gly-Gly
COMMON-NAME - a TtuB sulfur-carrier protein
COMMENT - TtuB is a small sulfur-carrier protein, similar to |FRAME: G1 ThiS| and |FRAME: EG11597 MoaD|. The protein participates in the biosynthesis of tRNA thiouridine at position 54 of tRNAs of some thermophilic organisms such as |FRAME: TAX-274| and |FRAME: TAX-2261| |CITS: [4369142][16547008]|.
/
/This type of proteins contains a double glycine motif at the C terminus. The free carboxylate group of the terminal glycine is activated by an accessory protein (in this case TtuC) to a carboxy-adenylate form, which is then sulfurylated by a sulfurase, resulting in a thiocarboxylate. Another enzyme, TtuA, then transfers the sulfur to the uracil at position 54 of the tRNA |CITS: [23444054]|.
