UNIQUE-ID - Alpha-factor
TYPES - Modified-Peptides
COMMON-NAME - an &alpha; factor
SYNONYMS - <i>Saccharomyces cerevisiae</i> mating pheromon &alpha; factor
COMMENT - Mating in |FRAME: TAX-4932| results from the fusion of two haploid cells of opposite mating type, a and &alpha;, to
/form a diploid. The mating pheromones, |FRAME: CPD-10692| and |FRAME: Alpha-factor|, produced by a and &alpha; haploid cells, respectively, stimulate receptors on cells of the opposite mating type to initiate responses that lead to cell fusion.
/
/The molecular structure of the &alpha; factor has been investigated.
/Four different oligopeptides exhibiting &alpha; factor activity have been isolated |CITS: [776628]|.
/These peptides, designated as &alpha;1, &alpha;2, &alpha;3, and &alpha;4 are structurally closely related, being
/composed of thirteen (&alpha;1 and &alpha;3) or twelve (&alpha;2 and &alpha;4) amino acids, respectively.
/The &alpha;3 and &alpha;4 peptides are oxidation products, containing an internal |FRAME: L-Methionine-sulfoxides| instead of |FRAME: MET|.
/
/The peptides were found to be composed of the following amino acids: 2 glutamate or glutamine, 2 proline, 1 glycine,
/methionine or methionine sulfoxide, 2 leucine, 1 tyrosine, 1 lysine, 1 histidine, 1 or 2 tryptophan.
/
/|FRAME: TYR| is the C-terminal amino acid in all four peptides. The tridekapeptides differ from the dodekapeptides by an
/additional N-terminal |FRAME: TRP| residue.
//
