TYPES - Acylated-Amino-Acid-Lipids
COMMON-NAME - an <i>N</i>,<i>N</i>-dimethylornithine lipid
COMMENT - Ornithine lipids are phosphorus-free membrane lipids that are widespread in bacteria but absent from archaea and eukaryotes. They  comprise of |FRAME: LYSO-ORNITHINE-LIPIDS| with a second fatty acyl group ester-linked to the 3-hydroxy position of the first fatty acyl group (reviewed in |CITS: [19703488]|). The composition of the amide-linked (R1) and ester-linked (R2) fatty acids in ornithine lipids varies among bacterial species |CITS: [6315433][3409887][3030307][16856942]|. In addition, ornithine lipids are often modified by hydroxylation and methylation at different positions |CITS: [21707055][21205018][25404698][25925947]|.
//
