UNIQUE-ID - Demethylated-methyl-acceptors
TYPES - Methyl-Acceptors
COMMON-NAME - a demethylated methyl donor
SYNONYMS - a demethylated methyl acceptor
SYNONYMS - a demethylated methyl donor
COMMENT - |FRAME: Methyl-Acceptors "A methyl group donor"| is a compound that can donate a methyl group to another compound in a reaction catalyzed by enzymes that belong to the |FRAME: EC-2.1.1 methyltransferase group"|.
/Prior to donating the methyl group the compound is |FRAME: Methylated-methyl-acceptors| and after donating it the compound is |FRAME: Demethylated-methyl-acceptors|.
/
/Since methylation reactions are sometimes reversible, the distinction between a methyl group donor and a methyl group acceptor is not always determined by the actual chemical entity, but by the role it plays in a particular reaction. However, some compounds are often used as methyl group donors by the methyltransferases in reactions that are physiologically unidirectional.
/
/By far, the most common methyl group donor in biology is |FRAME: S-ADENOSYLMETHIONINE|. However, other methyl donors exist, including |FRAME: METOH|, |FRAME: 5-METHYL-THF-GLU-N "<i>N</i><sup>5</sup>-methyl tetrahydrofolate"|, |FRAME: METHYL-THMPT|, |FRAME: METHYLAMINE|, |FRAME: DIMETHYLAMINE|, |FRAME: TRIMETHYLAMINE|, and |FRAME: CPD-7671|.
/
/This particular entry is used when the identity of the methyl group donor (or acceptor) is not known or cannot be defined.
//
