UNIQUE-ID - 15-E-alpha-Phycoerythrocyanins
TYPES - alpha-Phycoerythrocyanins
COMMON-NAME - a [phycoerythrocyanin &alpha;-subunit]-Cys<sup>84</sup>-(15<i>E</i>)-phycoviolobilin
SYNONYMS - PecA
COMMENT - |FRAME: Phycoerythrocyanins Phycoerythrocyanins| are members of the |FRAME: Phycobiliproteins phycobiliproteins|, which are components of the photosynthetic light-harvesting antenna complexes of |FRAME: TAX-1117| and some algae (|FRAME: TAX-2763 rhodophytes|, |FRAME: TAX-3027 cryptomonads|, and |FRAME: TAX-38254 glaucocystophytes|) that capture light energy and pass it on to |FRAME: Chlorophylls chlorophylls| during photosynthesis. They increase the efficiency of photosynthesis by collecting light energy at wavelengths over which chlorophyll absorbs poorly.
/
/Phycoerythrocyanins, which are found in in some cyanobacteria, have a characteristic magenta color, and an absorption maximum around 575 nm. Like other |FRAME: Phycobiliproteins phycobiliproteins|, they are composed from two types of subunits. The &alpha; chain (encoded by the <i>pecA</i> gene) contains one molecule of the violet chromophore |FRAME: Phycoviolobilins phycoviolobilin|, which is covalently attached at Cys-84, and the &beta; subunit (encoded by the <i>pecB</i> gene) contains two molecules of the blue chromophore |FRAME: Phycocyanobilins phycocyanobilin|, which are covalently attached at Cys-84 and -155, respectively.
/
/Free |FRAME: Phycoviolobilins phycoviolobilin| does not seem to exist. Studies have shown that the |FRAME: CPLX-8936| enzyme is bifunctional, and catalyzes the attachment of free |FRAME: CPD-17222| to the &alpha; subunit of |FRAME: Phycoerythrocyanins phycoerythrocyanin| (PecA) followed by its isomerization to |FRAME: Phycoviolobilins phycoviolobilin| |CITS: [10708746][19182270]|.
/
/|FRAME: Phycoviolobilins Phycoviolobilin| is formed in a |FRAME: 15-Z-alpha-Phycoerythrocyanins " (15<i>Z</i>)"| isomeric configuration. Upon absorbing light at 570 nm it is coverted to a |FRAME: 15-E-alpha-Phycoerythrocyanins "(15<i>E</i>)"| form. The 15<i>Z</i> form is restored when the excited 15<i>E</i> isomer emits a photon at 500 nm |CITS: [Zhao95]|.
//
