UNIQUE-ID - Ferrihemoglobins
TYPES - Hemoglobins
COMMON-NAME - a ferrihemoglobin
SYNONYMS - metHb
SYNONYMS - a methemoglobin
COMMENT - |FRAME: Ferrihemoglobins "Ferrihemoglobin"| (also known as methemoglobin) is form of |FRAME: Hemoglobins "hemoglobin"| in which the iron in the heme group is in the Fe<sup>III</sup> (ferric) state.
/
/The iron of the |FRAME: Heme-b| group is bound covalently to the globular protein via the imidazole ring of a histidine residue (known as the proximal histidine) below the porphyrin ring (as is shown in the image). A sixth position of the iron can reversibly bind oxygen by a coordinate covalent bond, but only when the iron is in the ferrous (II) state.
/
/When oxygen is bound, it is in an "end-on bent" geometry where one oxygen atom binds the Fe atom and the other protrudes at an angle. When oxygen is not bound, a very weakly bonded water molecule fills the site, forming a distorted octahedron.
/
/Methemoglobin cannot bind oxygen. When formed in blood, it is converted back to |FRAME: Ferrohemoglobins| by the enzyme |FRAME: EC-1.6.2.2| (CYB5R1, CYB5R3).
