COMMENT - The pathways for methanogenesis from methylated C1 compounds follow a similar route. Methyl transfer from the electron acceptor to |FRAME: CoM| is carried out by enzyme systems composed of three polypeptides: a protein that binds a corrinoid prosthetic group |CITS: [9654068]|, and two methyltransferases, named MT1 and MT2. MT1 and the corrinoid protein form a tight heterodimeric complex. When the substrate binds to this complex, MT1 catalyzes the transfer of the methyl group from the substrate to the corrinoid group. MT2 then transfers the methyl group from the corrinoid to 
/|FRAME: CoM| |CITS:[6438059]|. Individual MT1 and corrinoid-binding proteins are highly specific for their respective substrate, and exhibit little or no activity with similar substrates |CITS: [6615129][9195968][9006042][9654067][10852929]|.
/
/The enzymes responsible for methanogenesis from |FRAME: CPD-7679| were isolated from |FRAME: TAX-117561| and found to consist of two methyltransferases (MtqA and MtqB) and a 22-kDa corrinoid protein (MtqC) (the naomenclature MTQ stands for Methyl Transferase Quarternary amine) |CITS: [9732435]|.
//
UNIQUE-ID - CPD-12145
TYPES - Quinones
TYPES - In-Situ-Cofactors
COMMON-NAME - tryptophan tryptophylquinone
SYNONYMS - TTQ
COMMENT - Tryptophan tryptophylquinone (TTQ), the cofactor of |FRAME: CPLX-3247| (MADH), is formed by covalent cross-linking of two tryptophan residues and incorporation of two oxygen atoms into one of the indole rings to form a quinone. During the catalytic cycle, TTQ mediates electron transfer from substrate to a copper protein, amicyanin. These electrons are transferred to the respiratory chain via a c-type cytochrome |CITS: [10721104]|.
//
