UNIQUE-ID - Medicarpin
TYPES - PTEROCARPANS
COMMON-NAME - medicarpin
SYNONYMS - 9-methoxy-6a,11a-dihydro-6H-[1]benzofuro[3,2-c]chromen-3-ol
COMMENT - Pterocarpan phytoalexins are antimicrobial compounds in leguminous plants formed upon pathogenic attacks and similar biotic stress-related events. 
/
/|FRAME: Medicarpin Medicarpin|, first isolated from heartwood of the tropical tree |FRAME: TAX-149635| |CITS: [Harper65]|, is a major pterocarpan phytoalexin. It has been reported from many legumes, including alfalfa (|FRAME: TAX-3879|) |CITS: [Smith71][8071365]|, red clover (|FRAME: TAX-57577|) |CITS: [Higgins72]|, broad bean (|FRAME: TAX-3906|) |CITS: [Hargreaves76]|, all members of the |FRAME: TAX-78532| genus |CITS: [Ingham76]|, and the model legume |FRAME: TAX-3880| |CITS: [15605242]|.
/
/|FRAME: Medicarpin Medicarpin| is found in both a (-) and a (+) conformations. While |FRAME: CPD-3402| appears to be the most common form, |FRAME: CPD-20031| has been reported from several plants such as |FRAME: TAX-3897| and |FRAME: TAX-77268| |CITS: [Vanetten83][Martínez-Sotres12]|.
//
UNIQUE-ID - Inactive-R-2OH-Isocaproyl-CoA-Dehydratas
TYPES - Inactive-R-2-Hydroxyacyl-CoA-Dehydratase
COMMON-NAME - an inactive (<i>R</i>)-2-hydroxyisocaproyl-CoA dehydratase
COMMENT - |FRAME: EC-4.2.1.157|, which participates in an |FRAME: PWY-7767 "L-leucine fermentation pathway"| in some anaerobic bacteria, is a member of the (<i>R</i>)-2-hydroxyacyl-CoA dehydratase family.
/
/Members of this family are two-component systems composed of an extremely oxygen-sensitive activator (component A) and a dehydratase (component D). Component A is a homodimer with one [4Fe&ndash;4S] cluster bound in the dimer interface, while component D is a heterodimer with 1-2 [4Fe&ndash;4S] clusters and FMN. In order to catalyze the reaction, the dehydratase requires one high-energy electron that transiently reduces the electrophilic thiol ester carbonyl to a nucleophilic ketyl radical anion, facilitating the elimination of the hydroxyl group. The electron needs to be supplied only once, before the first reaction takes place, since it is regenerated at the end of each reaction cycle. This initial activation is provided by the activator. 
/
/The activator, which has been named |FRAME: CPLX-9331 archerase| because its open position resembles an archer shooting arrows, binds two ADP molecules. Upon the reduction of its [4Fe&ndash;4S] cluster by a single electron, delivered by a dedicated flavodoxin, the two ADP molecules exchange for two ATP molecules, resulting in a large conformational change. The change results in the activator binding to the dehydratase component, upon which the two ATP molecules are hydrolyzed and the electron is transferred to the dehydratase, activating it |CITS: [15374661][18337824]|.
/
/The structure shown here depicts the oxidized [4Fe&ndash;4S] cluster.
//
