UNIQUE-ID - Cypemycin
TYPES - Peptide-Antibiotics
COMMON-NAME - cypemycin
COMMENT - Cypemycin is a modified peptide antibiotic produced by |FRAME: TAX-932694|.
/It has potent activity against mouse leukemia cells |CITS: [7802859]|. The peptide is classified as a member of the lantibiotic family of peptides mostly due to the presence of dehydrobutyrine (Dhb) and S-[(Z)-2-aminovinyl]-D-cysteine (Avi-Cys) residues.
/
/Six distinct posttranslational modifications participate in cypemycin biosynthesis, altering 9 of the 22 amino acids found in the mature peptide, including four threonine residues that are dehydrated to form Dhb,  one cysteine that is dethiolated to form dehydroalanine, a C-terminal Cys that is oxidatively decarboxylated to form an enethiolate, two isoleucine residues that are isomerized to form L-allo-Isoleucine, and two <i>N</i>-methylations of the N-terminal alanine |CITS: [20805503]|.
//
UNIQUE-ID - Phytocassanes
TYPES - Diterpenes
TYPES - Phytoalexins
COMMON-NAME - a phytocassane
COMMENT - The phytocassanes are rice phytoalexins that were isolated from |FRAME: TAX-148305| infected rice leaves or |FRAME: TAX-456999| infected rice stems. The first four were discovered in 1995 and named phytocassanes A-D |CITS: [Koga95]|, and were followed by a fifth member (phytocassane E) in 1997 |CITS: [Koga97]|.
/
/It should be noted that several years later it was shown that the rice phytocassanes are configured with <i>ent</i>-, rather than the originally suggested normal stereochemistry and, thus, are enantiomeric to the originally suggested chemical structures |CITS: [Yajima00]|.
//
UNIQUE-ID - Brassinosteroids
TYPES - Steroid-Hormones
TYPES - Plant-Hormones
COMMON-NAME - a brassinosteroid
COMMENT - |FRAME: Brassinosteroids Brassinosteroid|s are steroidal phytohormones that regulate various important physiological and developmental processes, such as cell elongation and division, pollen fertility, photomorphogenesis, differentiation of vascular elements, and stress resistance |CITS: [16056912][Mandava88][15012241]|. Brassinosteroids, which have structural similarity to |FRAME: ECDYSONE|, the molting hormone of insects, are C<sub>27</sub>, C<sub>28</sub> and C<sub>29</sub> steroids depending on their C-24 alkyl substituents. More than 70 free, naturally occurring brassinosteroids have been identified in plants. The C<sub>28</sub> brassinosteroid |FRAME: CPD-697| (BL) is the most biologically active and together with its C<sub>28</sub> congeners is distributed widely in the plant kingdom |CITS:[15012241]|.
//
