UNIQUE-ID - Oxidized-cytochromes
TYPES - Cytochromes
COMMON-NAME - an oxidized cytochrome
SYNONYMS - a ferricytochrome
COMMENT - Cytochromes are proteins containing |FRAME: Hemes| groups and are primarily involved in electron transport.
/They were initially described in 1884 by MacMunn as respiratory pigments (originally named myohematin or histohematin) |CITS: [MacMunn84]| and were renamed cytochromes after being rediscovered in 1920.
/
/In general cytochromes are named based on the type of heme they carry - cytochrome <i>c</i> contains a heme <i>c</i>, while cytochrome <i>aa</i><sub>3</sub> contains both a heme <i>a</i> and a heme <i>a</i><sub>3</sub>. Often cytochromes are further designated by their reduced state R-band maximum, e.g. cyt <i>c</i><sub>559</sub>.
/
/In most cytochromes the heme group contains an iron ion, which interconverts between its reduced state (Fe<sup>2+</sup>) and its oxidized state (Fe<sup>3+</sup>). Thus, cytochromes are reduced by accepting an electron from a donor, and deliver the electron to the oxidized form of an acceptor, reducing it in the process. Cytochromes play an indispensable role in most respiratory chains and in photosynthesis.
/
/The diagram below shows |FRAME: Cytochromes-c|, in which a |FRAME: HEME_C| group is bound to the protein by one or two thioether bonds involving sulfhydryl groups of cysteine residues. Note that not all cytochromes are covalently attached to their proteins.
//
