UNIQUE-ID - Azurins
TYPES - Blue-Copper-Proteins
COMMON-NAME - an azurin
COMMENT - Azurin is a periplasmic blue copper protein found in some bacteria, which undergoes oxidation-reduction between Cu(I) and Cu(II), and transfers single electrons between enzymes |CITS: [1942029][17030312]|.
/
/The overall architecture of azurins resembles that of |FRAME: Plastocyanins plastocyanins|, with the additional presence of a back flap formed by two &alpha;-helices located between the fifth and sixth &beta;-strands |CITS: [10975566]|.
/
/Azurins and pseudoazurins participate in the oxidative deamination of primary amines and also in denitrification processes
/by shuttling electrons from aromatic amine dehydrogenase to cytochrome oxidase and from some <i>c</i>-type cytochromes to nitrite reductases |CITS: [10975566]|. The two types of nitrite reductases (Copper-containing and heme cd1-containing) interact with different azurins |CITS: [7640272]|.
/
/The physiological partner of azurin in the denitrification electron transfer chain is |FRAME: Cytochromes-C551|, a monomeric heme protein |CITS: [6283101][8811189][11897350][12486716]|. The azurin-<i>c</i><sub>551</sub> complex has been investigated at single molecule level by atomic force spectroscopy |CITS: [16869557]| and by surface plasmon resonance and fluorescence |CITS: [24446376]|.
//
