COMMON-NAME - a reduced [NADPH-hemoprotein reductase]
COMMENT - |FRAME: EC-1.6.2.4|, is a flavoprotein containing both |FRAME: FMN| and |FRAME: FAD| that catalyzes the reduction of cytochrome P-450 enzymes, such as |FRAME: EC-1.14.14.1| and |FRAME: EC-1.14.14.16|.
/
/The enzyme also catalyzes the reduction of |FRAME: EC-1.14.14.18|, and can reduce |FRAME: Cytochromes-b5 "cytochrome <i>b</i><sub>5</sub>"| and |FRAME: Cytochromes-c "cytochrome <i>c</i>"|.
/
/The structure shown here shows the reduced form of the flavin cofactor.
//
UNIQUE-ID - Adjacent-pyrimidine-dimer-in-DNA
TYPES - DNA-With-Pyrimidine-Dimers
COMMON-NAME - a dimer of adjacent pyrimidine nucleosides in DNA
COMMENT - Exposure of cells to ultraviolet light results in the formation of DNA photoproducts, the majority of which arise from a photoreaction between two pyrimidines. The structure and stereochemistry of the photoproducts depend on the conformation of the two bases at the time of irradiation. Irradiation of A form DNA generates |FRAME: CPD-11654 "spore photoproducts"|, while irradiation of B form DNA produces <i>cis</i>-<i>syn</i> cyclobutane pyridine dimers, |FRAME: CPD-11657 "pyrimidine (6-4) pyrimidone photoproducts"|, and their Dewar valence isomers |CITS: [15748634][30065996]|.
/
/The vast majority of pyrimidine dimers occurs from an interaction of two adjacent pyrimidine nucleotide. Non-adjacent photodimers of both intra-strand and inter-strand types are much rarer, but do occur, leading to UV-induced deletion mutations |CITS: [18680367]|.
//
