UNIQUE-ID - PC-19
TYPES - primary-active-transporters
COMMON-NAME - a P-type-ATPase transporter
COMMENT - The P-type ATPases (P-ATPase), also known as E1-E2 ATPases, are a large group of evolutionarily related ion and lipid pumps that are found in bacteria, archaea, and eukaryotes. The P in the name comes from the  fact that these enzymes catalyze the auto-phosphorylation of a key conserved aspartate residue within the pump 
/
/The P-type ATPase Superfamily is classified as TC 3.A.3 in the Transporter Classification Database |CITS: [24225317]|. Most members of this superfamily catalyze cation uptake and/or efflux, although one subfamily (TC 3.A.3.8) is involved in flipping phospholipids across the membrane.
/
/P-type ATPases have a single catalytic subunit of 70 - 140 kDa. This catalytic subunit hydrolyzes ATP, contains the aspartyl phosphorylation site and binding sites for the transported ligand(s), and catalyzes ion transport. However, enzymes from some subfamilies (e.g. P1A, P2A, P2C and P4 ATPases) also need additional subunits that are involved in trafficking, folding, and regulation.
//
