UNIQUE-ID - Polyketide-synthase-PKS13
TYPES - Polyketide-Synthases
COMMON-NAME - polyketide synthase PKS13
SYNONYMS - PKS13
COMMENT - 
/
/PKS13 is a member of the type I polyketide synthase gene family. Sequence analysis revealed that it contains two non-equivalent phosphopantetheine-binding domains, a ketoacyl synthase domain, an acyl transferase domain, and a thioesterase domain |CITS: [14695899][15653820]|.
/
/PKS13 is involved in the Claisen-type condensation as the final step in the synthesis of mycolic acid in |FRAME: TAX-1773|. The first step of this condensation is the binding of a C52-&alpha;-meroacyl group in  an activated AMP form and a 2-carboxyl-cerotoyl group in its CoA-activated form to an N-terminal [acp] domain and a C-terminal [acp] domain, respectively. The binding reactions are catalyzed by the two  4' phosphopentetheinyl transferase domains.
/
/Following the initial binding, the meroacyl group is transferred from the N-terminal domain to the ketoacyl-synthase (KS) domain in a reaction catalyzed by the acyltransferase domain.
/
/The next step involves the nucleophilic attack of the carbonyl group of the trans-keto-meroacyl-moiety by the acidic &alpha;-carbon of the 2-carboxyl-cerotoyl-moiety, resulting in the formation of 3-oxo-C87-trans-mycolate bound to the near C-terminal [acp] domain. This condensation is catalyzed by the ketoacyl synthase domain |CITS:[14695899][15042094][15653820]|.
//
