UNIQUE-ID - PC-25
TYPES - electrochemical-potential-driven-transpo
COMMON-NAME - resistance-nodulation-cell division (RND) superfamily
COMMENT - Family 2.A.6 in the IUBMB classification of membrane transport proteins and in the Transporter Classification Database |CITS: [24225317]|.
/
/The RND (Resistance, Nodulation, cell Division) family of integral membrane proteins participate in the formation of chemiosmotic H+-antiporter efflux systems.
/
/RND superfamily members have been classified into nine recognized phylogenetic families, which generally correlate with specific substrate specificity. Family 1 members catalyze export of heavy metals; family 2 members export multiple drugs; family 3 members exprot lipooligosaccharides concerned with plant nodulation for the purpose of symbiotic nitrogen fixation; family 4 members (SecDF proteins) export unfolded proteins; family 5 members export lipids and possibly antibiotic drugs in Gram positive bacteria; family 6 members are eukaryotic proteins that export cholesterol/lipid/steroid hormones; family 7 members export fused pentacyclic ring compounds such a hopanoids; family 8 members export pigments; and family 9 members export cholesterol-modified peptides such as "hedgehog", a sterol sensor in animals. 
/
/Most of the RND superfamily transport systems consist of large polypeptide chains that contain 12 transmembrane domains. A large periplasmic domain is involved in substrate recognition and forms a cavity that can accommodate multiple drugs simultaneously. While RND systems may consist of three, two, or one distinct RND polypeptide chains, most contain only one RND polypeptide. However, the RND members of families 1-3 function in conjunction with a membrane fusion protein (MFP) and an outer membrane factor (OMF), achieving efflux across both membranes of the Gram-negative bacterial cell envelope in a single energy-coupled step.
//
