UNIQUE-ID - RING-E3-ubiquitin-carrier-proteins
TYPES - E3-ubiquitin-carrier-proteins
COMMON-NAME - a RING E3 ubiquitin-carrier protein
COMMENT - |FRAME: E3-ubiquitin-carrier-proteins "E3 ubiquitin-carrier proteins"| (also called incorrectly ubiquitin ligases or E3 ubiquitin ligases) are enzymes that transfer |FRAME: Ubiquitins ubiquitin| from a ubiquitin-|FRAME: Ubiquitin-carrier-proteins-E2 E2| complex to the target protein that is to be ubiquitinated. The enzyme attaches the ubiquitin to a lysine residue on the target protein via an isopeptide bond.
/Since no ATP is required for this transfer operation, these enzymes are transferases and not ligases.
/
/RING E3 ubiquitin-carrier proteins are |FRAME: E3-ubiquitin-carrier-proteins "E3 ubiquitin-carrier proteins"| that contain a RING (Really Interesting New Gene) finger domain. The RING domains bind one or more zinc atoms, and are involved in binding the target protein.
//
UNIQUE-ID - Capsaicinoids
TYPES - ALKALOID
TYPES - Guaiacols
COMMON-NAME - a capsaicinoid
COMMENT - The pungency of chili or hot peppers comes from phenolic alkaloids called |FRAME: Capsaicinoids capsaicinoids|. These compounds are exclusively produced in fruits of plants belonging to the |FRAME: TAX-4071| genus. A quarter of the world population consumes hot peppers in some form daily |CITS: [16938870]|. Structurally capsaicinoids consist of a common aromatic moiety, |FRAME: CPD-9327|, modified by a short chain fatty acid that may have variable length and different degrees of saturation |CITS: [Curry99]|. 
/
/The accumulation of |FRAME: Capsaicinoids capsaicinoids| is strictly correlated with developmental stages of the fruit and usually spans the ripening stages after fruit size increase has ceased |CITS: [SUKRASNO93]|. The capsaicinoids are localized in the epidermal cells of the fruit placenta |CITS: [12810854]|. Pungency differs considerably in species ranging from very hot to sweet peppers and has a positive correlation with the level of capsaicinoids biosynthetic gene expression |CITS: [12810854]|.
/
/|FRAME: CAPSAICIN Capsaicin| and |FRAME: CPD-9185| are the most common types. Other naturally occurring capsaicinoids include |FRAME: CPD-9182|, |FRAME: CPD-9333|, |FRAME: CPD-9331|, |FRAME: CPD-9181|, and |FRAME: CPD-9330|, which differ in the fatty acid chain length (n=7-10) and the presence and/or position of a double bond |CITS: [Curry99]|.
//
