COMMENT - A primary alcohol is a compound in which a hydroxy group, -OH, is attached to a saturated carbon atom that is connected to no more than one other carbon atom.
/
/Primary alcohols are also classified based on their length.
/
/|FRAME: Short-Chain-Primary-Alcohols "Short-chain primary alcohols"| have alkyl chains with fewer than six carbons.
/
/|FRAME: Medium-Chain-Primary-Alcohols "Medium-chain primary alcohols"| have alkyl chains of 6-12 carbons.
/
/|FRAME: Long-Chain-Primary-Alcohols "Long-chain primary alcohols"| (also known as fatty alcohols) have alkyl chains of 13-22 carbons.
/
/|FRAME: Very-Long-Chain-Primary-Alcohols "Very long-chain primary alcohols"| have alkyl chains of 23 carbons or longer.
//
