UNIQUE-ID - CPD-18692
TYPES - PGL
COMMON-NAME - PGL-1
SYNONYMS - [3,6-di-<i>O</i>-methyl-&beta;-D-glucopyranosyl-(1&rarr;4)-2,3-di-<i>O</i>-methyl-&alpha;-L-rhamnopyranosyl-(1&rarr;3)-3-<i>O</i>-methyl-&alpha;-L-rhamnopyranosyl] dimycocerosyl phenol-phthiocerol
COMMENT - |FRAME: CPD-18578 Phenol-phthiocerol|-based glycolipids, known as PGLs, have been found in |FRAME: TAX-1769|, |FRAME: TAX-1768|, |FRAME: TAX-1765|, |FRAME: TAX-1781|, and |FRAME: TAX-78331| |CITS: [3113946]|.
/
/In the major PGL of |FRAME: TAX-1769|, known as PGL-1, the phenolphthiocerol moiety is attached to the trisaccharide 3,6-di-<i>O</i>-methyl-&beta;-D-glucopyranosyl-(1&rarr;4)-2,3-di-<i>O</i>-methyl-&alpha;-L-rhamnopyranosyl-(1&rarr;3)-3-<i>O</i>-methyl-&alpha;-L-rhamnopyranose and the two secondary alcohol functions are esterified by |FRAME: Mycocerosic-Acids "mycocerosic acids"| |CITS: [3113946]|. PGL-1 inhibits the proliferation of T lymphocytes after stimulation with concanavalin A, seems to be associated with resistance to intracellular killing by macrophages, and promotes phagocytosis of |FRAME: TAX-1769| by macrophages and Schwann cells through binding to complement component C3 and laminin-2, respectively.
//
UNIQUE-ID - 2-3-Butanediols
TYPES - glycols
COMMON-NAME - a 2,3-butanediol
SYNONYMS - a butane-2,3-diol
SYNONYMS - a 2,3-butylene glycol
COMMENT - |FRAME: 2-3-Butanediols 2,3-butanediol| is a bacterial/fungal fermentation product of commercial interest, mostly as an antifreeze agent due to to its low freezing point |CITS: [Magee87]|. One of its well known applications is the formation of methyl ethyl ketone, by dehydration, which can be used as a liquid fuel additive |CITS: [11234948]|. All three stereo isomer of 2,3-butanediol (|FRAME: BUTANEDIOL|, |FRAME: CPD-346| and |FRAME: CPD-12004|) can be produced by various organisms |CITS: [11687934]|.
/
/The metabolic function of 2,3-butanediol is not yet known, although it may play a role in preventing intracellular acidification by changing the metabolism from acid production to the formation of a neutral compound |CITS: [6298028]|.
/In addition, the |FRAME: P125-PWY| pathway might participate in regulation of the NADH/NAD<sup>+</sup> ratio in the bacteria |CITS: [8444801]|.
//
