UNIQUE-ID - Oxidized-adrenal-ferredoxins
TYPES - Adrenodoxins
TYPES - Oxidized-2Fe-2S-Ferredoxins
COMMON-NAME - an oxidized adrenodoxin
SYNONYMS - an oxidized adrenal ferredoxin
COMMENT - |FRAME: Adrenodoxins Adrenodoxin|, also known as adrenal ferredoxin, is a small mammalian iron-sulfur protein (a |FRAME: 2Fe-2S-Ferredoxins "[2Fe-2S] ferredoxin"|) that transfers electrons to the mitochondrial class I cytochrome P450 enzymes , including |FRAME: HS06719|,  |FRAME: HS08547|, and |FRAME: HS11355|, which are involved in steroid hormone biosynthesis, as well as |FRAME: HS00395|, |FRAME: G-10917 CYP27A1|, and |FRAME: G-10947 CYP27B1|, which are involved in |FRAME: Vitamin-D "vitamin D"| metabolism and the hepatic degradation of |FRAME: CHOLESTEROL| to |FRAME: Bile-acids "bile acids"| |CITS: [22556163]|.
/
/Adrenodoxin receives the electrons from NADPH through a special protein, |FRAME: EC-1.18.1.6|. The three proteins - adrenoredoxin, adrenoredoxin reductase, and the hydroxylase, form a ternary complex.
/
/Even though the iron-sulfur cluster contains more than one iron atom, it can carry only one extra electron. Thus adrenodoxins participate in single electron transfer reactions |CITS: [10899784]|.
/
/It has been suggested that adrenodoxin is also involved in mitochondrial [Fe-S] cluster assembly, although this suggestion remains controversial |CITS: [20547883][22101253]|.
//
