UNIQUE-ID - Cytochromes-b5
TYPES - Cytochromes-B
COMMON-NAME - a cytochrome <i>b</i><sub>5</sub>
COMMENT - Cytochromes <i>b</i><sub>5</sub> are ubiquitous electron transport hemoproteins found in animals, plants, fungi and purple phototrophic bacteria. The microsomal and mitochondrial variants are membrane-bound, while bacterial and those from erythrocytes and other animal tissues are water-soluble. 
/
/In addition to cytochrome <i>b</i><sub>5</sub> itself, the family includes hemoprotein domains covalently associated with other redox proteins, as is the case in flavocytochrome <i>b</i><sub>2</sub> (|FRAME: L-LACTATE-DEHYDROGENASE-CYTOCHROME-RXN "EC 1.1.2.3, L-lactate dehydrogenase"|), sulfite oxidase (|FRAME: SULFITE-OXIDASE-RXN "EC 1.8.3.1"|), assimilatory nitrate reductase (|FRAME: NITRATE-REDUCTASE-NADH-RXN "EC 1.7.1.1"|, |FRAME: NITRATE-REDUCTASE-NADPORNOPH-RXN "EC 1.7.1.2"| and |FRAME: NITRATE-REDUCTASE-NADPH-RXN "EC 1.7.1.3"|)  |CITS: [7893819]| and various microsomal desaturases |CITS: [12538077]|.
/
/Cytochrome <i>b</i><sub>5</sub> can be reduced by |FRAME: EC-1.6.2.2| or |FRAME: EC-1.6.2.4|.
//
