TYPES - Phenylpropanoids
COMMON-NAME - a hydrolyzable tannin
COMMENT - A hydrolyzable tannin is a type of tannin that, upon heating with hydrochloric or sulfuric acids, yields |FRAME: CPD-183| or |FRAME: CPD-17769|.
/
/At the center of a hydrolyzable tannin molecule there is a carbohydrate core (usually D-glucose, although sometimes it is a cyclitol like |FRAME: QUINATE| or |FRAME: SHIKIMATE|). The hydroxyl groups of the carbohydrate core are partially or totally esterified with phenolic groups such as |FRAME: CPD-183| in |FRAME: Gallotanins gallotannins| or |FRAME: CPD-17769| in |FRAME: Ellagitannins ellagitannins|.
