UNIQUE-ID - Reduced-Rubredoxins
TYPES - Rubredoxins
COMMON-NAME - a reduced rubredoxin
COMMENT - Rubredoxins are found in some bacteria and archaea. Unlike |FRAME: FeS-Proteins "iron-sulfur (Fe-S) proteins"|, rubredoxins do not contain inorganic sulfide. Instead they contain a mononuclear thiolate complex [Fe(Cys)<sub>4</sub>]<sup>2-</sup>. Rubredoxins participate in electron transfer in biological systems, and transfer a single electron. During the process, the central iron atom changes between the +2 and +3 oxidation states.
/
/The reduction potential of a rubredoxin is typically in the range +50 mV to -50 mV.
