UNIQUE-ID - U6-snRNA
TYPES - snRNAs
COMMON-NAME - a U6 snRNA
SYNONYMS - a U6 spliceosomal RNA
COMMENT - U6 snRNA is a non-coding  (|FRAME: snRNAs "small nuclear RNA"|) that forms an RNA-protein complex known as the U6 snRNP (small nuclear ribonucleoprotein) complex. 
/
/This complex, in turn, combines with other snRNPs, unmodified pre-mRNA, and various other proteins to assemble a spliceosome, a large RNA-protein molecular complex that removes introns from a transcribed pre-mRNA. U6 is one of five snRNPs that are found in the spliceosome |CITS: [3041282]|.
/
/Base-pair specificity of the U6 snRNA allows the U6 snRNP to bind tightly to the U4 snRNA and loosely to the U5 snRNA  during the initial phase of the splicing reaction |CITS: [7882985]|. During the reaction cycle the U6 snRNA dissociates from U4 and binds to the U2 snRNA |CITS: [8299941]|. It is also associated with the 5' end of the intron that is being cleaved.
//
