UNIQUE-ID - Apo-EntF
TYPES - apo-Peptidyl-carrier-proteins
COMMON-NAME - an <i>apo</i>-[EntF L-seryl-carrier protein]
COMMENT - EntF is a four-domain protein that contains an N-terminal elongation/condensation domain, an adenylation domain, a peptidyl-carrier protein domain, and a C-terminal thioesterase domain |CITS: [10688898]|. It is part of the enterobactin synthase complex.
/
/<i>Holo</i>-EntF contains a covalently bound 4'-phosphopantetheine moiety that is attached posttranslationally by the EntD  enzyme to a serine side chain in the peptidyl-carrier domain. The enzyme activates L-serine through an ATP-pyrophosphate exchange reaction at the carboxylate group of L-serine, then transfers the seryl-moiety to its peptidyl-carrier domain, where it remains bound for further reactions |CITS: [3040679][1826089][1338974][8939709][9025288][22365602]|.
/
/The other substrate for EntF is |FRAME: 23DHB-EntB|, which if formed by the EntE-catalyzed acylation of the |FRAME: Holo-EntB "<i>holo</i>-EntB protein"| with |FRAME: 2-3-DIHYDROXYBENZOATE|. EntF then catalyzes formation of the three amide and three ester bonds, resulting on formation of |FRAME: ENTEROBACTIN| |CITS: [9485415]|.
ABBREV-NAME - [EntF L-seryl-carrier protein]
