UNIQUE-ID - Cytochromes-D-Reduced
TYPES - Cytochromes-D
TYPES - Reduced-cytochromes
COMMON-NAME - a reduced <i>d</i>-type cytochrome
SYNONYMS - reduced Cytochrome D protein
SYNONYMS - cytD proteins-2e
COMMENT - Cytochromes are proteins containing |FRAME: Hemes| groups and are primarily involved in electron transport.
/They were initially described in 1884 by MacMunn as respiratory pigments (originally named myohematin or histohematin) |CITS: [MacMunn84]| and were renamed cytochromes after being rediscovered in 1920.
/
/<i>d</i>-Type cytochromes contain a |FRAME: HEME_D| group attached to the surrounding protein matrix through a single coordination bond between the heme iron and an amino-acid side-chain. Unlike <i>c</i>-type cytochromes, they lack a covalent bond between the porphyrin ring and the protein.
/
/<i>d</i>-Type cytochromes have been described in complexes that contain other types of cytochromes. Cytochrome <i>bd</i> functions as a terminal oxidase in some bacterial species (such as |FRAME: TAX-659| and |FRAME: TAX-562|), while cytochrome <i>cd</i><sub>1</sub> is found in a common dissimilatory nitrite reductase present in many denitrifying bacteria.
//
