UNIQUE-ID - CPD-25234
TYPES - Methylketones
TYPES - Polyphenols
COMMON-NAME - usnate
SYNONYMS - usnic acid
COMMENT - Usnic acids are found almost exclusively in lichens. In macrolichens usnic acid is one of the most common cortical substances (along with the depside |FRAME: CPD-25039|). Usnic acids and cortical substances in general protect the photobiont from solar UV-B radiation |CITS: [Fernandez96]|.
/
/In addition to their photoprotective qualities, usnic acids have antimicrobial activities. Both the (+) and (-) enantiomers of usnic acid are effective against a large variety of Gram-positive bacterial strains, including strains from clinical isolates, irrespective of their resistant phenotype, including multi-resistant strains of |FRAME: TAX-1280|, enterococci and mycobacteria |CITS: [12061397]|.
/
/|FRAME: CPD-7411 (-)-Usnate| is also a selective natural herbicide because it is an irreversible inhibitor of the key plant enzyme |FRAME: EC-1.13.11.27| |CITS: [11034349]|.
/
/As of 2021, no biosynthetic pathway for usnic acid has been described. A usnic acid biosynthetic gene cluster from the lichen |FRAME: TAX-174080| was proposed in 2016 |CITS: [26895859]|. A putative polyketide synthase gene involved in usnic acid biosynthesis has been described from the lichen |FRAME: TAX-150890| in 2018 |CITS: [30020937]|. Another proposal for usnic acid biosynthetic gene cluster was made in 2020 |CITS: [33151307]|. However, as of 2021 none of these proposals have been verified.
//
