COMMON-NAME - an N-terminal L-glutaminyl-[protein]
SYNONYMS - a peptide with N-terminal L-glutamine
SYNONYMS - a [protein] N-terminal L-glutamine
COMMENT - In eukaryotes, |FRAME: N-terminal-asparagine "N-terminal Asn"| (N) and |FRAME: L-Glutaminyl-Peptides "N-terminal Gln"| (Q) are tertiary destabilizing residues in that they function, through enzymatic deamidation, to yield the secondary destabilizing N-terminal residues Asp (D) and Glu (E). Asp and Glu are conjugaed by ATE1-encoded Arg-tRNA-protein transferase, to arginine, one of the primary destabilizing N-terminal residues. Arginine is recognized by the E3 Ub ligases of the N-end rule pathway, called N-recognins.
/
/A third destabilizing residue that functions through arginylation is an |FRAME: N-terminal-L-cysteine "N-terminal Cys"| (C), which is arginylated after its nitric oxide (NO)-dependent oxidation to |FRAME: N-terminal-L-cysteine-sulfinate| or |FRAME: N-terminal-L-cysteine-sulfonate| (via |FRAME: Protein-nitrosothiol-L-alanine|) |CITS: [16222293]|.
