UNIQUE-ID - Cobalamins
TYPES - Cobamides
COMMON-NAME - a <i>Co</i>&alpha;-[&alpha;-(5,6-dimethylbenzimidazolyl)]-cobamide
SYNONYMS - a cobalamin
COMMENT - |FRAME: Cobamides "A cobamide"| is a corrinoid molecule based on the structure of |FRAME: CPD-20843|, a cobalt-corrinoid hexaamide that is formed from |FRAME: COBINAMIDE| by the attachment of an &alpha;-D-ribofuranose 3-phosphate residue at the 2 position of the aminopropanol chain.
/
/Active forms of cobamides, such as the B12 vitamins, contain upper (&beta;) and lower (&alpha;) ligands. The most common type of cobamides, |FRAME: Cobalamins cobalamin|, contains |FRAME: DIMETHYLBENZIMIDAZOLE| as the lower ligand.
/
/Since the cobalamin term does not specify the upper axial ligand, it includes several compounds that differ in their upper axial ligand. The functional forms of cobalamin, |FRAME:CPD-9037| and |FRAME:ADENOSYLCOBALAMIN|, include either a methyl group or an 5'-deoxyadenosyl group as their upper axial ligand, respectively. The form of cobalamin known as vitamin B12 is the artificially-made |FRAME: CPD-315|, which is converted to an active form in the human body upon ingestion.
//
