UNIQUE-ID - CpG-Sites
TYPES - Dinucleotide-Nucleic-Acid
COMMON-NAME - a CpG site
COMMENT - The CpG sites or CG sites are regions of DNA where a cytosine nucleotide occurs 5' to a guanine nucleotide.
/"CpG" is shorthand for "-C-phosphate-G-", that is, cytosine and guanine separated by a single phosphate group.
/The "CpG" notation is used to distinguish this linear sequence from the CG base-pairing of cytosine and guanine.
/
/Cytosines in CpG dinucleotides are often methylated to form 5-methylcytosine. In mammals, 70% to 80% of CpG cytosines are methylated |CITS: [15177689]|.
//
