UNIQUE-ID - Monoterpenoid-Indole-Alkaloids
TYPES - Terpenoid-Indole-Alkaloids
COMMON-NAME - a monoterpenoid indole alkaloid
SYNONYMS - a secologanin-tryptamine alkaloid
COMMENT - Monoterpenoid indole alkaloids (MIAs) are a very large class of terpenoid indole alkaloids synthesized by the Apocynaceae, Loganiaceae, and Rubiaceae plant families. Almost all of the 2000 known members are derived from |FRAME: STRICTOSIDINE|, which is biosynthesized from |FRAME: TRP| and |FRAME: SECOLOGANIN-CPD|.
/
/Though more than 42 skeletons have been described, they can be classified according to their carbon skeleton and biogenetic branch points into five major subgroups - the Aspidosperma, Ajmalan, Corynanthe, Iboga, and Quinoline alkaloids.
/
/Some of the MIAs exhibit a broad range of biological activities including anticancer, antimalarial, and antiarrhythmic properties.
//
UNIQUE-ID - Heparosan
TYPES - Glucosaminoglycans
COMMON-NAME - heparosan
SYNONYMS - heparan
COMMENT - |FRAME: Heparosan "Heparosan"| (also known as heparan) is a member of the |FRAME: Glycosaminoglycans "glycosaminoglycan"| family. It consists of a repeating disaccharide unit composed of |FRAME: CPD-12521|-(1,4)-|FRAME: CPD-12541|. The disaccharide units are linked by a (1-4) linkage to each other.
/
/Heparosan is a bacterial glycosaminoglycan produced and found in the capsule of some pathogenic bacteria such as Escherichia coli K5 and Pasteurella multocida.
/
/The heparosan skeleton serves as a starting point in the biosynthesis of several other glycosaminoglycan such as |FRAME: Heparan-Sulfate| and |FRAME: HEPARIN|, and bacterial heparosan is sometimes used for the synthesis of non-animal sourced heparin-like products.
//
