UNIQUE-ID - HEPARIN
TYPES - Glucosaminoglycans
COMMON-NAME - heparin
SYNONYMS - enoxaparin
COMMENT - |FRAME: HEPARIN "Heparin"| is a glycosaminoglycan polymer with a molecular weight ranging from 3 to 30 kDa. It is composed of a variable sulfated repeating disaccharide units composed of hexuronic (either iduronic or glucuronic) acid and glucosamine residues, in which the 2 position of the hexuronic acid and the 2, 3, or 6 positions of glucosamine may be sulfated. The two residues within a disaccharide are linked by a (1->4) bond, as are the disaccharides to each other.
/
/The main disaccharide unit consists of |FRAME: CPD-12518| and |FRAME: CPD-12533| [it is often referred to as IdoA(2S)-(1->4)-GlcNS(6S)]. However, |FRAME: CPD-12518| can be substituted by |FRAME: CPD-12521|, and |FRAME: CPD-12533| can be replaced by |FRAME: N-ACETYL-D-GLUCOSAMINE|, |FRAME: N-sulfo-D-glucosamine|, |FRAME: CPD-12545| or |FRAME: CPD-12565|.
/
/The basic IdoA(2S)-(1->4)-GlcNS(6S) disaccharide accounts for at least 85% of heparin isolated from beef lung and about 75% of heparin from porcine intestinal mucosa |CITS: [Casu89][Gatti79]|.
/
/Variations in the extent and location of sulfation, as well as the conformation of the alternating hexuronic acid residues, lead to a high degree of heterogeneity. By convention, heparin refers to molecules which possess a high sulfate content and large amounts of iduronic acid.
/
/The structure of |FRAME: HEPARIN| is very similar to that of |FRAME: Heparan-Sulfate| (also known as heparitin sulfate). Heparan sulfate contains lower amounts of sulfate and less iduronic acid than heparin |CITS: [5484472]|. In addition, heparan sulfates disaccharide units are organized into distinct sulfated and non-sulfated domains, while heparin disaccharides are sulfated more uniformly |CITS: [15047699]|.
//
UNIQUE-ID - 8-Methylmenaquinones
TYPES - Modified-Menaquinones
COMMON-NAME - an 8-methylmenaquinone
COMMENT - Several methylated or demethylated forms of menaquinone have been identified, including 8-methylmenaquinone, which is found in a diverse range of microorganisms such as members of the bacterial phyla |FRAME: TAX-201174 Actinobacteria| and |FRAME: TAX-1224 Proteobacteria| as well as the archaeal phyla |FRAME: TAX-28889 Crenarchaeota| and |FRAME: TAX-28890 Euryarchaeota| |CITS: [6663282][3937542][2312688][26472620][28164386]|. The addition of methyl groups to menaquinone shifts the redox potential to more negative values |CITS: [Schmid99][19265668]|, making these derivatives good redox mediators in electron transport chains that use low-potential electron acceptors such as polysulfide or sulfite |CITS: [11856339]|.
