UNIQUE-ID - m7G5-pppR-mRNAs
TYPES - Modified-mRNAs
COMMON-NAME - a 5'-(<i>N</i><sup>7</sup>-methyl 5'-triphosphoguanosine)-(ribonucleotide)-[mRNA]
SYNONYMS - m<sup>7</sup>G(5')pppR-mRNA
COMMENT - The messenger RNAs (mRNAs) of all metazoan organisms and most eukaryotic viruses possess a 5' cap structure consisting of a 7-methyl guanosine (m7G) linked via an inverted 5'–5' triphosphate bridge to the initiating nucleoside
/of the transcript.
/
/The inverted m7G, which is also known as a cap0 structure, marks transcription start sites, and has multiple effects on gene expression, including enhancement of RNA stability, splicing, nucleocytoplasmic transport and translation initiation, as facilitated by interactions with nuclear and cytoplasmic cap binding proteins.
/
/The cap0 structure is present on all eukaryotic mRNAs and is essential for cell growth of Saccharomyces cerevisiae and survival of mammalian cells |CITS: [21310715]|.
