UNIQUE-ID - Heparan
TYPES - Glucosaminoglycans
COMMON-NAME - heparosan-[core protein]
COMMENT - This compound class describes a |FRAME: Heparosan| polymer, attached to a serine residue in a glycoprotein, prior to any subsequent modifications. In animal tissues heparosan is synthesized attached to cell surface or extracellular matrix proteins, known as "core proteins".
/
/Heparosan consists of a repeating disaccharide unit composed of |FRAME: CPD-12521|-(1,4)-|FRAME: CPD-12541|. The disaccharide units are linked by a (1-4) linkage to each other. The polymer chain is attached to the core proteins via a tetrasaccharide linkage region that differs in composition from the rest of the polymer.
/
/The heparosan skeleton serves as a starting point in the biosynthesis of several other glycosaminoglycan such as |FRAME: Heparan-Sulfate| and |FRAME: HEPARIN|, and bacterial heparosan is sometimes used for the synthesis of non-animal sourced heparin-like products.
//
