UNIQUE-ID - Sphinga-4E-8E-dienine-Ceramides
TYPES - Sphinga-4-8-dienine-Ceramides
COMMON-NAME - a (4<i>E</i>,8<i>E</i>)-sphinga-4,8-dienine ceramide
COMMENT - Ceramides are found in high concentrations within the cell membrane and are one of the component lipids that make up |FRAME: Sphingomyelins sphingomyelin|, one of the major lipids in the lipid bilayer.
/
/This type of ceramide, containing an additional double bond at position 8 of the sphingoid base, is a common modification in plants and fungi |CITS: [9786850][11171153][19047747]|.
/In plants, there is commonly a mixture of ceramides with the double bond at position 8 in both <i>cis</i> and <i>trans</i> configurations, whereas the double bond at the 4 position is generally in the <i>trans</i> configuration |CITS: [Lynch04]|. In the diatom |FRAME: TAX-35128| both bonds are in the <i>trans</i> configuration |CITS: [15978045]|.
//
