UNIQUE-ID - Aspergilus-galactomannan-core
TYPES - Mannans
COMMON-NAME - a galactofuranosemannan core (<i>Aspergillus</i>)
COMMENT - Mannans are polymers composed of |FRAME: MANNOSE| residues. Pure mannans are rarely found, and most contain &alpha;(1,6)-linked galactopyranosyl side chains. However, in certain filamentous fungi galactofuranose (Gal<i>f</i>) is found in galactomannan instead of galactopyranose.
/
/The galactomannan attached to <i>N</i>-glycans in |FRAME: TAX-746128| is composed of a linear mannan core comprising |FRAME: CPD-20116 "&alpha;-(1-2)-linked mannotetraose"| repeating units attached to each other via &alpha;-(1-6) linkages and decorated by side chains of &beta;-(1-5)-galactofuranose units, which are linked to the C2 position of the non-reducing mannose residue in each mannotetraose unit |CITS: [7960122]|.
/
/The length of the side chains depends on growth conditions. Cells grown in YPD medium produced galactomannan with side chain consisting an average of 3-4 units of galactofuranose |CITS: [7960122][25187160]|, while cells grown in YNB medium incorporated on average 10 Gal<i>f</i> units that may contain one &beta;-(1,6) linkage midchain |CITS: [25187160]|.
/
/It should be noted that a different form of galactomannan containing galactofuranose resides is found in <i>O</i>-glycans produced by this organism, in which the mannan core is much shorter, consisting of only one to two mannosyl residues |CITS: [25187160]|.
//
