UNIQUE-ID - GIPC-40-0-2s
TYPES - Glycosyl-IPCs
COMMON-NAME - a glycosylinositolphosphoceramide(40:0)-2
SYNONYMS - a GIPC(40:0)-2
COMMENT - In this class of glycosylinositol phosphoceramides, a long carbon chain is attached at position R1 to form a fatty amide and a long carbon chain is attached at position R2 to form a long chain base. Either or both of these chains may contain one or more double bonds and may have hydroxyl groups attached.
/
/Based on the notation GIPC(m:n)-p, each compound within this class has a total of 40 carbons (m), zero double bonds (n), and two hydroxyl groups (p) present in the sphingoid base and the fatty amide. However, the length, hydroxylation position, double bond position, and double bond orientation of the groups attached at R2 and R3 will differ between individual members of this group of compounds.
//
UNIQUE-ID - Levan
TYPES - Exopolysaccharides
TYPES - Fructans
COMMON-NAME - a levan
COMMENT - Levan is a non-structural polysaccharide present in several microorganisms and a few plant species. It consists almost solely of fructosyl residues linked via &beta;-2,6 linkages, and is packed into nano-sized spherical forms, giving it a very low intrinsic viscosity. Levan is a main ingredient in natto, a traditional Japanese food.
/
/Plants synthesize levan in the vacuole by the concerted action of various fructosyltransferases such as |FRAME: EC-2.4.1.10|. When acting alone, this enzyme synthesizes linear levan chains from sucrose via the trisaccharide intermediate |FRAME: 6-KESTOSE| (it can also use |FRAME: 1-KESTOTRIOSE| and |FRAME: NEOKESTOSE| as the initial fructose acceptors). Plant fructans generally have a low degree of polymerization (DP <10 to 100). 
/
/The occurrence of levansucrase is widespread in Gram-positive and Gram-negative bacteria. Bacterial levans reach much higher molecular masses and contain up to 10,000 fructosyl units. Species that belong to the |FRAME: TAX-1301|, |FRAME: TAX-1243|, and |FRAME: TAX-1578| genera also contain |FRAME: EC-2.4.1.9|, which forms &beta;-(2,1) fructosyl-fructose linkages. When expressed together with levansucrase, that enzyme creates branching points that connect multiple &beta;-(2,6) linked levan chains, forming a branched polymer known as |FRAME: Graminans graminan| |CITS: [27178733]|.
//
