UNIQUE-ID - Fucan
TYPES - Sulfated-Polysaccharides
COMMON-NAME - a fucan
COMMENT - Fucan is a generic term used to define a family of |FRAME: L-fucoses|-containing sulfated polysaccharides with extremely variable molecular weights that are produced by brown algae (|FRAME: TAX-2870|) |CITS: [Kylin13]| and marine vertebrates |CITS: [Vasseur48]|. It has been recommended to use this term to refer to polysaccharide based mainly on sulfated L-fucose, with less than 10% other monosaccharides |CITS: [12626402]|.
/
/In marine invertebrates, sulfated fucans have been found in the egg jelly coat of sea urchins |CITS: [Vasseur48][8071336]| and in the body wall of sea cucumber |CITS: [3038547]|. In brown algae the fucan is present in the cell walls and can account for more than 40% of the dry weight of isolated cell walls |CITS: [Kloareg84]|. The fucans of brown algae are often called |FRAME: Fucoidans fucoidans|.
/
/The structures of fucans vary among species and sometimes among different parts of the organism |CITS: [Dietrich95]|. Fucan structures can be divided into three main groups: one group, found in |FRAME: TAX-33637| species of brown algae  and several species of sea urchines, has a central chain composed of (1&rarr;3)-linked &alpha;-L-fucopyranose residues |CITS: [8408031]|; a second group, found so far only in the sea urchins |FRAME: TAX-7640| and |FRAME: TAX-7671|, has a central chain composed of (1&rarr;4)-linked &alpha;-L-fucopyranose residues |CITS: [11687579]|; the third group, which includes fucoidan isolated from |FRAME: TAX-52968| and |FRAME: TAX-3011| species of brown algae, has a central chain composed of repeating (1&rarr;3) and (1&rarr;4) linked &alpha;-L-fucopyranose residues |CITS: [11269406][21566795]|. Besides fucose and sulfate, the presence of monosaccharide residues such as mannose, galactose, glucose, xylose and uronic acids were also identified |CITS: [18794778]|.
/
/Several fucose-containing polymers with less than 90% fucosyl residues have also been reported from brown algae and some of them were given names: ascophyllan or xylofucoglycuronan, isolated from |FRAME: TAX-52969|, is based on a backbone of mannuronate with branches of 3-<i>O</i>-D-xylosyl-L-fucose-4-sulfate |CITS: [Larsen66][Kloareg86]|; sargassan or glycuronofucoglycan, also isolated from |FRAME: TAX-52969|, is based on linear chains of D-galactose with branches of L-fucose-3-sulfate or occasionally uronate |CITS: [Percival68][Medcalf78][Kloareg86]|. However, those are classified as sub-types of fucoidan and not fucan, due to the large percentage of non-fucose saccharides.
//
