UNIQUE-ID - m7G5-pppAm-mRNAs
TYPES - m7G5-pppRm-mRNAs
COMMON-NAME - a 5'-(<i>N</i><sup>7</sup>-methyl 5'-triphosphoguanosine)-(2'-<i>O</i>-methyladenosine)-[mRNA]
SYNONYMS - m<sup>7</sup>G(5')pppAm
COMMENT - The messenger RNAs (mRNAs) of all metazoan organisms and most eukaryotic viruses possess a 5' cap structure consisting of a 7-methyl guanosine (m7G) linked via an inverted 5'–5' triphosphate bridge to the initiating nucleoside
/of the transcript.  The inverted m7G, which is also known as a cap0 structure, marks transcription start sites, and has multiple effects on gene expression, including enhancement of RNA stability, splicing, nucleocytoplasmic transport and translation initiation, as facilitated by interactions with nuclear and cytoplasmic cap binding proteins.
/
/The initiating nucleoside of the transcript, and often the second transcribed nucleotide, are modified by 2'-O-ribose methylation. Methylation of the ribose on the first transcribed nucleotide is termed cap1 and similar methylation of the second transcribed position is termed cap2 |CITS: [21310715]|.
