UNIQUE-ID - Gamma-linolenoyl-groups
TYPES - Fatty-Acids-Within-Glycerolipids
COMMON-NAME - a [glycerolipid]-&gamma;-linolenate
SYNONYMS - a [glycerolipid]-6Z,9Z,12Z-octadecatrienoic acid
SYNONYMS - a [glycerolipid]-6Z,9Z,12Z-octadecatrienoate
SYNONYMS - a [glycerolipid]-(6,9,12)-linolenoic acid
SYNONYMS - a [glycerolipid]-(6,9,12)-linolenate
SYNONYMS - a [glycerolipid]-&gamma;-linolenic acid
COMMENT - This class describes a |FRAME: CPD-8117| group that is incorporated within a lipid molecule
/
/|FRAME: CPD-8117| (GLA) is a polyunsaturated (18:3) &omega;-6 fatty acid (the 6 refers to the position of the first double bond from the methyl end of the fatty acid). It is synthesized from |FRAME: LINOLEIC_ACID| by &Delta;<sup>6</sup> desaturase enzymes. Unlike its precursor, GLA is not an essential fatty acid for animals, since almost all animals possess a &Delta;<sup>6</sup> desaturase enzyme.
/
/GLA is of major importance in animal cells, being the precursor for the synthesis of several &Delta;<sup>6</sup>-desaturated fatty acids, such as |FRAME: ARACHIDONIC_ACID| and |FRAME: 5Z8Z11Z14Z17Z-EICOSAPENTAENOATE| (see |FRAME: PWY-7592|). &Delta;<sup>6</sup>-desaturated fatty acids have roles in the maintenance of membrane structure and function, in the regulation of cholesterol synthesis and transport, in the prevention of water loss from the
/skin, and as precursors of eicosanoids, including prostaglandins and leucotrienes |CITS: [1334266]|.
/
/Like other fatty acids, |FRAME: CPD-8117| is rarely found in its free form. It is usually found either as |FRAME: GAMMA-LINOLENOYL-COA| or |FRAME: Gamma-linolenoyl-groups "incorporated into a lipid"|.
//
