UNIQUE-ID - Rubbers
TYPES - CIS-TRANS-POLYISOPRENYL-PP
COMMON-NAME - rubber
SYNONYMS - natural rubber
SYNONYMS - <i>cis</i>-1,4-polyisoprene
COMMENT - Natural rubber is an important raw material in an enormous number of products. The backbone of natural rubber comprises a (<i>cis</i>)-1,4-polyisoprene with two or three <i>trans</i>-isoprene units at the &omega;-terminus, formed by the sequential condensation of |FRAME: DELTA3-ISOPENTENYL-PP| (IPP) units in <i>cis</i> configuration onto a short <i>all-trans</i> prenyl diphosphate. It is very similar in structure to |FRAME: DOLICHOL dolichols|, but the chain length is much longer (C>1500).
/
/Natural rubber is produced from latex - a material that makes up the cytoplasmic content of the latecifers or latex vessels of |FRAME: TAX-3981| (the Brazilian rubber tree) |CITS: [17545224]|. Although over 2000 plant species capable of producing rubber have been identified, only a few synthesize the high molecular weight rubber that is required for the production of high quality rubber products, and natural rubber is currently produced commercially only from |FRAME: TAX-3981|. A potential alternative source is the Russian rubber-producing dandelion (|FRAME: TAX-333970|), which was cultivated in the former Soviet Union during World War II to satisfy the demand for natural rubber |CITS: [22504822]|.
/
/Rubber biosynthesis is carried out by |FRAME: EC-2.5.1.20|. The enzyme is localized at the surface of cytosolic vesicles known as rubber particles, and biosynthesis is initiated through the binding of an allylic pyrophosphate primer, such as |FRAME: FARNESYL-PP| |CITS: [Tanaka01][14622254][18799172]|.
/
/The R in the structure stands for an unspecified number of (<i>cis</i>)-connected isoprene units.
//
