UNIQUE-ID - Stearoyl-lipid
TYPES - Fatty-Acids-Within-Glycerolipids
COMMON-NAME - a [glycerolipid]-stearate
COMMENT - Stearate is a saturated fatty acid that occurs in many animal and vegetable fats and oils. It is a large constituent in milk fats, lard, and cocoa and shea butters.
/
/The name comes from Greek for "hard fat", reflecting the fact that stearate forms a waxy solid |CITS: [16477801]|. Stearate was first described by Michel Eugene Chevreul in 1823.
/
/ In cells |FRAME: STEARIC_ACID| is usually found in the form of |FRAME: Stearoyl-ACPs stearoyl-[acp]|, |FRAME: STEAROYL-COA| or |FRAME: Stearoyl-lipid "incorporated into lipids"|.
//
UNIQUE-ID - 1-4-beta-Xylan
TYPES - Xylans
COMMON-NAME - a (1&rarr;4)-&beta;-D-xylan
COMMENT - |FRAME: 1-4-beta-Xylan " (1&rarr;4)-&beta;-D-xylan"| is a polymer of |FRAME: BETA-D-XYLOSE| residues connected by (1&rarr;4) links.
/It is found in the cell walls of plants and some green and red algae, and is the major constituent of |FRAME: Hemicelluloses|. 
/Pure xylan, consisting of only xylopyranosyl residues, is rare. Most forms of |FRAME: 1-4-beta-Xylan| are decorated with other types of sugar.
//
