UNIQUE-ID - Saturated-Fatty-Acids
TYPES - CPD66-39
COMMON-NAME - a saturated fatty acid
COMMENT - |FRAME: Fatty-Acids "A fatty acid"| is a carboxylic acid with a long unbranched aliphatic tail.
/Even though fatty acids derived from natural fats and oils, such as |FRAME:CPD-195|, are usually at least 8 carbon atoms long, carboxylic acids as short as |FRAME:BUTYRIC_ACID| (4 carbon atoms) are considered to be fatty acids.
/
/When a fatty acid contains only single bonds, it is referred to as |FRAME: Saturated-Fatty-Acids|. When it contains one or more double bonds, it is referred to as |FRAME: Unsaturated-Fatty-Acids|. If it contains a double bond in the <i>trans</i> configuration, it is often referred to as a <i>trans</i> fatty acid. Most fatty acids in the <i>trans</i> configuration are not found in nature and are the result of human processing.
//
UNIQUE-ID - i-Antigens
TYPES - blood-group-substances
COMMON-NAME - an i antigen
SYNONYMS - a &beta;-D-Gal-(1&rarr;4)-&beta;-D-GlcNAc-(1&rarr;3)-&beta;-D-Gal-(1&rarr;4)-&beta;-D-GlcNAc-R
SYNONYMS - a &beta;-D-galactosyl-(1&rarr;4)-<i>N</i>-acetyl-&beta;-D-glucosaminyl-(1&rarr;3)-&beta;-D-galactosyl-(1&rarr;4)-<i>N</i>-acetyl-&beta;-D-glucosaminyl-R
SYNONYMS - a &beta;-D-galactosyl-(1,4)-<i>N</i>-acetyl-&beta;-D-glucosaminyl-(1,3)-&beta;-D-galactosyl-(1,4)-<i>N</i>-acetyl-D-glucosaminyl-[glycoprotein]
SYNONYMS - an i histo-blood group antigen
SYNONYMS - an <i>N</i>-acetyl-&beta;-D-galactosyl-(1,4)-<i>N</i>-acetyl-&beta;-D-glucosaminyl-(1,3)-&beta;-D-galactosyl-(1,4)-<i>N</i>-acetyl-&beta;-D-glucosaminyl-R
SYNONYMS - an <i>N</i>-acetyl-&beta;-D-galactosyl-1,4-<i>N</i>-acetyl-&beta;-D-glucosaminyl-1,3-&beta;-D-galactosyl-1,4-<i>N</i>-acetyl-D-glucosaminyl-[glycoprotein]
SYNONYMS - <i>N</i>-acetyl-&beta;-D-galactosyl-1,4-<i>N</i>-acetyl-&beta;-D-glucosaminyl-1,3-&beta;-D-galactosyl-1,4-<i>N</i>-acetyl-D-glucosaminyl-[glycoprotein]
SYNONYMS - <i>N</i>-acetyl-&beta;-D-galactosyl-(1,4)-<i>N</i>-acetyl-&beta;-D-glucosaminyl-(1,3)-&beta;-D-galactosyl-(1,4)-<i>N</i>-acetyl-&beta;-D-glucosaminyl-R
SYNONYMS - blood group i antigen
COMMENT - The |FRAME: i-Antigens "i antigen"| is found on membrane proteins in red blood cells and many other cell types as well as various body secretions of developing fetuses and newborn infants |CITS: [13767181][4971635]|, while the |FRAME: I-antigens "I antigen"| is found in all adults |CITS: [13292836]|. The i antigen undergoes gradual conversion to the I antigen in newborn infants, a process that completes in about 18 months.
/
/Both antigens are based entirely on Type 2 (|FRAME: BETA-D-GALACTOSYL-ETCETERA-GLUCOSAMINE "<i>N</i>-acetyllactosamine"|) chains. The basic i structure is an unbranched polylactosamine comprising at least two <i>N</i> - acetyllactosamine units connected by a &beta;(1&rarr;3) linkage |CITS: [823020][22356451]|.
/The crucial step in the transition from the i antigen to the I antigen is catalyzed by |FRAME: EC-2.4.1.150|, also known as the I-branching enzyme, which introduces the branching by adding a GlcNAc residue by a &beta;(1&rarr;6) linkage to the galactose residue to which other residues are already attached by a 1,3 linkage |CITS: [6490658]|.
/Note that the structure shown here is the core structure that defines I antigenicity. Most i antigens are further glycosylated.
/(Reviewed in |CITS: [Daniels13]|).
//
