UNIQUE-ID - CPD-17355
TYPES - Fatty-Acids-Within-Glycerolipids
COMMON-NAME - a [glycerolipid]-(4Z,7Z,10Z,13Z,16Z,19Z)-docosahexaenoate
SYNONYMS - a [glycerolipid]-docosahexaenoate
SYNONYMS - a [glycerolipid]-docosahexaenoic acid
SYNONYMS - a [glycerolipid]-DHA
SYNONYMS - a [glycerolipid]-<i>all-cis</i>-docosa-4,7,10,13,16,19-hexaenoate
SYNONYMS - a [glycerolipid]-(4Z,7Z,10Z,13Z,16Z,19Z)-docosahexaenoate
SYNONYMS - a [glycerolipid]-(4Z,7Z,10Z,13Z,16Z,19Z)-docosa-4,7,10,13,16,19-hexaenoate
SYNONYMS - a docosahexaenoyl-[glycerolipid]
COMMENT - |FRAME: CPD-10244 Docosahexaenoate| (DHA) is a  22-carbon long-chain polyunsaturated fatty acid (LCPUFA) with 6 methylene interrupted <i>cis</i>-double bonds |CITS: [15292371]|. It is prevalent in the membrane lipids of some human tissues such as brain, testis and retina, and plays a critical role in the development and function of these tissues. It is also a precursor of different classes of eicosanoid effectors involved in the regulation of many important functions in mammals |CITS: [15292371]|.
/
/DHA is an <i>n</i>-3 (&omega;-3) fatty acid which is defined according to the location of the last double bond at the methyl end. It is synthesized <i>de novo</i> in several microalgae as well as in some fungi. It is also produced by some marine bacteria, mostly those adapted to low temperatures and high pressures |CITS: [10220156]|.
/
/Mammals are not able to synthesis DHA <i>de novo</i>, and instead synthesize it from the essential fatty acid |FRAME: LINOLENIC_ACID| (which they obtain in their diet) via alternating steps of microsomal aerobic desaturation and elongation |CITS: [11397798][14704315]| followed by a peroxisomal &beta;-oxidation step |CITS: [10903473]|.
/
/Like other fatty acids, |FRAME: CPD-10244| is rarely found in its free form. It is usually found either as |FRAME: CPD-17312| or |FRAME: CPD-17355 "incorporated into a lipid"|.
//
