UNIQUE-ID - Teichoic-Acid
TYPES - Teichoic-Acids
COMMON-NAME - a polyisoprenyl-teichoic acid
COMMENT - Teichoic acids were first reported in 1958 |CITS: [Armstrong58]|, after being discovered serendipitously as "contaminants" in bacterial extracts from |FRAME: TAX-1590| |CITS: [2662967]|. As they make up a significant portion of the cell walls (about 60% in |FRAME: TAX-1423|) |CITS: [13684313]|, they were named based on the Greek word teikhos, which means a fortification wall.
/
/The teichoic acids are found in the cell walls of a wide range of Gram-positive bacteria |CITS: [5411858][2496299]|. There are two main types of teichoic acids: the lipoteichoic acids (LTAs), which are anchored to the plasma membrane and extend from the cell surface into the peptidoglycan layer |CITS: [406922]|, and the wall teichoic acids (WTAs), which are covalently attached to peptidoglycan and extend through and beyond the cell wall.
/
/In |FRAME: TAX-224308| the main form of teichoic acid is a polymer of |FRAME: CPD-75 "poly(glycerol phosphate)"|, while in |FRAME: TAX-655816| the major variety is a polymer of |FRAME: CPD-19310 "poly(ribitol phosphate)"| |CITS: [13684313]|. In both cases, the repeating units are joined together by phosphodiester linkages, and are anchored via 2-3 glycerol phosphate units to a <i>N</i>-acetyl-&beta;-D-mannosaminyl-(1&rarr;4)-<i>N</i>-acetyl-&alpha;-D-glucosamine disaccharide. The glycerol and ribitol units of the polysaccharides are modified with D-alanine esters and/or monosaccharides such as glucose or <i>N</i>-acetylglucosamine |CITS: [13684313][4321415]|.
/
/It should be noted that strain 168 also possesses a |FRAME: CPD-19345 "minor form of wall teichoic acid"| that is comprised of poly(glucosyl <i>N</i>-acetylgalactosamine 1-phosphate) |CITS: [4202940]|). 
/
/Teichoic acids serve several roles in the cell. They serve as reservoirs of phosphates which can be mobilized when phosphate becomes limiting |CITS: [104966]|. Being anionic, they are scavengers of cations (in particular Mg<sup>2+</sup>), and may create a pH gradient across the wall by sequestering the protons expelled through the cytoplasmic membrane |CITS: [8396121]|. In addition, lipoteichoic acids are the main source of the hydrophobicity of the cell envelope |CITS: [6337099]|, and may contribute to its adhesiveness. Teichoic acids are also immunogenic, and can be considered the Gram-positive equivalent of the Gram-negative lipopolysaccharides |CITS: [46620]|.
//
UNIQUE-ID - Mycocerosic-Acids
TYPES - Methyl-Branched-Fatty-Acids
TYPES - Saturated-Fatty-Acids
TYPES - Very-long-chain-fatty-acids
COMMON-NAME - a mycocerosate
SYNONYMS - a mycocerosic acid
COMMENT - A unique feature of mycobacterial cell wall lipids is the presence of very long chain fatty acids with multiple methyl
/branches toward the carboxyl end of the carbon chain. Many types of such acids exist, including |FRAME: Mycosanoic-Acids "mycosanoic acids"|, |FRAME: Mycolipanoic-Acids "mycolipanoic acids"|, |FRAME: Mycolipanolic-Acids "mycolipanolic acids"|, |FRAME: Mycolipenic-Acids "mycolipenic acids"|, |FRAME: Mycolipodienoic-Acids "mycolipodienoic acids"|, |FRAME: Phthioceranic-Acids "phthioceranic acids"|, and |FRAME: Mycocerosic-Acids "mycocerosic acids"|.
/
/Mycocerosic acids are 2,4,6-trimethyl- and 2,4,6,8-tetramethyl-2-alkanoic acids present in many pathogenic |FRAME: TAX-1762|, including |FRAME: TAX-1773|, |FRAME: TAX-1765|, |FRAME: TAX-1777|, |FRAME: TAX-29311|, |FRAME: TAX-1768|, |FRAME: TAX-1769| |CITS: [3149973][19493698]|. Unlike the other types of fatty acids found in mycobacteria, the chiral centers bearing the methyl groups have an L (levorotatory) stereo configuration. The name "mycocerosic acid" was suggested by Ginger and Anderson in 1945 |CITS: [Ginger45]|.
/
/The mycocerosic acids of the mycobacteria are found mainly as |FRAME: CPD-18612| (DIM A) waxes or in phenolic glycolipids. In |FRAME: TAX-1773| the common mycoceroic acids are C30 and C32 |CITS: [3900276][3149973][8129476][8129476]|. In |FRAME: TAX-1765|  the common mycoceroic acids are mainly C26, C27, C29, and C30 |CITS: [3900276]|.
//
