UNIQUE-ID - 1-2-Beta-D-Glucans
TYPES - Beta-D-Glucans
COMMON-NAME - a 1,2-&beta;-D-glucan
SYNONYMS - 1,2-&beta;-D-glucan<sub>(n-1)</sub>
SYNONYMS - 1,2-&beta;-D-glucan<sub>(n+1)</sub>
SYNONYMS - 1,2-&beta;-D-glucan<sub>(n)</sub>
SYNONYMS - (1,2-&beta;-D-Glucosyl)<sub>(n)</sub>
SYNONYMS - (1,2-&beta;-D-Glucosyl)<sub>(n+1)</sub>
SYNONYMS - (1,2-&beta;-D-Glucosyl)<sub>(n-1)</sub>
COMMENT - &beta;-1,2-Glucan is a homopolymer composed of glucose residues connected by &beta;(1,2) linkages.
/
/This type of glucan has been reported from some Gram-negative bacteria, such as |FRAME: TAX-357|, |FRAME: TAX-379|, |FRAME: TAX-28105|, and |FRAME: TAX-234|, where it exists mainly in cyclic form |CITS: [Hisamatsu82][2117876][8078434][15880113][22583376]|. Cyclic &beta;-1,2-glucans have been reported to play a role in osmotic regulation |CITS: [3941890][2318812][10779706]|, but were also reported  to act as commensal factors in |FRAME: TAX-379| |CITS: [18052882]| and as infectious factors in |FRAME: TAX-235| |CITS: [11401996]|.
/
/Cyclic &beta;-1,2-glucans are usually found with a degree of polymerization (DPs) around 20, although a much longer glucan (DPs of around 40) has been reported from |FRAME: TAX-382| |CITS: [Koizumi84]|.
/
/Linear &beta;-1,2-glucans have been found in |FRAME: TAX-434| and |FRAME: TAX-338| |CITS: [Amemura85][3540204]|, and linear glucans with &beta;-1,6-glucosyl branches was reported in |FRAME: TAX-562| and |FRAME: TAX-317| (see |FRAME: CPD-16398|) |CITS: [3941890][7961404][10779706]|.
