UNIQUE-ID - sLex-Antigen
TYPES - Lewis-Antigen
COMMON-NAME - a sialyl-Lewis x epitope
SYNONYMS - an sLe<sup>x</sup> antigen
SYNONYMS - &alpha;NeuNAc-(2&rarr;3)-&beta;Gal-(1&rarr;4)-[&alpha;Fuc-(1&rarr;3]-&beta;GlcNAc-[protein]
SYNONYMS - a sialyl Lewis x antigen
SYNONYMS - a histo-blood group sialyl Lewis x antigen
COMMENT - The sialyl Lewis-X (SLeX) antigen is expressed on glycolipids and glycoproteins on the cell surfaces. 
/
/In adults, SLeX antigen is expressed principally on the surfaces of granulocytic cells. It plays an important role during early steps of inflammatory response as a ligand of the three known selectins - E-selectin (also known as endothelial leucocyte adhesion molecules, ELAM-1), P-Selectin, and L-selectin, resulting in the capture of leucocytes from the plasma and their attachment to blood endothelial cells |CITS: [2210723][7591266]|. In the case of L-selectin, the antigen needs to be sulfated first, forming |FRAME: 6-Sulfo-sLex-Antigen| |CITS: [9556613]|.
/
/The antigen is expressed in high frequency in tumor tissue where it plays a role in adhesion between tumor cells and blood endothelial cells during tumor metastases |CITS: [6386148][12029441][1699667][1701275]|.
/
/The SLeX antigen is synthesized from |FRAME: B-Gal-14-NacGlc-R| by the action of two enzymes, |FRAME: EC-2.4.3.6| and |FRAME: EC-2.4.1.152| |CITS: [1339443][25498912]|.
//
UNIQUE-ID - Cellodextrins
TYPES - 1-4-beta-D-Glucan
TYPES - Short-glucans
COMMON-NAME - a cellodextrin
COMMENT - Cellodextrins are &beta;-1,4 linked glucose polymers of varying length (two or more glucose monomers) resulting from the breakdown of cellulose. 
/
/During the degradation of glucose an endoglucanase first cuts the crystalline cellulose in an amorphous zone producing somewhat shorter glucans. Exoglucanases subsequently cleave these large insoluble chunks of cellulose into smaller, soluble cellodextrins which can be used by the cell.
/
/Common cellodextrins are cellotriose, cellotetraose, cellopentaose and cellohexaose.
