UNIQUE-ID - CPD-17410
TYPES - Fatty-Acids-Within-Glycerolipids
COMMON-NAME - a [glycerolipid]-&alpha;-parinarate
SYNONYMS - a [glycerolipid]-&alpha;-parinaric acid
SYNONYMS - a [glycerolipid]-<i>cis</i>-parinarate
COMMENT - |FRAME: CPD-17408 &alpha;-Parinarate| is a conjugated polyunsaturated fatty acid with 18 carbon atoms and 4 conjugated double bonds. It occurs naturally in the seeds of the makita tree (|FRAME: ORG-6271|), which is found in Fiji and other Pacific islands. Makita seeds contain about 46% of |FRAME: CPD-17408|, and 34% of another conjugated fatty acid, |FRAME: CPD-8231|. |FRAME: CPD-17408 &alpha;-Parinarate| is also found in the seed oil of |FRAME: TAX-63779|, where it makes about 30% of the seed oil.
/
/Because of its fluorescent properties, &alpha;-parinarate is commonly used as a molecular probe in the study of biomembranes.
/
/Like other fatty acids, |FRAME: CPD-17408| is rarely found in the cell in its free form. It is usually |FRAME: CPD-17410 "incorporated into glycerolipids"|.
