UNIQUE-ID - I-antigens
TYPES - blood-group-substances
COMMON-NAME - an I antigen
SYNONYMS - a &beta;-D-Gal-(1&rarr;4)-&beta;-D-GlcNAc-(1&rarr;3)-[&beta;-D-Gal-(11&rarr;4)-&beta;-D-GlcNAc-(1->6)]-&beta;-D-Gal-(1&rarr;4)-&beta;-D-GlcNAc-R
SYNONYMS - an I histo-blood group antigen
SYNONYMS - an <i>N</i>-acetyl-&beta;-D-galactosyl-(1,4)-[&beta;-D-galactosyl-(1,4)-<i>N</i>-acetyl-&beta;-D-glucosyl-(1,6)]-<i>N</i>-acetyl-&beta;-D-glucosaminyl-(1,3)-&beta;-D-galactosyl-(1,4)-<i>N</i>-acetyl-&beta;-D-glucosaminyl-R
SYNONYMS - an <i>N</i>-acetyl-&beta;-D-galactosyl-1,4-[&beta;-D-galactosyl-1,4-<i>N</i>-acetyl-&beta;-D-glucosyl-1,6]-<i>N</i>-acetyl-&beta;-D-glucosaminyl-1,3-&beta;-D-galactosyl-1,4-<i>N</i>-acetyl-D-glucosaminyl-[glycoprotein]
SYNONYMS - <i>N</i>-acetyl-&beta;-D-galactosyl-1,4-[&beta;-D-galactosyl-1,4-<i>N</i>-acetyl-&beta;-D-glucosyl-1,6]-<i>N</i>-acetyl-&beta;-D-glucosaminyl-1,3-&beta;-D-galactosyl-1,4-<i>N</i>-acetyl-D-glucosaminyl-[glycoprotein]
SYNONYMS - <i>N</i>-acetyl-&beta;-D-galactosyl-(1,4)-[&beta;-D-galactosyl-(1,4)-<i>N</i>-acetyl-&beta;-D-glucosyl-(1,6)]-<i>N</i>-acetyl-&beta;-D-glucosaminyl-(1,3)-&beta;-D-galactosyl-(1,4)-<i>N</i>-acetyl-&beta;-D-glucosaminyl-R
SYNONYMS - blood group I antigen
COMMENT - The |FRAME: i-Antigens "i antigen"| is found on membrane proteins in red blood cells and many other cell types as well as various body secretions of developing fetuses and newborn infants |CITS: [13767181][4971635]|, while the |FRAME: I-antigens "I antigen"| is found in all adults |CITS: [13292836]|. The i antigen undergoes gradual conversion to the I antigen in newborn infants, a process that completes in about 18 months.
/
/Both antigens are based entirely on Type 2 (|FRAME: BETA-D-GALACTOSYL-ETCETERA-GLUCOSAMINE "<i>N</i>-acetyllactosamine"|) chains. The basic i structure is an unbranched polylactosamine comprising at least two <i>N</i> - acetyllactosamine units connected by a &beta;(1&rarr;3) linkage |CITS: [823020][22356451]|.
/The crucial step in the transition from the i antigen to the I antigen is catalyzed by |FRAME: EC-2.4.1.150|, also known as the I-branching enzyme, which introduces the branching by adding a GlcNAc residue by a &beta;(1&rarr;6) linkage to the galactose residue to which other residues are already attached by a 1,3 linkage |CITS: [6490658]|.
/Note that the structure shown here is the core structure that defines I antigenicity. Most I antigens are further glycosylated.
/
/(Reviewed in |CITS: [Daniels13]|).
//
