UNIQUE-ID - sLea-Antigen
TYPES - Lewis-Antigen
COMMON-NAME - a sialyl-Lewis a epitope
SYNONYMS - an sLe<sup>a</sup> antigen
SYNONYMS - &alpha;NeuNAc-(2&rarr;3)-&beta;Gal-(1&rarr;3)-[&alpha;Fuc-(1&rarr;4]-&beta;GlcNAc-[protein]
SYNONYMS - a histo-blood group sialyl Lewis a epitope
COMMENT - The |FRAME: sLea-Antigen "sialyl-Lewis a epitope"| (SLe<sup>a</sup>) was discovered in 1979 with the use of a monoclonal antibody |CITS: [94699]|. While the antigen is believed to play an important role during embryogenesis |CITS: [6381330]|, in adults only low amounts of the antigen are present on normal epithelial cells |CITS: [6751528][6381289]|.
/When the selectin family of adhesion molecules was described, it was found that SLe<sup>a</sup>, along with the |FRAME: sLex-Antigen "sialyl-Lewis x antigen"|, is a ligand for E-selectin.
/
/Higher expression of the SLe<sup>a</sup> antigen in adults is strongly associated with cancer. It was found in high amounts on the surface of human pancreatic, colon and gastric cancer cell lines |CITS: [7142214][6188455]| and in human adenocarcinomas of the colon, stomach, pancreas and gall-bladder |CITS: [94699][6751528][2910493]|.
/
/The expression of the antigen has been linked to tumor progression. A gradual increase in SLe<sup>a</sup> was found in colon and rectum during neoplastic transformation and progression |CITS: [2863413]|, and its presence was restricted to tumorigenic and invasive human urothelial cell lines |CITS: [8900435]|. The antigen is responsible for adhesion of colon,
/pancreas, urinary bladder and gastric cancer cells to endothelium via its interaction with selectin E |CITS: [1716885][7687590][7678075][8900435][9578490]|.
/
/The expression level of the SLe<sup>a</sup> antigen is used as a prognostic factor for colorectal carcinoma, and is associated with high incidence of recurrence and the length of survival time |CITS: [8273774][7697593][9303355]|.
//
