UNIQUE-ID - H-antigen
TYPES - blood-group-substances
COMMON-NAME - an H antigen
SYNONYMS - &alpha;-L-fucosyl-(1,2)-&beta;-D-galactosyl-(1,4)-<i>N</i>-acetyl-&beta;-D-glucosamine-(1,3)-&beta;-D-galactosyl-[protein]
SYNONYMS - an &alpha;-L-fucosyl-(1->2)-D-galactosyl-R
SYNONYMS - a glycoprotein-&alpha;-L-fucosyl-(1,2)-D-galactose
SYNONYMS - a 2-O-(6-deoxy-&alpha;-L-galactopyranosyl)-&beta;-D-galactopyranosyl
SYNONYMS - an &alpha;-L-fucosyl-1,2-&beta;-D-galactoside
SYNONYMS - an &alpha;-L-fucosyl-1,2-&beta;-D-galactosyl-R
COMMENT - The |FRAME: H-antigen "H antigens"| are fucosylated oligosaccharides that decorate proteins on the surface of red blood cells in people with O blood type. In people with A or B blood types an additional monosaccharide is attached to one of the &beta;-D-galactosyl residues of the H antigen (|FRAME: CPD-12557| in |FRAME: A-antigen "A antigens"| and |FRAME: GALACTOSE| in |FRAME: B-antigen "B antigens"|).
/
/These fucosylated structures are found not only on blood cells but also on many other cell types (mainly epithehal), and it has been suggested that they should be called histo-blood group antigens.
/
/The majority of the A, B and H antigens are linked to the ends of long polylactosamine chains attached mainly to band 3 protein (encoded by SLC4A1), the anion exchange protein of the red blood cells. A minor fraction of the antigens is attached to a ceramide moiety, forming neutral glycosphingolipids.
/
/Several H antigens exist, differing in their core disaccharide |CITS: [2093726]|. The different types are:
/
/|FRAME: Type-1-H-Antigen "Type 1"|: &alpha;Fuc-(1,2)-&beta;Gal-(1&rarr;3)-&beta;GlcNac-(1&rarr;R)
/
/|FRAME: Type-2-H-Antigen "Type 2"|: &alpha;Fuc-(1,2)-&beta;Gal-(1&rarr;4)-&beta;GlcNac-(1&rarr;R)
/
/|FRAME: Type-3-H-Antigen "Type 3"|: &alpha;Fuc-(1,2)-&beta;Gal-(1&rarr;3)-&alpha;GalNac-(1&rarr;R)
/
/|FRAME: Type-4-H-Antigen "Type 4"|: &alpha;Fuc-(1,2)-&beta;Gal-(1&rarr;3)-&beta;GalNac-(1&rarr;R)
/
/|FRAME: Type-5-H-Antigen "Type 5"|: &alpha;Fuc-(1,2)-&beta;Gal-(1&rarr;3)-&beta;Gal-(1&rarr;R)
/
/|FRAME: Type-6-H-Antigen "Type 6"|: &alpha;Fuc-(1,2)-&beta;Gal-(1&rarr;4)-&beta;Glc-(1&rarr;R)
/
/Most of the H antigens found in the cell are either type 1 or type 2, followed by type 3 and 4. Type 1 is found in secretions and in the serum, while type 2 is found exclusively on the surface of red blood cells. Type 6 molecules have been described in exocrine secretions. It is not clear if type 5 H antigens exist, although the type 5 precursor has been characterized |CITS: [2093726]|.
//
UNIQUE-ID - Soluble-Heteroglycans-LI
TYPES - Soluble-Heteroglycans
COMMON-NAME - SHG<sub>LI</sub>
SYNONYMS - a soluble heteroglycan fraction LI (plants)
SYNONYMS - a soluble heteroglycan LI
COMMENT - This class of soluble heteroglycans has been identified in Arabidopsis plants and is involved in the cytosolic metabolism of maltose released from the chloroplast during starch degradation |CITS:[16098110][16640603]|. 
/
/In the "L" fraction obtained from Arabidopsis leaves, the SHG is composed of fucose, arabinose, rhamnose, galactose, glucose, xylose, and mannose with galactose and arabinose making up the bulk of the glycan |CITS:[16098110]|. Compared to subfraction LII, LI heteroglycans are less branched but have more complex linkages, such as various glucosyl, mannosyl and fucosyl linkages |CITS:[16098110]|.
//
