UNIQUE-ID - 6-Sulfo-sLex-Antigen
TYPES - Lewis-Antigen
COMMON-NAME - a 6-sulfo-sialyl Lewis x epitope
SYNONYMS - an sLe<sup>x</sup> antigen
SYNONYMS - &alpha;NeuNAc-(2&rarr;3)-&beta;Gal-(1&rarr;4)-[&alpha;Fuc-(1&rarr;3]-6-sulfo-&beta;GlcNAc-[protein]
SYNONYMS - a 6-sulfo sialyl Lewis x antigen
COMMENT - The sialyl Lewis-X (SLeX) antigen is expressed on glycolipids and glycoproteins on the cell surfaces. 
/
/In adults, SLeX antigen is expressed principally on the surfaces of granulocytic cells. It plays an important role during early steps of inflammatory response as a ligand of the three known selectins - E-selectin (also known as endothelial leucocyte adhesion molecules, ELAM-1), P-Selectin, and L-selectin, resulting in the capture of leucocytes from the plasma and their attachment to blood endothelial cells |CITS: [2210723][7591266]|.
/
/The antigen is expressed in high frequency in tumor tissue where it plays a role in adhesion between tumor cells and blood endothelial cells during tumor metastases |CITS: [6386148][12029441][1699667][1701275]|.
/
/The SLeX antigen is synthesized from |FRAME: B-Gal-14-NacGlc-R| by the action of two enzymes, |FRAME: EC-2.4.3.6| and |FRAME: EC-2.4.1.152| |CITS: [1339443]|.
//
