UNIQUE-ID - Callose
TYPES - 1-3-beta-D-Glucans
TYPES - 1-6-beta-D-Glucan
COMMON-NAME - callose
COMMENT - Cell walls of higher plants contain callose, which is a linear homopolysaccharide made up |FRAME: 1-3-beta-D-Glucans| with &beta;-1,6 branches. Callose plays an important role in many processes associated with plant development and in response to environmental stimuli in the form of abiotic and biotic stresses. Callose is also a transitory component of cell plate involved in the formation of new walls during cell division. It is a structural component of plasmodesmatal canals, and is also found in developing cell walls of fibre cells and cotton seed hairs |CITS: [19410266]|.
/
/The main enzyme in callose biosynthesis is callose synthase. The molecular mechanism underlying callose biosynthesis is still poorly understood. Molecular studies have revealed a set of genes in Arabidopsis genome that catalyze and degrade callose |CITS: [19286936]|. 12 glucan synthase like (GSL) genes appear to be involved in male gametogenesis in Arabidopsis |CITS: [18315544]|. Two genes, GSL1 and GSL5, are also known to play a role in pollen development and fertility |CITS: [16021399]|.
/
/Callose is degraded by &beta;-1,3-glucanases |CITS: [11785931]|. 
/
/See |CITS: [19816126]| for a review.
//
