UNIQUE-ID - Mannosyl5-N-Glycans
TYPES - N-Glycans
COMMON-NAME - Man<sub>5</sub>(GlcNAc)<sub>2</sub>-[protein] (isomer 5A<sub>1,2</sub>)
SYNONYMS - an [&alpha;-D-Man-(1&rarr;3)-{&alpha;-D-Man-(1&rarr;3)-[&alpha;-D-Man-(1&rarr;6)]-&alpha;-D-Man-(1&rarr;6)}-&beta;-D-Man-(1&rarr;4)-&beta;-D-GlcNAc-(1&rarr;4)-&beta;-D-GlcNAc]-<i>N</i>-Asn-[protein]
SYNONYMS - an &alpha;-D-Man-(1&rarr;3)-[&alpha;-D-Man-(1&rarr;3)-[&alpha;-D-Man-(1&rarr;6)]-&alpha;-D-Man-(1&rarr;6)]-&beta;-D-Man-(1&rarr;4)-&beta;-D-GlcNAc-(1&rarr;4)-&beta;-D-GlcNAc-1-N-Asn-[protein]
SYNONYMS - a [(mannosyl)<sub>5</sub>(<i>N</i>-acetylglucosaminyl)<sub>2</sub>]-L-asparginyl-[protein] (isomer 5A<sub>1,2</sub>)
SYNONYMS - M<sub>5</sub> <i>N</i>-glycan
COMMENT - This is one of four possible isomers of Man<sub>5</sub>GlcNAc<sub>2</sub> chains. It is the turning point between the processing phase of high-mannose <i>N</i>-glycans and the synthesis phase of complex and hybrid <i>N</i>-glycans. It is the substrate for the first <i>N</i>-acetylglucosaminyltransferase that is involved in the synthesis of the latter, |FRAME: EC-2.4.1.101|.
/
/The nomenclature used to identify high mannose glycans has not been standardized. Several earlier systems were insufficient to describe all possible isomers |CITS: [7954510][17719235][17685584]|. The nomenclature used here is that proposed by Prien et al |CITS: [19181540]|, which can represent all processing isomers.
/According to this nomenclature, the other three Man<sub>5</sub>GlcNAc<sub>2</sub> isomers are named isomer 5A<sub>2,3</sub>, isomer 5A<sub>1,3</sub>,  and isomer 5A<sub>2</sub>B<sub>2</sub>.
/
/According to the nomenclature used for hybrid and complex <i>N</i>-glycans, this compound is known simply as M<sub>5</sub> |CITS: [24178944]|.
//
UNIQUE-ID - TAX-86661
TYPES - TAX-1386
COMMON-NAME - Bacillus cereus group
//
UNIQUE-ID - MDO-D-Glucoses
TYPES - Osmoregulated-Periplasmic-Glucans
COMMON-NAME - an osmoregulated periplasmic glucan
SYNONYMS - an MDO-&beta;-D-glucan
SYNONYMS - an OPG-&beta;-D-glucan
COMMENT - Osmoregulated periplasmic glucans (OPGs), formerly known as membrane derived oligosaccharides (MDOs), represent a class of periplasmic oligosaccharides occuring in Gram-negative bacteria and implicated in osmoregulation.
/
/Cyclic, branched, and open-chain variants have been found, usually containing in the order of a dozen D-glucose units.
/The MDO of |FRAME: TAX-562| constitute a closely related family of compounds containing about 8-10 glucose units in a highly branched structure linked by &beta;-1&rarr;2 and &beta;1&rarr;6 bonds.
/
/The glucose residues are substituted with various amounts of <i>sn</i>-1-phosphoglycerol and smaller amounts of phosphoethanolamine residues in phosphodiester linkage on the 6 position of certain of the glucose residues. Some species of membrane-derived oligosaccharide also contain succinate in O-ester linkage |CITS: [6272307]|.
//
UNIQUE-ID - kappa-Carrageenan
TYPES - Carrageenoses
COMMON-NAME - &kappa;-carrageenose
SYNONYMS - &kappa;-carrageenan
COMMENT - |FRAME: Carrageenans Carrageenans| and |FRAME: Carrageenoses carrageenoses| are sulfated polysaccharides that are extracted from sea weeds belonging to the |FRAME: TAX-2763| (red algae), mainly from |FRAME: TAX-2769|, and species from the |FRAME: TAX-31444| and |FRAME: TAX-33664| genera. They are laid out in the cell wall at a high density and can constitute up to 50% of the algae dry mass.
/
/The basic units of |FRAME: Carrageenans carrageenans| are repeats of alternating &alpha;-1,3 linked D-galactose and &beta;-1,4-linked D-galactose units, which are often substituted by sulfate. Carrageenans are classified according to the
/number and the position of sulfated ester |CITS: [1367970]|. 
/
/In |FRAME: Carrageenoses carrageenoses| the &alpha;-1,3-linked galactose units are modified by having a 3,6-anhydro bridge. These bridges, which form a double helix during aggregation, are responsible for the gelation that is typical to these compounds. Despite this distinction, carrageenoses are often referred to as carrageenans.
/
/The three most industrially exploited carrageenans, namely, |FRAME: kappa-Carrageenan|, |FRAME: iota-Carrageenan| and |FRAME: Lambda-Carrageenan|, are distinguished by the presence of one, two or three ester-sulfate groups per repeating disaccharide unit respectively.
/
/|FRAME: kappa-Carrageenan| is sulfated only at position 4 of the &beta;-1,4 linked D-galactose units.
//
UNIQUE-ID - CPD-17397
TYPES - Lipid-hydroxy-fatty-acids
COMMON-NAME - a [glycerolipid]-densipolate
SYNONYMS - a [glycerolipid]-densipolic acid
