UNIQUE-ID - O-N-acetylgalactosamine-Glycans
TYPES - O-Glycans
COMMON-NAME - an <i>O</i>-(<i>N</i>-acetylgalactosamine) glycan
COMMENT - <i>O</i>-Linked glycans are polysaccharide or oligosaccharide that are linked to a protein via the oxygen atom in the side chain of an |FRAME: SER| or |FRAME: THR| residue. 
/Most commonly O-glycosylation begins with the attachment of |FRAME: CPD-3604| to the free hydroxyl group of the amino acid, although O-linkages to fucose, glucose, mannose, xylose and other sugars are known.
/
/Mucin-type O-glycosylation, consisting of glycans attached via O-linked |FRAME: CPD-3604|, is one of the most abundant forms of protein glycosylation in animals. Eight core-type structures of mucin-type <i>O</i>-glycans have been proposed.
/
/In the structure below, R1 is hydrogen when the modified amino acid is |FRAME: SER| and carbon when the amino acid is |FRAME: THR|. 
/
/In eukaryotes, <i>O</i>-linked glycans are assembled in the Golgi apparatus one sugar at a time, while attached to the core protein. 
/
/Examples for <i>O</i>-linked glycoproteins include glycophorin, |FRAME: Mucin mucin|, notch, thrombospondin, |FRAME: Factor-VII "factor VII"| and |FRAME: Factor-IX "factor IX"|.
//
