UNIQUE-ID - Anteiso-fatty-acids
TYPES - Methyl-Branched-Fatty-Acids
COMMON-NAME - an <i>antiso</i>-fatty acid
COMMENT - <i>Anteiso</i>-fatty acids are a class of branched-chain fatty acids (BCFA) that are characterized by a methyl-substituent located on the antepenultimate carbon of the carboxyalkyl chain.
/
/<i>Anteiso</i>-fatty acids are the most prominent fatty acids of cell membranes of some bacteria, especially of the genus <i>Bacillus</i>. The most relevant anteiso-fatty acids in food and bacteria are |FRAME: CPD-9917| and |FRAME: CPD-23509| |CITS: [28129363]|.
/
/Unlike classic fatty acids and |FRAME: Iso-fatty-acids "<i>iso</i>-fatty acids"|, <i>anteiso</i>-fatty acids are chiral molecules due to the stereogenic center at the carbon of the branching point. A distinct pre-dominance of (<i>S</i>)-<i>anteiso</i>-fatty acids, or even (<i>S</i>)-enantiopurity has been described in bacteria |CITS: [1886522][20117788]|, and also in fish |CITS: [13373794][17508720][20221853]|, dairy products |CITS: [13373794][13412644][13827622][20221853]|, mutton fat |CITS: [13018208]|, and Brussel sprouts |CITS: [26390192]|.
//
