//
UNIQUE-ID - Starch
TYPES - Alpha-6-branched-alpha-14-glucans
COMMON-NAME - starch
COMMENT - Starch is a glucose-based polysaccharide produced by plants, green algae, and cyanobacteria. Starch combines two polymeric carbohydrates (polysaccharides) called |FRAME: Alpha-Amyloses "&alpha;-amylose"| and |FRAME: CPD-7043|. |FRAME: Alpha-Amyloses "&alpha;-Amylose"| contains up to several thousand &alpha;-glucosyl units linked almost exclusively in linear &alpha;(1->4) linkages, with very few branches of &alpha;(1->6) linkages. In |FRAME: CPD-7043|, on the other hand, branching is common, and occurs approximately every 24-30 glucose monomer units. Amylopectin is one of (if not the) largest biological polymer known and contains from 10<sup>5</sup>&ndash;10<sup>6</sup> glucose residues |CITS: [9730163]|. Unlike |FRAME: Glycogens glycogen| molecules, which is limited to ~55,000 glucose units, the starch branched structure leads to clusters of chains that allow for indefinite growth of the polysaccharide. |FRAME: Alpha-Amyloses "&alpha;-Amylose"| accounts for 30% of starch, while |FRAME: CPD-7043| accounts for the other 70%.
/
/The dense packing of branches at the root of the clusters generates tightly packed glucan chains that are close enough to align and form parallel double helical structures. The helices within a single cluster and neighbouring clusters align and form sections of crystalline structures separated by sections of amorphous material (containing the branches) thereby generating the semi-crystalline nature of amylopectin and of the ensuing starch granule. The crystallized chains become insoluble and typically collapse into a macrogranular solid that is osmotically inert |CITS: [9730163]|. The enzymes of starch synthesis and mobilization are unable to interact directly with the solid structure, with the exception of |FRAME: EC-2.4.1.242 "granule-bound starch synthase"| |CITS: [14502990]|.
/
/The solid semi-crystalline starch and hydrosoluble |FRAME: Glycogens glycogen| define two distinct physical states of the same type of storage polysaccharide. Glycogen is by far the most widespread form of storage, as it is found in Archaea, Bacteria, and Eukaryotes. The appearance of semi-crystalline storage polysaccharides appears linked to the requirement of unicellular diazotrophic cyanobacteria to fuel nitrogenase and protect it from oxygen through respiration of large amounts of stored carbon |CITS: [21220783]|.
//
UNIQUE-ID - Man6-GlcNAc2-protein-A12B2
TYPES - N-Glycans
COMMON-NAME - Man<sub>6</sub>(GlcNAc)<sub>2</sub>-[protein] (isomer 6A<sub>1,2</sub>B<sub>2</sub>)
SYNONYMS - an &alpha;-D-Man-(1&rarr;2)-&alpha;-D-Man-(1&rarr;3)-[&alpha;-D-Man-(1&rarr;2)-&alpha;-D-Man-(1&rarr;3)-[&alpha;-D-Man-(1&rarr;6)]-&alpha;-D-Man-(1&rarr;6)]-&beta;-D-Man-(1&rarr;4)-&beta;-D-GlcNAc-(1&rarr;4)-&beta;-D-GlcNAc-1-L-asparaginyl-[protein]
SYNONYMS - a [(mannosyl)<sub>6</sub>(<i>N</i>-acetylglucosaminyl)<sub>2</sub>]-L-asparaginyl-[protein] (isomer 6A<sub>1,2</sub>B<sub>2</sub>)
COMMENT - This is one of three isomers of Man<sub>6</sub>GlcNAc<sub>2</sub> chains that are found in <i>N</i> glycans.
/
/The nomenclature used to identify high mannose glycans has not been standardized. Several earlier systems were insufficient to describe all possible isomers |CITS: [7954510][17719235][17685584]|. The nomenclature used here is that proposed by Prien et al |CITS: [19181540]|, which can represent all processing isomers.
/
/According to this nomenclature, the other two Man<sub>6</sub>GlcNAc<sub>2</sub> isomers are named |FRAME: Man6GlcNAc2-protein-A123 "isomer 6A<sub>1,2,3</sub>"| and |FRAME: Man6GlcNAc2-protein-A12B1 "isomer 6A<sub>2,3</sub>B<sub>1</sub>"|.
//
