UNIQUE-ID - GlgE-Glycogen
TYPES - Alpha-6-branched-alpha-14-glucans
COMMON-NAME - a GlgE-glycogen
SYNONYMS - a mycobacterial &alpha;-D-glucan
COMMENT - |FRAME: TAX-1773| and other pathogenic mycobacterial species produce a capsular layer outside the bacterial wall and plasma membrane that is thought to be involved in immune evasion and virulence |CITS: [13630872][13711244]|. The capsular layer is composed of &alpha;-glucan (80–90%) and arabinomannan (10–20%) polysaccharides, proteins of the ESX-1 secretion system, and small amounts of lipid |CITS: [20221442]|. The glucan structure resembles |FRAME: Glycogens glycogen|, consisting of relatively short chains of &alpha; (1->4)-linked glucose molecules, which are connected to each other in a branching pattern by &alpha; (1->6) bonds |CITS: [8297342][10656114][21341078]|. However, the polymer differs from classical glycogen in seceral aspects. The chains are shorter, consisting of 7 sugars vs 11. In addition, the branching pattern is different - while there are more &alpha;-1,6 branches than in glycogen (14% vs 9%), less branches are coming off each branch (1.2-1.6 vs 1.8-1.9 in glycogen) |CITS: [27221142]|.
//
