UNIQUE-ID - CPD-16400
TYPES - CPD-16398
COMMON-NAME - an osmoregulated periplasmic glucan with phosphoglycerol substituent
SYNONYMS - an MDO-6-(glycerophospho)-D-glucose
SYNONYMS - an OPG-6-(<i>sn</i>-1-phosphoglycero)-&beta;-D-glucan
SYNONYMS - an <i>E. coli</i> MDO-D-glucose with phosphoglycerol substituent
COMMENT - Osmoregulated periplasmic glucans (OPGs), formerly known as membrane derived oligosaccharides (MDOs), represent a class of periplasmic oligosaccharides occuring in Gram-negative bacteria and implicated in osmoregulation.
/
/Cyclic, branched, and open-chain variants have been found, usually containing in the order of a dozen D-glucose units.
/The MDO of |FRAME: TAX-562| constitute a closely related family of compounds containing about 8-10 glucose units in a highly branched structure linked by &beta;-1&rarr;2 and &beta;1&rarr;6 bonds.
/
/The glucose residues are substituted with various amounts of <i>sn</i>-1-phosphoglycerol and smaller amounts of phosphoethanolamine residues in phosphodiester linkage on the 6 position of certain of the glucose residues. Some species of membrane-derived oligosaccharide also contain succinate in O-ester linkage |CITS: [6272307]|.
//
