UNIQUE-ID - GALACTOSYL-BETA-GALACTOSAMINYL-R
TYPES - Mucin-type-glycans
SYNONYMS - &beta;-D-galactosyl-1,3-(<i>N</i>-acetyl-D-glucosaminyl-1,6)-<i>N</i>-acetyl-D-galactosaminyl-R
SYNONYMS - &beta;-D-galactosyl-1,3-(<i>N</i>-acetyl-&beta;-D-glucosaminyl-1,6)-<i>N</i>-acetyl-D-galactosaminyl-R
SYNONYMS - &beta;-D-galactosyl-1,3-(<i>N</i>-acetyl-&beta;-D-glucosaminyl-1,6)-<i>N</i>-acetyl-D-galactosaminyl-[glycoprotein]
COMMENT - <i>O</i>-Linked glycans are polysaccharide or oligosaccharide that are linked to a protein via the oxygen atom in the side chain of a |FRAME: SER| or |FRAME: THR| residue.
/Most commonly <i>O</i>-glycosylation begins with the attachment of |FRAME: CPD-3604| to the free hydroxyl group of the amino acid, although O-linkages to fucose, glucose, mannose, xylose and other sugars are known. In eukaryotes, <i>O</i>-linked glycans are assembled in the Golgi apparatus one sugar at a time, while attached to the core protein.
/
/Mucin-type <i>O</i>-glycosylation, consisting of glycans attached via O-linked |FRAME: CPD-3604|, is one of the most abundant forms of protein glycosylation in animals.
//
