SYNONYMS - <i>N</i>-acetyl-&beta;-D-glucosaminyl-1,3-<i>N</i>-acetyl-D-galactosaminyl-R
SYNONYMS - <i>N</i>-acetyl-&beta;-D-glucosaminyl-1,3-<i>N</i>-acetyl-&alpha;-D-galactosaminyl-R
SYNONYMS - core 3
COMMENT - <i>O</i>-Linked glycans are polysaccharide or oligosaccharide that are linked to a protein via the oxygen atom in the side chain of a |FRAME: SER| or |FRAME: THR| residue.
/Most commonly <i>O</i>-glycosylation begins with the attachment of |FRAME: CPD-3604| to the free hydroxyl group of the amino acid, although O-linkages to fucose, glucose, mannose, xylose and other sugars are known. In eukaryotes, <i>O</i>-linked glycans are assembled in the Golgi apparatus one sugar at a time, while attached to the core protein.
/
/Mucin-type <i>O</i>-glycosylation, consisting of glycans attached via O-linked |FRAME: CPD-3604|, is one of the most abundant forms of protein glycosylation in animals. Eight core-type structures of mucin-type <i>O</i>-glycans have been proposed, including |FRAME: Core1 "core 1"|, |FRAME: Core2 "core 2"|, |FRAME: GLUCOSAMINYL-13-N-ETCETERA-GALACTOSAMINY "core 3"|, |FRAME: GLUCOSAMINYL-16-ETCETERA-GALACTOSAMINYL- "core 4"|, |FRAME: Core5 "core 5"|, |FRAME: Core6 "core 6"|, |FRAME: Core7 "core 7"| and |FRAME: Core8 "core 8"| |CITS: [16413314]|.
/
/In the structure below, which describes core 3, R=H when the modified amino acid is |FRAME: SER| and R=CH<sub>3</sub> when the amino acid is |FRAME: THR|.
